{"title_page": "Tornadoes of 2020", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Notable tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in 2020}}\n{{Infobox tornado year\n|name          = Tornadoes of 2020\n|image         = 2020 United States tornado count.png\n|caption       = A chart of the 2020 United States tornado count estimated from the number of preliminary reports\n|timespan      = January 3 \u2013 ongoing\n|max_EF        = EF4\n|max_location  = 4 different locations\n|max_date      = 3 different days\n|tornadoes_usa = 399\n|total_damages_usa = >$4.4&nbsp;billion\n|total_fatalities_world = 75\n|total_fatalities_usa = 75\n|year = 2020\n}}\n\nThis page documents notable [[tornado]]es and [[tornado outbreak]]s worldwide in '''2020'''. Strong and destructive tornadoes form most frequently in the [[United States]], [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[East India|Eastern India]], but can occur almost anywhere under the right conditions. Tornadoes also develop occasionally in southern [[Canada]] during the [[Northern Hemisphere]]'s summer and somewhat regularly at other times of the year across [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. Tornadic events are often accompanied by other forms of [[severe weather]], including strong [[thunderstorm]]s, strong [[winds]], and [[hail]].\n\nThere have been 456 preliminary filtered reports of tornadoes in the United States in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Severe Weather Report Summary 2020 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/online/monthly/2020_annual_summary.html |publisher=Storm Prediction Center |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> of which at least 399 have been confirmed. Worldwide, 75 tornado-related deaths have been confirmed, all in the United States.\n\n==Events==\n{{Tornadoes of 2020/Deadly}}\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\n\n===United States yearly total===\n<!-- This section is transcluded to other articles; modify with caution. -->\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 398\n|FU = 8\n|F0 = 121\n|F1 = 192\n|F2 = 56\n|F3 = 16\n|F4 = 4\n|F5 = 0\n| Enhanced=yes\n}}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==January==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#January}}\nThere were 90 tornadoes reported in the United States in January, of which 88 were confirmed. Overall, January was an active month, with over twice the national average of 35 tornadoes.\n\n===January 3 (South Africa)===\nOn January 3, severe thunderstorms developed over the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]]. One thunderstorm developed into a supercell which produced an EF3 tornado that caused significant damage to a farm, destroyed the houses of seven families, and destroyed about {{convert|200|hectare|acre|sigfig=1}} of pine forest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Panbult tornado (Mpumalanga) on the 3rd of January 2020. |url=https://twitter.com/SAWeatherServic/status/1214087467692941312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1214087467692941312&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.news24.com%2FSouthAfrica%2FNews%2Fwatch-tornado-lasting-about-40-minutes-destroyed-farm-and-7-houses-in-mpumalanga-saws-confirms-20200106 |website=Twitter |publisher=South African Weather Service |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===January 10\u201311===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of January 10\u201311, 2020}}\n{{stack begin}}{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 25|EF1= 41|EF2= 13|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=0}}{{stack end}}\n[[File:Carollton EF2 damage1.jpg|thumb||float|left|High-end EF2 damage to a house near Carrollton, Alabama.]]\nOn January 10, the Storm Prediction Center issues a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the Southern United States, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. A squall line of severe thunderstorms with numerous embedded circulations and semi-discrete supercell structures moved from [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]] to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], producing numerous tornadoes. A high-end EF2 tornado near [[Carrollton, Alabama]] destroyed multiple homes and mobile homes, and resulted in three fatalities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three people killed in Pickens Co. tornado |url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/11/three-people-killed-pickens-co-tornado/ |publisher=WBRC |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Three people were fatally injured when a long-tracked EF2 tornado destroyed two mobile homes south of [[Haughton, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enfinger |first1=Emily |title=87-year-old dies from injuries from Haughton tornado |url=https://eu.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/local/2020/01/15/third-death-confimred-haughton-tornado/4480014002/ |publisher=Shreveport Times |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> and an EF1 tornado killed one person near [[Nacogdoches, Texas]] when a large tree fell onto a mobile home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brackett |first1=Ron |last2=Wesner Childs |first2=Jan |title=Tornadoes, Severe Storms Kill 8; More Than 300,000 Lose Power |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-severe-storms-tornadoes-impact-texas-louisiana-tennessee-arkansas-mississippi |website=weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Houston, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey for January 10 Burleson County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHGX&e=202001112109|date=January 11, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado struck [[Rome, Mississippi]], causing significant damage and destroying the local post office. An EF2 tornado also struck [[Union Grove, Alabama]], significantly damaging a school building in the community. Another school also sustained major damage near [[Kershaw, South Carolina]], as a result of another EF2 tornado. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 79 tornadoes, and resulted in 7 fatalities. Total damage from the event reached $1.1&nbsp;billion according to the [[National Centers for Environmental Information]].<ref name=\"NCEI_billion\">{{cite web|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters: Events|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/billions/events}}</ref>\n\n==February==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#February}}\nThere were 51 tornadoes reported in the United States in February, of which 42 were confirmed. February was also an active month, besting the national average of 29 tornadoes.\n\n===February 5\u20137===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 21|EF2= 6|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=1}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of February 5\u20137, 2020}}\n[[File:KannapolisNCEF2-2020.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF2 damage to a house near Kannapolis, North Carolina.]]\nBeginning on February 5, a moderate tornado outbreak affected the Deep South and Eastern United States. On the first day of the outbreak, an EF2 tornado caused significant tree and outbuilding damage near [[Pickens, Mississippi]], and injured four people. A long-tracked EF2 tornado touched down near [[Bay Springs, Mississippi]] and passed though the town of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise]], downing numerous trees and power poles and toppling a metal fire tower. This tornado tore large sections of roofing off of multiple homes in rural areas as well. On February 6, one person was killed in [[Marengo County, Alabama]] when an EF1 tornado destroyed a mobile home near [[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/06/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202002070055|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Jackson, Mississippi|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/05/2020 \u2013 02/06/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #1|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSJAN&e=202002070252|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado also touched down near [[Kannapolis, North Carolina]], to the north of [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]]. No injuries were reported, though multiple homes were damaged, including one that lost its roof and some exterior walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/06/tornado-touches-down-kannapolis/|title=Tornado touches down in Kannapolis|website=WBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/confirmed-tornado-damages-homes-in-kannapolis/275-3a51f749-53cd-490f-bf2c-3fd08c8c793c|title=Confirmed tornado damages homes in the Kannapolis area|website=WCNC|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Tornado rips roof off home in Kannapolis, North Carolina|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gE8N-dBHI7k|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Another EF2 downed metal truss transmission towers near [[Kings Mountain, North Carolina|Kings Mountain]], and an EF1 tornado caused damage in the southern suburbs of Charlotte.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://salisburypost.com/2020/02/08/three-rescued-from-flood-waters-weather-service-confirms-tornado-in-rowan-county/|title=As flooding, damage lingers, 3 rescued from Third Creek, weather service confirms tornadoes in Rowan|last=Walker|first=Shavonne|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=WBTV>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/07/nws-confirms-ef-tornado-near-pineville/|title=NWS confirms EF-1 tornado near Pineville|last=Myers|first=Jason|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/tornado-stanly-albemarle-damage-storm/275-227d0b28-9341-4b91-a7a0-057602e4a803|title=EF-1 tornado confirmed near Albemarle|work=[[WCNC-TV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> A high-end EF1 tornado moved directly through [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] as well, causing considerable damage to homes and businesses.<ref name=WBTV/> On February 7, five tornadoes touched down in Maryland, including an EF1 that struck [[Westminster, Maryland|Westminster]] and [[Manchester, Maryland|Manchester]], causing moderate damage. An EF0 tornado also caused minor damage in [[Leesburg, Virginia]]. Along with the tornadic storms, heavy rainfall resulted in widespread flooding also occurred throughout the southern states. Total economic losses from the event exceeded $925&nbsp;million. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 37 tornadoes, and resulted in one fatality.<ref>{{cite report|publisher=Aon|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Global Catastrophe Recap: February 2020|url=http://thoughtleadership.aonbenfield.com/Documents/20200309_analytics-if-february-global-recap.pdf|page=4|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==March==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#March}}\nThere were 106 tornadoes reported in the United States in March, of which 78 were confirmed. Although March was slightly below average in number of tornadoes, the series of severe weather outbreaks and tornadoes throughout March inflicted widespread damage across the country. Combined economic losses reached approximately $2.4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matt Sheehan|publisher=Reinsurance News|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Separate billion-dollar events mark active month for US tornadoes: Aon|url=https://www.reinsurancene.ws/separate-billion-dollar-events-mark-active-month-for-us-tornadoes-aon/}}</ref>\n\n===March 2\u20133===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2020}}\n[[File:CookevilleTNEF4rubbleanddamage.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF4 damage in a residential area near Cookeville, Tennessee.]]\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 3|EF2= 4|EF3= 1|EF4= 1|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA small but devastating tornado outbreak affected parts of the Southern United States on the evening of March 2 into the early morning hours of March 3, with the most severe damage and all fatalities occurring in Tennessee. [[Nashville, Tennessee]] was directly struck by a high-end EF3 tornado just after 12:30&nbsp;a.m. CDT on March 3. Major structural damage and six fatalities occurred as the tornado passed just north of downtown Nashville and through [[Mount Juliet, Tennessee|Mount Juliet]] to the east. Additional tornadoes were reported in [[Missouri]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Kentucky]]. An EF2 tornado killed one person and caused significant damage to homes, mobile homes, and outbuildings near [[Camden, Tennessee]] as well. The majority of the deaths occurred in Putnam County, where a violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Baxter, Tennessee|Baxter]] shortly before 2:00&nbsp;a.m. and moved into western [[Cookeville, Tennessee|Cookeville]]. Many homes and other buildings were completely leveled or swept away in residential areas of Cookeville, and 19 people were killed in town.<ref name=\"OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=March 2\u20133, 2020 Tornadoes and Severe Weather|url=https://www.weather.gov/ohx/20200303|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=21 killed, 221 hospitalized after tornadoes rip through Nashville, surrounding areas|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/six-killed-at-least-20-hurt-after-tornadoes-rip-through-nashville-surrounding-areas|publisher=ABC Action News|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In addition, two EF2 tornadoes also downed numerous trees in forested areas near [[Alvaton, Kentucky]] and [[Clarkrange, Tennessee]] as well. A lone, long-tracked [[supercell]] thunderstorm was responsible for all nine of the tornadoes in Tennessee as it moved from near [[Dyersburg, Tennessee|Dyersburg]] in West Tennessee to near [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] in East Tennessee. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 14 tornadoes, and resulted in 26 fatalities.<ref name=\"OHX\"/>\n\n===March 18\u201319===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 11|EF2= 5|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nOn March 18, an intense [[supercell thunderstorm]] spawned numerous weak tornadoes as it tracked through [[Jack County, Texas|Jack]], [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]], [[Wise County, Texas|Wise]], and [[Young County, Texas|Young counties]] in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/18/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSFWD&e=202003201858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> With severe storms continuing into the early morning hours of March 19, two EF2 tornadoes caused considerable damage to trees, vehicles, farming equipment, and outbuildings near [[Trent, Texas]].<ref name=\"SJT0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in San Angelo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #1|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSSJT&e=202003201627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The thunderstorm responsible for those tornadoes went on to produce another EF2 tornado that damaged a large building and over 100 cars at a correctional facility northeast of [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]]. Near [[Sweetwater, Texas|Sweetwater]], an EF2 tornado damaged or destroyed several wind turbines.<ref name=\"SJT0319\"/> Later that day, a large portion of the southern [[Great Plains]] was in line for severe storms, along with parts of the [[Ohio Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Darrow|title=Mar 19, 2020 0100 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200319_0100.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the afternoon, a squall line with several embedded supercells formed from [[Oklahoma]] to [[Indiana]], producing tornadoes in [[Oklahoma]], [[Illinois]], and [[Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTSA&e=202003210250|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PAH0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003202132|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LZK0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornadoes Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003212158|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A large EF2 tornado touched down near [[Everton, Arkansas]] before moving through the southeastern part of town, causing significant damage to homes, a school, outbuildings, and trees.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> Three EF1 tornadoes also touched down in Arkansas, one of which tracked between [[Gassville, Arkansas|Gassville]] and [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]], inflicting considerable damage to some homes. Further north, two EF1 tornadoes caused damage in [[Sunfield, Illinois|Sunfield]] and [[Dahlgren, Illinois]].<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> One person was injured in Illinois,<ref name=\"PAH0319\"/> and another injury occurred in Arkansas. A total of 21 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/>\n\n===March 28\u201329===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 3|EF1= 11|EF2= 2|EF3= 1|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 3}}\nOn March 28, the SPC issued a moderate risk of severe weather for much of Illinois, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. An enhanced risk of severe weather was in place \nacross parts of Iowa, Missouri, Indiana, and Arkansas as well. Only weak tornadoes touched down in the moderate risk area, though a few strong tornadoes occurred elsewhere. A large EF3 tornado struck the city of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], while being streamed live on local news stations, producing major damage to homes, businesses, and a shopping mall. Vehicles were thrown and mangled, and the local airport sustained severe damage as well. A train was also derailed, and 22 injuries occurred in Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado flattens buildings in Jonesboro, Arkansas, as severe weather moves across the Midwest, Lower Mississippi River Valley |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/28/weather/tornadoes-severe-storms-forecast-saturday/index.html |website=CNN |publisher=CNN |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Damage Reported in Northeastern Arkansas as Tornado Strikes Jonesboro |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-03-28-severe-weather-tornado-impacts-plains-south-midwest |website=Weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20200328 reports\">{{cite web |title=Today's Storm Reports (20200328 1200 UTC \u2013 20200329 1159 UTC) (Print Version) |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200328_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=202003292239|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Zoellner |first1=Danielle |title=Tornado rips through Arkansas town, injuring six people |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/arkansas-tornado-jonesboro-weather-injured-a9432511.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same storm that produced this tornado also produced two EF1 tornadoes, one before and one after it moved over Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003292104|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\"/>\nInto the evening, numerous weak tornadoes touched down in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], and another in southwest [[Wisconsin]]. This included an EF1 tornado caused moderate damage to apartment buildings and trees in [[Oelwein, Iowa]].<ref name=\"20200328 reports\"/>\nA low-end EF2 tornado moved through the southern fringes of [[Henderson, Kentucky]], destroying numerous outbuildings and a barn, and damaging dozens of homes and trees.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Henderson County KY Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300139|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\nAnother EF2 struck the town of [[Newburgh, Indiana]], where five homes sustained partial to total roof removal, and one home had a few upper floor exterior walls ripped off. Numerous other homes in town sustained less severe damage, and two people were injured in Newburgh.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Newburgh Indiana Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300138|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the morning of March 29, the same storm system produced an EF0 tornado that mainly damaged trees near [[Sparta, Tennessee]]. Overall, this outbreak produced 20 tornadoes.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/29/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202003311858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 30\u201331===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 3|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 2}}\nOn the evening of March 30, isolated supercells developed across Texas and Oklahoma, producing two weak tornadoes. One of these was given an EFU rating, and the other, which was a [[landspout]] or non-mesocylonic tornado, was given an EF0 rating.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Amarillo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/30/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSAMA&e=202003312336|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \nOn March 31, multiple supercells and embedded mesocyclones formed along and just ahead of a convective line, producing several tornadoes across parts of the [[Southeastern United States]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\">{{cite web |title=SPC Storm reports for03/31/20 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200331_rpts.html |publisher=Storm Prediction |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nA high-end EF2 tornado caused significant damage just south of [[Eufaula, Alabama]], where multiple homes in a subdivision had their roofs torn off. A few of these homes sustained partial exterior wall loss.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuentes |first1=Carmen |title=Eufaula tornado runs through neighborhood |url=https://www.wtvy.com/content/news/Eufaula-tornado-runs-through-neighborhood-569268011.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=WTVY |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202004020401|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Multiple other weak tornadoes were confirmed in southeast [[Mississippi]], southern [[Alabama]], and northern [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004032145|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\"/> A landspout tornado was caught on video around 2:30&nbsp;p.m. PDT at the north edge of [[Richland, Washington]], causing no damage. A total of 15 tornadoes are confirmed.<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\"/>\n\n==April==\n{{see also|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\nThere have been 191 tornadoes confirmed in the United States in April.\n\n===April 7\u20139===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 20|EF1= 10|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA few weak tornadoes touched down across [[Ohio]] and [[Pennsylvania]] late on April 7 and into the early morning of April 8, causing tree and structure damage. Later on the night of April 8, a large EF2 cone tornado touched down near [[Weiner, Arkansas]], completely destroying a mobile home. The tornado then struck [[Harrisburg, Arkansas]] in [[Poinsett County, Arkansas|Poinsett County]].<ref>https://twitter.com/nwsmemphis/status/1248334194377232384?s=21</ref><ref>https://media.arkansasonline.com/img/photos/2020/04/09/storm1_t800.jpg?90232451fbcadccc64a17de7521d859a8f88077d</ref> In Harrisburg, one frail home was completely leveled by the tornado, and several homes nearby were also badly damaged or destroyed in residential areas of town.<ref>https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/apr/09/forecasters-tornado-touched-down-overnight-northwe/#.Xo9c00N8lmQ.twitter</ref> Extensive tree damage occurred and two people were injured in Harrisburg.<ref>https://twitter.com/kwoodallTV/status/1248076374084124673?s=19</ref> Numerous tornadoes, all of which weak and short-lived, occurred across [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and Ohio that night as well. One EF1 tornado caused considerable damage to a brick building in downtown [[Mooresville, Indiana]]. Another EF1 tornado damaged two mobile homes, a garage, and trees near [[Wilkesville, Ohio]] on April 9 before the outbreak came to an end. Numerous reports of damaging straight line winds were also received throughout the event. A total of 31 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n=== April 12\u201313 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 30|F1 = 72|F2 = 20|F3 = 13|F4 = 2|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{main|2020 Easter tornado outbreak}}\n[[File:Cantwell Mill, Mississippi, April 12, 2020, tornado damage.jpg|thumb||float|left|High-end EF4 damage to a large, well-anchored cabin northeast of Bassfield, Mississippi.]]\nFrom the late morning of April 12 through the early morning of April 13, a major tornado outbreak unfolded across the [[Southeastern United States]], with more than 100 tornadoes touching down in just over 36 hours. Over a 48 hour period from nighttime on April 11 to the evening of April 13, 137 tornadoes touched down from Texas to Maryland. This event was well forecasted, with the [[Storm Prediction Center]] issuing severe weather outlooks as early as five days before the outbreak. At 10:40 a.m. CDT on April 12, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] [[Tornado Watch]] was issued by the Storm Prediction Center across northeast [[Louisiana]], southeast [[Arkansas]], and central and northern [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0106.html|title=PDS Watch 106|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 11:44 a.m. CDT, a [[Tornado emergency|tornado emergency]] was issued for [[Monroe, Louisiana]] as an [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF3 tornado]] moved through the city limits causing significant damage to more than 200 homes, as well as the [[Monroe Regional Airport (Louisiana)|Monroe Regional Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliareporter.com/news_and_business/regional_news/article_4f3bcd2e-7ce3-11ea-8412-1b0152c3f85d.html|title=Magnolia Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado Emergency for Monroe Louisiana and Northeast Ouachita Parish |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=SVSSHV&e=202004121644 |website=Iowa Environmental Mesonet |publisher=National Weather Service Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SteveWAFB/status/1249799061898760192?s=20|title=Steve Caparotta of WAFB on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 3:30 p.m. CDT, two back-to-back supercells began to produce three intense long-tracked tornadoes, including two rated EF4, that would move across southern Mississippi, prompting the [[National Weather Service]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to issue multiple tornado emergencies for numerous towns including [[Prentiss, Mississippi|Prentiss]], [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]], [[Collins, Mississippi|Collins]], and [[Soso, Mississippi|Soso]]. At 4:40 p.m. CDT, a second [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS watch]] was issued affecting extreme southeast Mississippi and most of [[Alabama]], including the cities of [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], and [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0110.html|title=Storm Prediction Center \u2013 PDS Watch 110|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As the system progressed northeastward into the nighttime hours, another tornado emergency was issued, this time at 11:28 p.m. EDT for the towns of [[Ooltewah, Tennessee|Ooltewah]] and [[Collegedale, Tennessee|Collegedale]] as a deadly EF3 tornado struck the eastern suburbs of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], killing three and injuring 19.<ref>https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMRX&e=202004151915|title=NWS Morristown Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, the storms that formed the day before congealed into a strong [[squall line]] as they advanced into eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Carolinas]]. At 6:55 a.m. EDT, an embedded supercell within a [[Squall line|QLCS]] prompted yet another tornado emergency as [[Walterboro, South Carolina]] took a direct hit from a confirmed tornado.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSCharlestonSC/status/1249652455073370113?s=20|title=NWS Charleston SC on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/StuOstro/status/1250057470669721602</ref> Nine EF3 tornadoes occurred on day two of the outbreak, including seven in [[South Carolina]] that resulted in a combined eight deaths, most notably the 3/4-mile wide EF3 in [[Hampton County, South Carolina|Hampton County]] that took the lives of five people near the towns of [[Estill, South Carolina|Estill]] and Nixville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSCHS&e=202004152035|title=NWS Charleston Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nWith <!-- do not change this unless the fatality count has updated -->32<!-- as of April 20, only 32 fatalities have been confirmed to be tornado-related --> tornado-related fatalities, it was the deadliest outbreak since <!-- again, do not change to 2012 unless the TORNADO-RELATED fatality count exceeds 35 -->[[Tornado outbreak of April 27\u201330, 2014|April 27\u201330, 2014]].<ref>{{cite web |title=At Least 41 People Have Died After a Tornado Outbreak Ravaged the South |url=https://time.com/5820741/deadly-tornadoes-storms-south/ |website=TIME USA |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 19\u201320===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 1|F0 = 5|F1 = 10|F2 = 3|F3 = 0|F4 = 1|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\nFor the second straight Sunday and Monday, several tornadoes touched down across the Southern United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Today's Storm Reports (20200419 1200 UTC \u2013 20200420 1159 UTC)|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200419_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> On April 19, a large, violent EF4 tornado moved through Hurricane Creek, [[Sandy Hook, Mississippi|Sandy Hook]], Pine Burr, and areas north of [[Purvis, Mississippi]], killing one person and injuring another.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in New Orleans|title=NWS New Orleans Tornado Report|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=LSRLIX&e=202004201907|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSJacksonMS/status/1252400542443122691|title=The Hurricane Creek/Pine Burr/Purvis/Camp Shelby tornado has been rated an EF-4 with estimated maximum wind of 170 MPH, path length of 54.2 miles, and maximum path width of 1.25 miles. Additional details will follow later this evening.|last=Jackson MS|first=NWS|date=2020-04-20|website=@NWSJacksonMS|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Later that evening, an EF2 tornado caused severe damage to homes near [[Andalusia, Alabama]] injuring one person.<ref>{{cite web|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Mobile, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for April 19, 2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMOB&e=202004212319|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> That night, an EF1 tornado caused damage to multiple mobile homes and destroyed an RV camper near [[Robertsdale, Alabama]] injuring one person.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMOB&e=202004210100|title=IEM :: PNS from NWS MOB|last=akrherz@iastate.edu|first=daryl herzmann|website=mesonet.agron.iastate.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\nEarly on April 20, another EF2 tornado damaged several homes and a mobile home near [[Bridgeboro, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee FL|title=NWS Tallahassee FL Damage Survey|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004211628|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Later on, several more tornadoes were reported throughout the morning into the afternoon in Central Florida.<ref>{{cite web|title=Today's Storm Reports (20200420 1200 UTC \u2013 20200421 1159 UTC)|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200420_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> An EF0 tornado caused considerable damage in [[Homosassa, Florida|Homosassa]] and [[Homosassa Springs, Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tampa Bay Ruskin FL|title=NWS Tampa Bay Ruskin FL Damage Survey|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTBW&e=202004201854|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chronicleonline.com/news/local/nws-tornado-causes-damage-in-homosassa-power-out-for-more-than-1-000-customers/article_ca25601c-831a-11ea-9981-a3a03237cc85.html|title=NWS: Tornado causes damage in Homosassa; power out for more than 1,000 customers|last=Thompson|first=Jeff Bryan & Buster|website=Chronicle Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Another EF0 tornado was caught on video lifting a stationary construction trailer across [[Interstate 75 in Florida|Interstate 75]] in [[Wildwood, Florida]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PaulFox13/status/1252257783912824832|title=That'll stop traffic. Line of strong to severe thunderstorms across central #Florida produced this potential #tornado in Citrus county on I-75. #Skytower|last=DellegattoHigh voltage signFOX|first=Paul|date=2020-04-20|website=@PaulFox13|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsbreak.com/news/0OoG9ZmK/suspected-tornado-crosses-interstate-as-severe-weather-hits-central-florida|title=Suspected Tornado Crosses Interstate as Severe Weather Hits Central Florida|website=News Break|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> 19 tornadoes have been confirmed so far and damage surveys are ongoing.\n\n===April 22\u201323===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 0|F1 = 0|F2 = 2|F3 = 0|F4 = 0|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of April 22\u201323, 2020}} \nNumerous tornadoes struck southern [[Oklahoma]] during the afternoon of April 22. A tornado of at least EF2 strength killed at least two people in [[Madill, Oklahoma|Madill]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Two people killed after tornado hits Marshall County, officials say |url=https://www.koco.com/article/person-killed-after-tornado-hits-marshall-county-officials-say/32243168 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |agency=KOCO News 5 |date=22 April 2020}}</ref> A large tornado was captured on video by multiple storm chasers near [[Springer, Oklahoma]], then the same cell produced another strong tornado near [[Wapanucka, Oklahoma]]. A large tornado moved through [[Polk County, Texas]] around 6:00 pm CDT.<ref>https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200422_rpts.html</ref> At 7:08 pm CDT a [[tornado emergency]] was issued for [[Jasper, Texas]]. The same storm prompted another tornado emergency for [[Fort Polk, Louisiana]] at 8:13 pm. More tornadoes kept forming from the storm system in [[Louisiana]]. A large, destructive tornado was spotted between the towns of [[Marksville, Louisiana]], and [[Alexandria, Louisiana]], reportedly damaging [[Louisiana State University of Alexandria|LSU-Alexandria]] and killing one person east of Woodworth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.katc.com/news/reports-lsua-buildings-damaged-by-severe-weather-wednesday-night|title=Reports: LSUA buildings damaged by severe weather Wednesday night|date=2020-04-23|website=KATC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/lsr/#LCH/202004230224/202004230224/0100 |title=LCH: 1 E Woodworth |date=2020-04-23 |access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> The system kept moving southwest, into the states of [[Mississippi]], [[Alabama]], and [[Florida]] in April 23. A possible morning tornado was spotted near the Alabama\u2013Florida state line, near the town of [[Barker Store, Florida]]. Another tornado was confirmed over [[Moultrie, Georgia]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tornado]]\n** [[Tornadoes by year]]\n** [[Tornado records]]\n** [[Tornado climatology]]\n** [[Tornado myths]]\n* [[List of tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n** [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of 21st-century Canadian tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of European tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in Asia]]\n** [[List of Southern Hemisphere tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes striking downtown areas]]\n* [[Tornado intensity]]\n** [[Fujita scale]]\n** [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 tornado months}}\n{{2020 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Tornadoes by year}}\n\n[[Category:2020 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2020]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists by year]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists|Torn]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Notable tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in 2020}}\n{{Infobox tornado year\n|name          = Tornadoes of 2020\n|image         = 2020 United States tornado count.png\n|caption       = A chart of the 2020 United States tornado count estimated from the number of preliminary reports\n|timespan      = January 3 \u2013 ongoing\n|max_EF        = EF4\n|max_location  = 4 different locations\n|max_date      = 3 different days\n|tornadoes_usa = 399\n|total_damages_usa = >$4.4&nbsp;billion\n|total_fatalities_world = 75\n|total_fatalities_usa = 75\n|year = 2020\n}}\n\nThis page documents notable [[tornado]]es and [[tornado outbreak]]s worldwide in '''2020'''. Strong and destructive tornadoes form most frequently in the [[United States]], [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[East India|Eastern India]], but can occur almost anywhere under the right conditions. Tornadoes also develop occasionally in southern [[Canada]] during the [[Northern Hemisphere]]'s summer and somewhat regularly at other times of the year across [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. Tornadic events are often accompanied by other forms of [[severe weather]], including strong [[thunderstorm]]s, strong [[winds]], and [[hail]].\n\nThere have been 456 preliminary filtered reports of tornadoes in the United States in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Severe Weather Report Summary 2020 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/online/monthly/2020_annual_summary.html |publisher=Storm Prediction Center |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> of which at least 399 have been confirmed. Worldwide, 75 tornado-related deaths have been confirmed, all in the United States.\n\n==Events==\n{{Tornadoes of 2020/Deadly}}\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\n\n===United States yearly total===\n<!-- This section is transcluded to other articles; modify with caution. -->\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 398\n|FU = 8\n|F0 = 121\n|F1 = 192\n|F2 = 56\n|F3 = 16\n|F4 = 4\n|F5 = 0\n| Enhanced=yes\n}}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==January==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#January}}\nThere were 90 tornadoes reported in the United States in January, of which 88 were confirmed. Overall, January was an active month, with over twice the national average of 35 tornadoes.\n\n===January 3 (South Africa)===\nOn January 3, severe thunderstorms developed over the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]]. One thunderstorm developed into a supercell which produced an EF3 tornado that caused significant damage to a farm, destroyed the houses of seven families, and destroyed about {{convert|200|hectare|acre|sigfig=1}} of pine forest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Panbult tornado (Mpumalanga) on the 3rd of January 2020. |url=https://twitter.com/SAWeatherServic/status/1214087467692941312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1214087467692941312&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.news24.com%2FSouthAfrica%2FNews%2Fwatch-tornado-lasting-about-40-minutes-destroyed-farm-and-7-houses-in-mpumalanga-saws-confirms-20200106 |website=Twitter |publisher=South African Weather Service |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===January 10\u201311===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of January 10\u201311, 2020}}\n{{stack begin}}{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 25|EF1= 41|EF2= 13|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=0}}{{stack end}}\n[[File:Carollton EF2 damage1.jpg|thumb||float|left|High-end EF2 damage to a house near Carrollton, Alabama.]]\nOn January 10, the Storm Prediction Center issues a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the Southern United States, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. A squall line of severe thunderstorms with numerous embedded circulations and semi-discrete supercell structures moved from [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]] to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], producing numerous tornadoes. A high-end EF2 tornado near [[Carrollton, Alabama]] destroyed multiple homes and mobile homes, and resulted in three fatalities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three people killed in Pickens Co. tornado |url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/11/three-people-killed-pickens-co-tornado/ |publisher=WBRC |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Three people were fatally injured when a long-tracked EF2 tornado destroyed two mobile homes south of [[Haughton, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enfinger |first1=Emily |title=87-year-old dies from injuries from Haughton tornado |url=https://eu.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/local/2020/01/15/third-death-confimred-haughton-tornado/4480014002/ |publisher=Shreveport Times |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> and an EF1 tornado killed one person near [[Nacogdoches, Texas]] when a large tree fell onto a mobile home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brackett |first1=Ron |last2=Wesner Childs |first2=Jan |title=Tornadoes, Severe Storms Kill 8; More Than 300,000 Lose Power |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-severe-storms-tornadoes-impact-texas-louisiana-tennessee-arkansas-mississippi |website=weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Houston, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey for January 10 Burleson County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHGX&e=202001112109|date=January 11, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado struck [[Rome, Mississippi]], causing significant damage and destroying the local post office. An EF2 tornado also struck [[Union Grove, Alabama]], significantly damaging a school building in the community. Another school also sustained major damage near [[Kershaw, South Carolina]], as a result of another EF2 tornado. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 79 tornadoes, and resulted in 7 fatalities. Total damage from the event reached $1.1&nbsp;billion according to the [[National Centers for Environmental Information]].<ref name=\"NCEI_billion\">{{cite web|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters: Events|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/billions/events}}</ref>\n\n==February==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#February}}\nThere were 51 tornadoes reported in the United States in February, of which 42 were confirmed. February was also an active month, besting the national average of 29 tornadoes.\n\n===February 5\u20137===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 21|EF2= 6|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=1}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of February 5\u20137, 2020}}\n[[File:KannapolisNCEF2-2020.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF2 damage to a house near Kannapolis, North Carolina.]]\nBeginning on February 5, a moderate tornado outbreak affected the Deep South and Eastern United States. On the first day of the outbreak, an EF2 tornado caused significant tree and outbuilding damage near [[Pickens, Mississippi]], and injured four people. A long-tracked EF2 tornado touched down near [[Bay Springs, Mississippi]] and passed though the town of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise]], downing numerous trees and power poles and toppling a metal fire tower. This tornado tore large sections of roofing off of multiple homes in rural areas as well. On February 6, one person was killed in [[Marengo County, Alabama]] when an EF1 tornado destroyed a mobile home near [[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/06/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202002070055|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Jackson, Mississippi|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/05/2020 \u2013 02/06/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #1|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSJAN&e=202002070252|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado also touched down near [[Kannapolis, North Carolina]], to the north of [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]]. No injuries were reported, though multiple homes were damaged, including one that lost its roof and some exterior walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/06/tornado-touches-down-kannapolis/|title=Tornado touches down in Kannapolis|website=WBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/confirmed-tornado-damages-homes-in-kannapolis/275-3a51f749-53cd-490f-bf2c-3fd08c8c793c|title=Confirmed tornado damages homes in the Kannapolis area|website=WCNC|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Tornado rips roof off home in Kannapolis, North Carolina|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gE8N-dBHI7k|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Another EF2 downed metal truss transmission towers near [[Kings Mountain, North Carolina|Kings Mountain]], and an EF1 tornado caused damage in the southern suburbs of Charlotte.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://salisburypost.com/2020/02/08/three-rescued-from-flood-waters-weather-service-confirms-tornado-in-rowan-county/|title=As flooding, damage lingers, 3 rescued from Third Creek, weather service confirms tornadoes in Rowan|last=Walker|first=Shavonne|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=WBTV>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/07/nws-confirms-ef-tornado-near-pineville/|title=NWS confirms EF-1 tornado near Pineville|last=Myers|first=Jason|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/tornado-stanly-albemarle-damage-storm/275-227d0b28-9341-4b91-a7a0-057602e4a803|title=EF-1 tornado confirmed near Albemarle|work=[[WCNC-TV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> A high-end EF1 tornado moved directly through [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] as well, causing considerable damage to homes and businesses.<ref name=WBTV/> On February 7, five tornadoes touched down in Maryland, including an EF1 that struck [[Westminster, Maryland|Westminster]] and [[Manchester, Maryland|Manchester]], causing moderate damage. An EF0 tornado also caused minor damage in [[Leesburg, Virginia]]. Along with the tornadic storms, heavy rainfall resulted in widespread flooding also occurred throughout the southern states. Total economic losses from the event exceeded $925&nbsp;million. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 37 tornadoes, and resulted in one fatality.<ref>{{cite report|publisher=Aon|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Global Catastrophe Recap: February 2020|url=http://thoughtleadership.aonbenfield.com/Documents/20200309_analytics-if-february-global-recap.pdf|page=4|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==March==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#March}}\nThere were 106 tornadoes reported in the United States in March, of which 78 were confirmed. Although March was slightly below average in number of tornadoes, the series of severe weather outbreaks and tornadoes throughout March inflicted widespread damage across the country. Combined economic losses reached approximately $2.4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matt Sheehan|publisher=Reinsurance News|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Separate billion-dollar events mark active month for US tornadoes: Aon|url=https://www.reinsurancene.ws/separate-billion-dollar-events-mark-active-month-for-us-tornadoes-aon/}}</ref>\n\n===March 2\u20133===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2020}}\n[[File:CookevilleTNEF4rubbleanddamage.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF4 damage in a residential area near Cookeville, Tennessee.]]\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 3|EF2= 4|EF3= 1|EF4= 1|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA small but devastating tornado outbreak affected parts of the Southern United States on the evening of March 2 into the early morning hours of March 3, with the most severe damage and all fatalities occurring in Tennessee. [[Nashville, Tennessee]] was directly struck by a high-end EF3 tornado just after 12:30&nbsp;a.m. CDT on March 3. Major structural damage and six fatalities occurred as the tornado passed just north of downtown Nashville and through [[Mount Juliet, Tennessee|Mount Juliet]] to the east. Additional tornadoes were reported in [[Missouri]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Kentucky]]. An EF2 tornado killed one person and caused significant damage to homes, mobile homes, and outbuildings near [[Camden, Tennessee]] as well. The majority of the deaths occurred in Putnam County, where a violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Baxter, Tennessee|Baxter]] shortly before 2:00&nbsp;a.m. and moved into western [[Cookeville, Tennessee|Cookeville]]. Many homes and other buildings were completely leveled or swept away in residential areas of Cookeville, and 19 people were killed in town.<ref name=\"OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=March 2\u20133, 2020 Tornadoes and Severe Weather|url=https://www.weather.gov/ohx/20200303|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=21 killed, 221 hospitalized after tornadoes rip through Nashville, surrounding areas|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/six-killed-at-least-20-hurt-after-tornadoes-rip-through-nashville-surrounding-areas|publisher=ABC Action News|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In addition, two EF2 tornadoes also downed numerous trees in forested areas near [[Alvaton, Kentucky]] and [[Clarkrange, Tennessee]] as well. A lone, long-tracked [[supercell]] thunderstorm was responsible for all nine of the tornadoes in Tennessee as it moved from near [[Dyersburg, Tennessee|Dyersburg]] in West Tennessee to near [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] in East Tennessee. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 14 tornadoes, and resulted in 26 fatalities.<ref name=\"OHX\"/>\n\n===March 18\u201319===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 11|EF2= 5|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nOn March 18, an intense [[supercell thunderstorm]] spawned numerous weak tornadoes as it tracked through [[Jack County, Texas|Jack]], [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]], [[Wise County, Texas|Wise]], and [[Young County, Texas|Young counties]] in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/18/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSFWD&e=202003201858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> With severe storms continuing into the early morning hours of March 19, two EF2 tornadoes caused considerable damage to trees, vehicles, farming equipment, and outbuildings near [[Trent, Texas]].<ref name=\"SJT0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in San Angelo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event \u2013 Update #1|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSSJT&e=202003201627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The thunderstorm responsible for those tornadoes went on to produce another EF2 tornado that damaged a large building and over 100 cars at a correctional facility northeast of [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]]. Near [[Sweetwater, Texas|Sweetwater]], an EF2 tornado damaged or destroyed several wind turbines.<ref name=\"SJT0319\"/> Later that day, a large portion of the southern [[Great Plains]] was in line for severe storms, along with parts of the [[Ohio Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Darrow|title=Mar 19, 2020 0100 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200319_0100.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the afternoon, a squall line with several embedded supercells formed from [[Oklahoma]] to [[Indiana]], producing tornadoes in [[Oklahoma]], [[Illinois]], and [[Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTSA&e=202003210250|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PAH0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003202132|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LZK0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornadoes Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003212158|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A large EF2 tornado touched down near [[Everton, Arkansas]] before moving through the southeastern part of town, causing significant damage to homes, a school, outbuildings, and trees.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> Three EF1 tornadoes also touched down in Arkansas, one of which tracked between [[Gassville, Arkansas|Gassville]] and [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]], inflicting considerable damage to some homes. Further north, two EF1 tornadoes caused damage in [[Sunfield, Illinois|Sunfield]] and [[Dahlgren, Illinois]].<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> One person was injured in Illinois,<ref name=\"PAH0319\"/> and another injury occurred in Arkansas. A total of 21 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/>\n\n===March 28\u201329===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 3|EF1= 11|EF2= 2|EF3= 1|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 3}}\nOn March 28, the SPC issued a moderate risk of severe weather for much of Illinois, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. An enhanced risk of severe weather was in place \nacross parts of Iowa, Missouri, Indiana, and Arkansas as well. Only weak tornadoes touched down in the moderate risk area, though a few strong tornadoes occurred elsewhere. A large EF3 tornado struck the city of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], while being streamed live on local news stations, producing major damage to homes, businesses, and a shopping mall. Vehicles were thrown and mangled, and the local airport sustained severe damage as well. A train was also derailed, and 22 injuries occurred in Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado flattens buildings in Jonesboro, Arkansas, as severe weather moves across the Midwest, Lower Mississippi River Valley |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/28/weather/tornadoes-severe-storms-forecast-saturday/index.html |website=CNN |publisher=CNN |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Damage Reported in Northeastern Arkansas as Tornado Strikes Jonesboro |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-03-28-severe-weather-tornado-impacts-plains-south-midwest |website=Weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20200328 reports\">{{cite web |title=Today's Storm Reports (20200328 1200 UTC \u2013 20200329 1159 UTC) (Print Version) |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200328_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=202003292239|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Zoellner |first1=Danielle |title=Tornado rips through Arkansas town, injuring six people |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/arkansas-tornado-jonesboro-weather-injured-a9432511.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same storm that produced this tornado also produced two EF1 tornadoes, one before and one after it moved over Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003292104|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\"/>\nInto the evening, numerous weak tornadoes touched down in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], and another in southwest [[Wisconsin]]. This included an EF1 tornado caused moderate damage to apartment buildings and trees in [[Oelwein, Iowa]].<ref name=\"20200328 reports\"/>\nA low-end EF2 tornado moved through the southern fringes of [[Henderson, Kentucky]], destroying numerous outbuildings and a barn, and damaging dozens of homes and trees.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Henderson County KY Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300139|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\nAnother EF2 struck the town of [[Newburgh, Indiana]], where five homes sustained partial to total roof removal, and one home had a few upper floor exterior walls ripped off. Numerous other homes in town sustained less severe damage, and two people were injured in Newburgh.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Newburgh Indiana Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300138|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the morning of March 29, the same storm system produced an EF0 tornado that mainly damaged trees near [[Sparta, Tennessee]]. Overall, this outbreak produced 20 tornadoes.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/29/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202003311858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 30\u201331===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 3|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 2}}\nOn the evening of March 30, isolated supercells developed across Texas and Oklahoma, producing two weak tornadoes. One of these was given an EFU rating, and the other, which was a [[landspout]] or non-mesocylonic tornado, was given an EF0 rating.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Amarillo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/30/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSAMA&e=202003312336|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \nOn March 31, multiple supercells and embedded mesocyclones formed along and just ahead of a convective line, producing several tornadoes across parts of the [[Southeastern United States]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\">{{cite web |title=SPC Storm reports for03/31/20 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200331_rpts.html |publisher=Storm Prediction |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nA high-end EF2 tornado caused significant damage just south of [[Eufaula, Alabama]], where multiple homes in a subdivision had their roofs torn off. A few of these homes sustained partial exterior wall loss.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuentes |first1=Carmen |title=Eufaula tornado runs through neighborhood |url=https://www.wtvy.com/content/news/Eufaula-tornado-runs-through-neighborhood-569268011.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=WTVY |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202004020401|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Multiple other weak tornadoes were confirmed in southeast [[Mississippi]], southern [[Alabama]], and northern [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004032145|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\"/> A landspout tornado was caught on video around 2:30&nbsp;p.m. PDT at the north edge of [[Richland, Washington]], causing no damage. A total of 15 tornadoes are confirmed.<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\"/>\n\n==April==\n{{see also|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\nThere have been 191 tornadoes confirmed in the United States in April.\n\n===April 7\u20139===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 20|EF1= 10|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nA few weak tornadoes touched down across [[Ohio]] and [[Pennsylvania]] late on April 7 and into the early morning of April 8, causing tree and structure damage. Later on the night of April 8, a large EF2 cone tornado touched down near [[Weiner, Arkansas]], completely destroying a mobile home. The tornado then struck [[Harrisburg, Arkansas]] in [[Poinsett County, Arkansas|Poinsett County]].<ref>https://twitter.com/nwsmemphis/status/1248334194377232384?s=21</ref><ref>https://media.arkansasonline.com/img/photos/2020/04/09/storm1_t800.jpg?90232451fbcadccc64a17de7521d859a8f88077d</ref> In Harrisburg, one frail home was completely leveled by the tornado, and several homes nearby were also badly damaged or destroyed in residential areas of town.<ref>https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/apr/09/forecasters-tornado-touched-down-overnight-northwe/#.Xo9c00N8lmQ.twitter</ref> Extensive tree damage occurred and two people were injured in Harrisburg.<ref>https://twitter.com/kwoodallTV/status/1248076374084124673?s=19</ref> Numerous tornadoes, all of which weak and short-lived, occurred across [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and Ohio that night as well. One EF1 tornado caused considerable damage to a brick building in downtown [[Mooresville, Indiana]]. Another EF1 tornado damaged two mobile homes, a garage, and trees near [[Wilkesville, Ohio]] on April 9 before the outbreak came to an end. Numerous reports of damaging straight line winds were also received throughout the event. A total of 31 tornadoes were confirmed.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n=== April 12\u201313 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 30|F1 = 72|F2 = 20|F3 = 13|F4 = 2|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{main|2020 Easter tornado outbreak}}\n[[File:Cantwell Mill, Mississippi, April 12, 2020, tornado damage.jpg|thumb||float|left|High-end EF4 damage to a large, well-anchored cabin northeast of Bassfield, Mississippi.]]\nFrom the late morning of April 12 through the early morning of April 13, a major tornado outbreak unfolded across the [[Southeastern United States]], with more than 100 tornadoes touching down in just over 36 hours. Over a 48 hour period from nighttime on April 11 to the evening of April 13, 137 tornadoes touched down from Texas to Maryland. This event was well forecasted, with the [[Storm Prediction Center]] issuing severe weather outlooks as early as five days before the outbreak. At 10:40 a.m. CDT on April 12, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] [[Tornado Watch]] was issued by the Storm Prediction Center across northeast [[Louisiana]], southeast [[Arkansas]], and central and northern [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0106.html|title=PDS Watch 106|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 11:44 a.m. CDT, a [[Tornado emergency|tornado emergency]] was issued for [[Monroe, Louisiana]] as an [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF3 tornado]] moved through the city limits causing significant damage to more than 200 homes, as well as the [[Monroe Regional Airport (Louisiana)|Monroe Regional Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliareporter.com/news_and_business/regional_news/article_4f3bcd2e-7ce3-11ea-8412-1b0152c3f85d.html|title=Magnolia Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado Emergency for Monroe Louisiana and Northeast Ouachita Parish |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=SVSSHV&e=202004121644 |website=Iowa Environmental Mesonet |publisher=National Weather Service Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SteveWAFB/status/1249799061898760192?s=20|title=Steve Caparotta of WAFB on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 3:30 p.m. CDT, two back-to-back supercells began to produce three intense long-tracked tornadoes, including two rated EF4, that would move across southern Mississippi, prompting the [[National Weather Service]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to issue multiple tornado emergencies for numerous towns including [[Prentiss, Mississippi|Prentiss]], [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]], [[Collins, Mississippi|Collins]], and [[Soso, Mississippi|Soso]]. At 4:40 p.m. CDT, a second [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS watch]] was issued affecting extreme southeast Mississippi and most of [[Alabama]], including the cities of [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], and [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0110.html|title=Storm Prediction Center \u2013 PDS Watch 110|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As the system progressed northeastward into the nighttime hours, another tornado emergency was issued, this time at 11:28 p.m. EDT for the towns of [[Ooltewah, Tennessee|Ooltewah]] and [[Collegedale, Tennessee|Collegedale]] as a deadly EF3 tornado struck the eastern suburbs of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], killing three and injuring 19.<ref>https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMRX&e=202004151915|title=NWS Morristown Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, the storms that formed the day before congealed into a strong [[squall line]] as they advanced into eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Carolinas]]. At 6:55 a.m. EDT, an embedded supercell within a [[Squall line|QLCS]] prompted yet another tornado emergency as [[Walterboro, South Carolina]] took a direct hit from a confirmed tornado.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSCharlestonSC/status/1249652455073370113?s=20|title=NWS Charleston SC on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/StuOstro/status/1250057470669721602</ref> Nine EF3 tornadoes occurred on day two of the outbreak, including seven in [[South Carolina]] that resulted in a combined eight deaths, most notably the 3/4-mile wide EF3 in [[Hampton County, South Carolina|Hampton County]] that took the lives of five people near the towns of [[Estill, South Carolina|Estill]] and Nixville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSCHS&e=202004152035|title=NWS Charleston Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nWith <!-- do not change this unless the fatality count has updated -->32<!-- as of April 20, only 32 fatalities have been confirmed to be tornado-related --> tornado-related fatalities, it was the deadliest outbreak since <!-- again, do not change to 2012 unless the TORNADO-RELATED fatality count exceeds 35 -->[[Tornado outbreak of April 27\u201330, 2014|April 27\u201330, 2014]].<ref>{{cite web |title=At Least 41 People Have Died After a Tornado Outbreak Ravaged the South |url=https://time.com/5820741/deadly-tornadoes-storms-south/ |website=TIME USA |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 19\u201320===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 1|F0 = 5|F1 = 10|F2 = 3|F3 = 0|F4 = 1|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\nFor the second straight Sunday and Monday, several tornadoes touched down across the Southern United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Today's Storm Reports (20200419 1200 UTC \u2013 20200420 1159 UTC)|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200419_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> On April 19, a large, violent EF4 tornado moved through Hurricane Creek, [[Sandy Hook, Mississippi|Sandy Hook]], Pine Burr, and areas north of [[Purvis, Mississippi]], killing one person and injuring another.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in New Orleans|title=NWS New Orleans Tornado Report|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=LSRLIX&e=202004201907|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSJacksonMS/status/1252400542443122691|title=The Hurricane Creek/Pine Burr/Purvis/Camp Shelby tornado has been rated an EF-4 with estimated maximum wind of 170 MPH, path length of 54.2 miles, and maximum path width of 1.25 miles. Additional details will follow later this evening.|last=Jackson MS|first=NWS|date=2020-04-20|website=@NWSJacksonMS|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Later that evening, an EF2 tornado caused severe damage to homes near [[Andalusia, Alabama]] injuring one person.<ref>{{cite web|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Mobile, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for April 19, 2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMOB&e=202004212319|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> That night, an EF1 tornado caused damage to multiple mobile homes and destroyed an RV camper near [[Robertsdale, Alabama]] injuring one person.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMOB&e=202004210100|title=IEM :: PNS from NWS MOB|last=akrherz@iastate.edu|first=daryl herzmann|website=mesonet.agron.iastate.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\nEarly on April 20, another EF2 tornado damaged several homes and a mobile home near [[Bridgeboro, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee FL|title=NWS Tallahassee FL Damage Survey|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004211628|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> Later on, several more tornadoes were reported throughout the morning into the afternoon in Central Florida.<ref>{{cite web|title=Today's Storm Reports (20200420 1200 UTC \u2013 20200421 1159 UTC)|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200420_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref> An EF0 tornado caused considerable damage in [[Homosassa, Florida|Homosassa]] and [[Homosassa Springs, Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tampa Bay Ruskin FL|title=NWS Tampa Bay Ruskin FL Damage Survey|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTBW&e=202004201854|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chronicleonline.com/news/local/nws-tornado-causes-damage-in-homosassa-power-out-for-more-than-1-000-customers/article_ca25601c-831a-11ea-9981-a3a03237cc85.html|title=NWS: Tornado causes damage in Homosassa; power out for more than 1,000 customers|last=Thompson|first=Jeff Bryan & Buster|website=Chronicle Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Another EF0 tornado was caught on video lifting a stationary construction trailer across [[Interstate 75 in Florida|Interstate 75]] in [[Wildwood, Florida]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PaulFox13/status/1252257783912824832|title=That'll stop traffic. Line of strong to severe thunderstorms across central #Florida produced this potential #tornado in Citrus county on I-75. #Skytower|last=DellegattoHigh voltage signFOX|first=Paul|date=2020-04-20|website=@PaulFox13|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsbreak.com/news/0OoG9ZmK/suspected-tornado-crosses-interstate-as-severe-weather-hits-central-florida|title=Suspected Tornado Crosses Interstate as Severe Weather Hits Central Florida|website=News Break|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> 19 tornadoes have been confirmed so far and damage surveys are ongoing.\n\n===April 22\u201323===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 0|F1 = 0|F2 = 2|F3 = 0|F4 = 0|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of April 22\u201323, 2020}} \nNumerous tornadoes struck southern [[Oklahoma]] during the afternoon of April 22. A tornado of at least EF2 strength killed at least two people in [[Madill, Oklahoma|Madill]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Two people killed after tornado hits Marshall County, officials say |url=https://www.koco.com/article/person-killed-after-tornado-hits-marshall-county-officials-say/32243168 |accessdate=23 April 2020 |agency=KOCO News 5 |date=22 April 2020}}</ref> A large tornado was captured on video by multiple storm chasers near [[Springer, Oklahoma]], then the same cell produced another strong tornado near [[Wapanucka, Oklahoma]]. A large tornado moved through [[Polk County, Texas]] around 6:00 pm CDT.<ref>https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200422_rpts.html</ref> At 7:08 pm CDT a [[tornado emergency]] was issued for [[Jasper, Texas]]. The same storm prompted another tornado emergency for [[Fort Polk, Louisiana]] at 8:13 pm. More tornadoes kept forming from the storm system in [[Louisiana]]. A large, destructive tornado was spotted between the towns of [[Marksville, Louisiana]], and [[Alexandria, Louisiana]], reportedly damaging [[Louisiana State University of Alexandria|LSU-Alexandria]] and killing one person east of Woodworth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.katc.com/news/reports-lsua-buildings-damaged-by-severe-weather-wednesday-night|title=Reports: LSUA buildings damaged by severe weather Wednesday night|date=2020-04-23|website=KATC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/lsr/#LCH/202004230224/202004230224/0100 |title=LCH: 1 E Woodworth |date=2020-04-23 |access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> The system kept moving southwest, into the states of [[Mississippi]], [[Alabama]], and [[Florida]] in April 23. A possible morning tornado was spotted near the Alabama-Florida state line, near the town of [[Barker Store, Florida]]. Another tornado was confirmed over [[Moultrie, Georgia]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tornado]]\n** [[Tornadoes by year]]\n** [[Tornado records]]\n** [[Tornado climatology]]\n** [[Tornado myths]]\n* [[List of tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n** [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of 21st-century Canadian tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of European tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in Asia]]\n** [[List of Southern Hemisphere tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes striking downtown areas]]\n* [[Tornado intensity]]\n** [[Fujita scale]]\n** [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 tornado months}}\n{{2020 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Tornadoes by year}}\n\n[[Category:2020 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2020]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists by year]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists|Torn]]\n", "name_user": "Ionmars10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 22\u201323:perMOS:ENBETWEEN", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tornadoes_of_2020"}
{"title_page": "Louis Brennan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Louis Brennan\n|honorific_suffix = <small>[[Order of the Bath|CB]]</small>\n|image         = Louis Brennan.jpg\n|image_size    = \n|caption       = Louis Brennan with a demonstration model\n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1852|01|28|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Castlebar]], [[Ireland]]\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1932|01|17|1852|10|29|df=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Montreux]], [[Switzerland]]\n|death_cause   = Motor vehicle accident\n|resting_place = [[St. Mary's Roman Catholic Cemetery]], [[Kensal Green]], [[London]]\n|resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|51.529679|-0.228953|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n|residence     = \n|nationality   = [[Irish Australian|Irish-Australian]]\n|other_names   = \n|known_for     = Inventor of the steerable [[Brennan Torpedo]]\n|education     = \n|alma_mater    = \n|employer      = \n|occupation    = [[Mechanical engineer]] and [[inventor]]\n|home_town     = \n|title         = \n|salary        = \n|networth      = \n|height        = \n|weight        = \n|term          = \n|predecessor   = \n|successor     = \n|party         = \n|boards        = \n|religion      = \n|spouse        = \n|partner       = \n|children      = \n|parents       = \n|relations     = \n|signature     = \n|website       = \n|footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Louis Brennan''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CB}} (28 January 1852 \u2013 17 January 1932) was an [[Irish Australian|Irish-Australian]] [[mechanical engineer]] and [[inventor]].\n\n==Biography==\nBrennan was born in [[Castlebar]], [[Ireland]], and moved to [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]] in 1861 with his parents. He started his career as a watchmaker and a few years later was articled to [[Alexander Kennedy Smith]], a renowned civil and mechanical engineer of the period.\nHe served as a sergeant in the Victorian Engineers under the command of Captain [[John_James_Clark |J. J. Clark]].\nBrennan invented the idea of a steerable [[torpedo]] in 1874, from observing that if a thread is pulled on a reel at an angle with suitable leverage, the reel will move away from the thread side. Brennan spent some years working out his invention, and received a grant of \u00a3700 from the [[Victoria, Australia|Victorian]] government towards his expenses. He patented the [[Brennan Torpedo]] in 1877. The idea was trialled at [[Camden Fort Meagher|Camden Fort]] near [[Crosshaven]], [[County Cork|Cork]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Walter |last=McGrath |year=1986 |journal=Journal of the Irish Railway Records Society |volume=16 |number=100 |pages=82\u201386 |issn= }}</ref>\n\nBrennan went to England in 1880 and brought his invention before the War Office. Sir [[Andrew Clarke (British Army officer, born 1824)|Andrew Clarke]] alerted the authorities to the possibilities of the torpedo if used in the defence of harbours and channels, and the patent was eventually bought for a sum believed to be more than \u00a3100,000 (\u00a3 {{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|100000|1879|r=-2}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}). In 1887 Brennan was appointed superintendent of the Brennan torpedo factory, and was consulting engineer 1896\u20131907.\n\n[[Image:Einschienerp.jpg|thumb|Brennan's gyroscopically balanced monorail on a demonstration run.]]\nHe did much work on a [[Gyro Monorail|monorail]] locomotive which was kept upright by a [[gyrostat]]. In 1903 he patented a [[Gyro Monorail|gyroscopically-balanced monorail]] system that he designed for military use; he successfully demonstrated the full sized system on 10 November 1909, at [[Gillingham, Medway|Gillingham]], [[England]]. At the [[Japan\u2013British Exhibition]] of 1910 at [[White City, London]] he built a mile long monorail track and gave rides for around 40 people at a time on his gyro stabilised 22-ton prototype. [[Winston Churchill]] (then Home Secretary) was one of the passengers and then drove the vehicle himself for one circuit. He was so impressed that he brought along the Prime Minister and other cabinet members and family to see it the following week. The exhibit was awarded the Grand Prize for the exhibition. Although the ability of the vehicle to balance itself on a single rail was amazing, especially when stationary, it was not to prove a commercial success, partly due to fears that the gyroscopes might fail, and partly because any wagons or coaches towed by the locomotive would also need powered gyroscopic stabilisation.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=The Monorail Society |url=http://www.monorails.org/tMspages/History.html |title=Monorails in History: Part I |accessdate=8 November 2005 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1916 to 1919 Brennan served in the munitions inventions department. In 1916 he submitted a patent application entitled \"Improvements Relating to Aerial Navigation\" in which he outlined designs for a helicopter,<ref>\"Improvements Relating to Aerial Navigation\", GB Patent 281735, 19 May 1916</ref> and in June 1916 he received support for his experimental helicopter project from the British [[Minister of Munitions|Ministry of Munitions]]. From 1919 to 1926 he was engaged by the [[Air Ministry]] in aircraft research work at the [[Royal Aircraft Establishment]], Farnborough,<ref name=ADB>{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A030208b.htm |title=Brennan, Louis (1852 - 1932) |accessdate=22 February 2008 |author=Sandow, Mary |work=Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 3 |publisher=Melbourne University Press |year=1969 |pages=223\u2013224|chapter=Brennan, Louis (1852\u20131932) }}</ref> and gave much time to developing his [[helicopter]]. The first tethered flights (inside a hangar) took place in December 1921, at which time the engine was up-rated from the [[Bentley BR1]] to the [[Bentley BR2]]. Flight trials in the open started in May 1924, however in October 1925 a demonstration flight ended with one of the twin blade rotors touching the ground causing damage to several components.<ref>Progress of British Aviation, Hull Daily Mail, 14 Oct 1925, p7</ref> The government had spent a large sum of money on it, and the Air Ministry was still offering an award of \u00a350,000 for the developments of a successful machine, but in 1926 the air ministry gave up funding the Brennan helicopter project, much to Brennan's disappointment.<ref>{{Dictionary of Australian Biography|First=Loius|Last=Brennan|shortlink=0-dict-biogBr-By.html#brennan2}}</ref> \n\nHe married Anna Quinn (died 1931) on 10 September 1892. He was survived by a son and a daughter. Brennan was created a Companion of the [[Order of the Bath]] in 1892, and was foundation member of the National Academy of Ireland in 1922. In January 1932 he was knocked down by a car at [[Montreux]], [[Switzerland]], and died on 17 January 1932.<ref name=ADB/> Brennan was buried at [[St. Mary's Roman Catholic Cemetery]], [[Kensal Green]], [[London]], in an unmarked plot numbered 2454 that is opposite the Chapel record office.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sites.google.com/site/stmaryskensalgreen/history/burialrecords/persons-of-note |title=Persons of Note |work=Burial records |publisher=St Mary's Cemetery, Kensal Green |location=London |date=March 2000 |accessdate=6 April 2012 }}</ref> On 11 March 2014, Irish [[Taoiseach]] [[Enda Kenny]] unveiled a new gravestone for Brennan at St. Mary's in a ceremony honouring the inventor's life and career.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/taoiseach-honours-mayo-born-inventor-of-the-torpedo-1.1720458 | title = Taoiseach honours Mayo-born inventor of the torpedo | last = Hennessy | first = Mark | newspaper = [[The Irish Times]] | date = 11 March 2014 | accessdate = 12 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nGillingham Library retains the archive of his papers.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gillingham, Medway|Gillingham]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |author=Tomlinson, Norman |title=Louis Brennan: Inventor Extraordinaire |publisher=John Halliwell |year=1980 |isbn=0905540182 }}\n*{{cite book |author=Wilkes, Robert Edward |title=Louis Brennan CB |publisher=Gillingham Library & Arts Committee |year=1973 |pages=30 |isbn=0903316056 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://vulpeculox.net/misc/brenn.htm The gyroscopic monorail of Louis Brennan]\n* [http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_heroes/hist_hero_louis_brennan.html \"Louis Brennan: The Wizard of Oz\"] in ''Heroes and Villains of Ireland''. Turtle Bunbury.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brennan, Louis}}\n[[Category:1852 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian inventors]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Australian people in rail transport]]\n[[Category:People from Castlebar]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Louis Brennan\n|honorific_suffix = <small>[[Order of the Bath|CB]]</small>\n|image         = Louis Brennan.jpg\n|image_size    = \n|caption       = Louis Brennan with a demonstration model\n|birth_name    = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1852|01|28|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Castlebar]], [[Ireland]]\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1932|01|17|1852|10|29|df=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Montreux]], [[Switzerland]]\n|death_cause   = Motor vehicle accident\n|resting_place = [[St. Mary's Roman Catholic Cemetery]], [[Kensal Green]], [[London]]\n|resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|51.529679|-0.228953|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n|residence     = \n|nationality   = [[Irish Australian|Irish-Australian]]\n|other_names   = \n|known_for     = Inventor of the steerable [[Brennan Torpedo]]\n|education     = \n|alma_mater    = \n|employer      = \n|occupation    = [[Mechanical engineer]] and [[inventor]]\n|home_town     = \n|title         = \n|salary        = \n|networth      = \n|height        = \n|weight        = \n|term          = \n|predecessor   = \n|successor     = \n|party         = \n|boards        = \n|religion      = \n|spouse        = \n|partner       = \n|children      = \n|parents       = \n|relations     = \n|signature     = \n|website       = \n|footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Louis Brennan''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CB}} (28 January 1852 \u2013 17 January 1932) was an [[Irish Australian|Irish-Australian]] [[mechanical engineer]] and [[inventor]].\n\n==Biography==\nBrennan was born in [[Castlebar]], [[Ireland]], and moved to [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]] in 1861 with his parents. He started his career as a watchmaker and a few years later was articled to [[Alexander Kennedy Smith]], a renowned civil and mechanical engineer of the period.\nHe served as a sergeant in the Victorian Engineers under the command of Captain [[John_James_Clark |J. J. Clark]].\nBrennan invented the idea of a steerable [[torpedo]] in 1874, from observing that if a thread is pulled on a reel at an angle with suitable leverage, the reel will move away from the thread side. Brennan spent some years working out his invention, and received a grant of \u00a3700 from the [[Victoria, Australia|Victorian]] government towards his expenses. He patented the [[Brennan Torpedo]] in 1877. The idea was trialled at [[Camden Fort Meagher|Camden Fort]] near [[Crosshaven]], [[County Cork|Cork]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Walter |last=McGrath |year=1986 |journal=Journal of the Irish Railway Records Society |volume=16 |number=100 |pages=82\u201386 |issn= }}</ref>\n\nBrennan went to England in 1880 and brought his invention before the War Office. Sir [[Andrew Clarke (administrator)|Andrew Clarke]] alerted the authorities to the possibilities of the torpedo if used in the defence of harbours and channels, and the patent was eventually bought for a sum believed to be more than \u00a3100,000 (\u00a3 {{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|100000|1879|r=-2}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}). In 1887 Brennan was appointed superintendent of the Brennan torpedo factory, and was consulting engineer 1896\u20131907.\n\n[[Image:Einschienerp.jpg|thumb|Brennan's gyroscopically balanced monorail on a demonstration run.]]\nHe did much work on a [[Gyro Monorail|monorail]] locomotive which was kept upright by a [[gyrostat]]. In 1903 he patented a [[Gyro Monorail|gyroscopically-balanced monorail]] system that he designed for military use; he successfully demonstrated the full sized system on 10 November 1909, at [[Gillingham, Medway|Gillingham]], [[England]]. At the [[Japan\u2013British Exhibition]] of 1910 at [[White City, London]] he built a mile long monorail track and gave rides for around 40 people at a time on his gyro stabilised 22-ton prototype. [[Winston Churchill]] (then Home Secretary) was one of the passengers and then drove the vehicle himself for one circuit. He was so impressed that he brought along the Prime Minister and other cabinet members and family to see it the following week. The exhibit was awarded the Grand Prize for the exhibition. Although the ability of the vehicle to balance itself on a single rail was amazing, especially when stationary, it was not to prove a commercial success, partly due to fears that the gyroscopes might fail, and partly because any wagons or coaches towed by the locomotive would also need powered gyroscopic stabilisation.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=The Monorail Society |url=http://www.monorails.org/tMspages/History.html |title=Monorails in History: Part I |accessdate=8 November 2005 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1916 to 1919 Brennan served in the munitions inventions department. In 1916 he submitted a patent application entitled \"Improvements Relating to Aerial Navigation\" in which he outlined designs for a helicopter,<ref>\"Improvements Relating to Aerial Navigation\", GB Patent 281735, 19 May 1916</ref> and in June 1916 he received support for his experimental helicopter project from the British [[Minister of Munitions|Ministry of Munitions]]. From 1919 to 1926 he was engaged by the [[Air Ministry]] in aircraft research work at the [[Royal Aircraft Establishment]], Farnborough,<ref name=ADB>{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A030208b.htm |title=Brennan, Louis (1852 - 1932) |accessdate=22 February 2008 |author=Sandow, Mary |work=Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 3 |publisher=Melbourne University Press |year=1969 |pages=223\u2013224|chapter=Brennan, Louis (1852\u20131932) }}</ref> and gave much time to developing his [[helicopter]]. The first tethered flights (inside a hangar) took place in December 1921, at which time the engine was up-rated from the [[Bentley BR1]] to the [[Bentley BR2]]. Flight trials in the open started in May 1924, however in October 1925 a demonstration flight ended with one of the twin blade rotors touching the ground causing damage to several components.<ref>Progress of British Aviation, Hull Daily Mail, 14 Oct 1925, p7</ref> The government had spent a large sum of money on it, and the Air Ministry was still offering an award of \u00a350,000 for the developments of a successful machine, but in 1926 the air ministry gave up funding the Brennan helicopter project, much to Brennan's disappointment.<ref>{{Dictionary of Australian Biography|First=Loius|Last=Brennan|shortlink=0-dict-biogBr-By.html#brennan2}}</ref> \n\nHe married Anna Quinn (died 1931) on 10 September 1892. He was survived by a son and a daughter. Brennan was created a Companion of the [[Order of the Bath]] in 1892, and was foundation member of the National Academy of Ireland in 1922. In January 1932 he was knocked down by a car at [[Montreux]], [[Switzerland]], and died on 17 January 1932.<ref name=ADB/> Brennan was buried at [[St. Mary's Roman Catholic Cemetery]], [[Kensal Green]], [[London]], in an unmarked plot numbered 2454 that is opposite the Chapel record office.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sites.google.com/site/stmaryskensalgreen/history/burialrecords/persons-of-note |title=Persons of Note |work=Burial records |publisher=St Mary's Cemetery, Kensal Green |location=London |date=March 2000 |accessdate=6 April 2012 }}</ref> On 11 March 2014, Irish [[Taoiseach]] [[Enda Kenny]] unveiled a new gravestone for Brennan at St. Mary's in a ceremony honouring the inventor's life and career.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/taoiseach-honours-mayo-born-inventor-of-the-torpedo-1.1720458 | title = Taoiseach honours Mayo-born inventor of the torpedo | last = Hennessy | first = Mark | newspaper = [[The Irish Times]] | date = 11 March 2014 | accessdate = 12 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nGillingham Library retains the archive of his papers.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gillingham, Medway|Gillingham]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |author=Tomlinson, Norman |title=Louis Brennan: Inventor Extraordinaire |publisher=John Halliwell |year=1980 |isbn=0905540182 }}\n*{{cite book |author=Wilkes, Robert Edward |title=Louis Brennan CB |publisher=Gillingham Library & Arts Committee |year=1973 |pages=30 |isbn=0903316056 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://vulpeculox.net/misc/brenn.htm The gyroscopic monorail of Louis Brennan]\n* [http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_heroes/hist_hero_louis_brennan.html \"Louis Brennan: The Wizard of Oz\"] in ''Heroes and Villains of Ireland''. Turtle Bunbury.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brennan, Louis}}\n[[Category:1852 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian inventors]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Australian people in rail transport]]\n[[Category:People from Castlebar]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Andrew Clarke (administrator)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louis_Brennan"}
{"title_page": "Bruno Bettelheim", "text_new": "{{short description|Austrian-American child psychologist and writer}}\n<nowiki></nowiki>{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name=Bruno Bettelheim\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=Bruno Bettelheim\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1903|8|28}}\n|birth_place=[[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n|death_date={{Death date and age|1990|3|13|1903|8|28}}\n|death_place=[[Silver Spring, Maryland]], United States\n|residence=\n|citizenship=United States\n|nationality=Austrian\n|field=Director of Orthogenic School (1944\u20131973)\n|work_institutions=\n|alma_mater=\n|doctoral_advisor=\n|doctoral_students=[[Benjamin Drake Wright]]\n|known_for=[[child psychology]]; <br>[[Autism]]; <br>''[[The Uses of Enchantment]]''\n|influences=\n|influenced=\n|prizes=\n|religion=\n|footnotes=\n|signature=\n|spouse=Gina Alstadt (1930\u2013?; divorced)<br>Gertrude Weinfeld (1941\u20131984; her death; 3 children)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6VIYAAAAIAAJ&q=Gertrude+Weinfeld+Bettelheim&dq=Gertrude+Weinfeld+Bettelheim|title=The Annual Obituary|publisher=|last1=Andrews|first1=Deborah|last2=Turner|first2=Roland|year=1990|isbn=9781558620926}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Bruno Bettelheim''' (August 28, 1903 \u2013 March 13, 1990) was an [[Austria|Austrian-born]] [[psychologist]], [[scholar]], [[public intellectual]] and author who spent most of his academic and clinical career in the United States. An early writer on [[autism]], Bettelheim's work focused on the education of [[Emotional and behavioral disorders|emotionally disturbed]] children, as well as Freudian psychology more generally. In the U.S., he later gained a position as professor at the [[University of Chicago]] and director of the [[Sonia Shankman Orthogenic School|Sonia Shankman Orthogenic School for Disturbed Children]], and after 1973 taught at [[Stanford University]].<ref name=\"Biographical Dictionary of American Educators, 1978\"/> \n\nBettelheim's ideas, which grew out of [[Freud's psychoanalytic theories|those of Sigmund Freud]], theorized that children with behavioral and emotional disorders were not born that way, and could be treated through extended psychoanalytic therapy, treatment that rejected the use of [[psychotropic drugs]] and [[Shock therapy (psychiatry)|shock therapy]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-03-14-9001210549-story.html |title=Dr. Bruno Bettleheim, child psychology expert |last=Fountain |first=John W. |date=March 14, 1990 |work=Chicago Tribune |access-date=2019-05-12 |language=en-US}}</ref> During the 1960s and 1970s he had an international reputation in such fields as autism, [[Child and adolescent psychiatry|child psychiatry]], and [[psychoanalysis]].<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/><ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\"/> \n\nMuch of his work was discredited after his death due to fraudulent academic credentials, allegations of abusive treatment of patients under his care,  accusations of [[plagiarism]], and lack of oversight by institutions and psychological community.  \n\n==Background in Austria==\nBruno Bettelheim was born in [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]], on August 28, 1903. When his father died, Bettelheim left his studies at the [[University of Vienna]] to look after his family's sawmill. Having discharged his obligations to his family's business, Bettelheim returned as a mature student in his thirties to the University of Vienna.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Sources disagree about his education (see section [[Bruno_Bettelheim#Misrepresented_credentials|Misrepresented credentials]]).\n\nBettelheim's first wife, Gina, took care of a troubled American child, Patsy, who lived in their home in Vienna for seven years, and who may or may not have been on the autism spectrum.<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-02-23/entertainment/9702230083_1_bruno-bettelheim-orthogenic-school-richard-pollak Biography As Revenge], ''Chicago Tribune'', Marie Winn (who writes regularly for ''The Wall Street Journal's'' Leisure & Arts Page), Feb. 23, 1997.  \"  .  .  He was familiar with this disease because his first wife, Gina, had cared for an autistic child in their home for several years.  .  \"</ref><ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/><ref name=\"Weekly-Standard-1997\"/>\n\nIn the Austrian academic culture of Bettelheim's time, one could not study the history of art without mastering aspects of [[psychology]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Candidates for the doctoral dissertation in the History of Art in 1938 at Vienna University had to fulfill prerequisites in the formal study of the role of [[Archetypes#Jungian archetypes|Jungian archetypes]] in art, and in art as an expression of the unconscious.\n\nThough Jewish by birth, Bettelheim grew up in a secular family. After the [[Nazi]] invasion and ''[[Anschluss]]'' (political annexation) of [[Austria]] on March 12, 1938, the Nazi authorities sent Bettelheim, other [[Austrian Jews]] and political opponents to the [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] and [[Buchenwald]] [[concentration camp]]s where they were brutally treated, and tortured or killed. Bettelheim was arrested on May 28, 1938 and was imprisoned in both these camps for ten and half months before being released on April 14, 1939.<ref name=\"NeuroTribes, Silberman, pages 202-03, Bettelheim's 10 and a 1/2 months in Dachau and Buchenwald\">''NeuroTribes: The Legacy of Autism and the Future of Neurodiversity'', Steve Silberman, Foreword by Oliver Sacks, Penguin Random House, 2015, [https://books.google.com/books?id=w3XoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT128&lpg=PT128&dq=%22On+May+28,+1938,+policemen+acting+on+orders+from+Berlin+arrived+at+Bettelheim's+door%22&source=bl&ots=qC4YMwdm-p&sig=ooaToQPrzuTq5LAv-3wP2w5wKr0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiW1-vQq8XTAhVFOhQKHQXwA8oQ6AEIIjAA#v=onepage&q=%22On%20May%2028%2C%201938%2C%20policemen%20acting%20on%20orders%20from%20Berlin%20arrived%20at%20Bettelheim's%20door%22&f=false pages 202-203].</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=rgGA91skoP4C&pg=PA39&lpg=PA39&dq=bettelheim+released+Nazis&source=bl&ots=S9ohBY_Twz&sig=mWk4HLedB4J3Xd_SFXXk99AtEQM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjxyoTV_qzUAhUL64MKHUVaAtIQ6AEIUDAJ#v=onepage&q=bettelheim%20released%20Nazis&f=false Dictionary of Genocide, Volume 1: A\u2013L], \"Bettelheim, Bruno (1903\u20131990),\" Samuel Totten, Paul R. Bartrop, with contributions by Steven Leonard Jacobs, Westport, Connecticut, U.S. and London, UK: Greenwood Publishing Group, 2008.</ref> While at the Buchenwald camp, he met and befriended the social psychologist [[Ernst Federn]]. As a result of an amnesty declared for [[Adolf Hitler]]'s birthday (which occurred slightly later on April 20, 1939), Bettelheim and hundreds of other prisoners were released. Bettelheim drew on the experience of the concentration camps for some of his later work.\n\n==Life and career in the United States==\nBettelheim arrived by ship as a refugee in New York City in late 1939 to join his wife Gina, who had already emigrated. They divorced because she had become involved with someone else during their separation.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} He soon moved to Chicago, became a naturalized U.S. citizen in 1944, and married an Austrian woman, Gertrude ('Trudi') Weinfeld, also an emigrant from Vienna.\n\n===Psychology===\nThe [[Rockefeller Foundation]] sponsored a wartime project to help resettle European scholars by circulating their resumes to American universities.  Through this process, Ralph Tyler hired Bettelheim to be his research assistant at the University of Chicago from 1939-1941 with funding from the [[Progressive Education Association]] to evaluate how high schools taught art. Once this funding ran out, Bettelheim found a job at Rockford College, Illinois, where he taught from 1942-1944.<ref name=\"Biographical Dictionary of American Educators, 1978\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=Z5YNz-kNZgsC&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&dq=Bettelheim+%22Progressive+Education+Association%22&source=bl&ots=_3BXp8Jzlq&sig=18cw_k46fLQgTtY-smixWcAQLiM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5_bqLrsbXAhXBYiYKHUBEAIAQ6AEIKzAB#v=onepage&q=Bettelheim%20%22Progressive%20Education%20Association%22&f=false Biographical Dictionary of American Educators, Vol. 1]\nedited by John F. Ohles, London, England and Westport, Connecticut: Greenwood Press, 1978.</ref><ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\"/><ref name=\"How Ralph W. Tyler Taught America to Teach, 2004\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ckIaTAr5yMkC&pg=PA41&lpg=PA41&dq=%22was+at+the+time+seeking+a+specialist+to+assess+art+appreciation%22&source=bl&ots=veq8m6hckb&sig=coaCMqgmt3l7Z91Sdc-rfTBiKLg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja6OH80ozYAhXC4yYKHUc_DuIQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=%22was%20at%20the%20time%20seeking%20a%20specialist%20to%20assess%20art%20appreciation%22&f=false Educating America: How Ralph W. Tyler Taught America to Teach], Morris Finder, Foreword by Henry Louis Gates, Jr., Westport, Connecticut, London: Praeger, 2004, page 41.</ref>\n\nIn 1943, he published the paper \"Individual and Mass Behavior in Extreme Situations\" about his experiences in the concentration camps, a paper which was highly regarded by Dwight Eisenhower among others.<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/>  Bettelheim claimed he had interviewed 1,500 fellow prisoners, although this was unlikely.<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/><ref name=\"NeuroTribes, Steve Silberman, 2015\">''NeuroTribes'', Silberman, 2015, [https://books.google.com/books?id=w3XoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT129&dq=%22exactly+the+person+we+need+for+psychoanalysis+to+grow+and+develop%22+intitle:NeuroTribes&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJ2abc87jTAhUHthQKHUTuBYsQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=%22exactly%20the%20person%20we%20need%20for%20psychoanalysis%20to%20grow%20and%20develop%22%20intitle%3ANeuroTribes&f=false pages 199-208].  \"  .  .  (The closest he ever came to meeting Freud was walking past his house.)  .  .  \"</ref> He stated that the Viennese psychoanalyst [[Richard Sterba]] had analyzed him, as well as implying in several of his writings that he had written a PhD dissertation in the philosophy of education. His actual PhD was in art history, and he had only taken three introductory courses in psychology.<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-January-23-1997\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-01-23/features/9701230196_1_orthogenic-school-bruno-bettelheim-pollak Genius Or Fraud? Bettelheim's Biographers Can't Seem To Decide], ''Chicago Tribune'', Ron Grossman, January 23, 1997, page 2: \" . . . he evidently gambled that because of the war no one would be able to check on his credentials. . . \"</ref>\n\nThrough Ralph Tyler's recommendation, the [[University of Chicago]] appointed Bettelheim as a professor of psychology, as well as director of the [[Sonia Shankman Orthogenic School]] for emotionally disturbed children.<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\"/>  He held both positions from 1944 until his retirement in 1973. He wrote a number of books on psychology and, for a time, had an international reputation for his work on [[Sigmund Freud]], [[psychoanalysis]], and [[Serious emotional disturbance|emotionally disturbed]] children.  \n\nAt the Orthogenic School, Bettelheim made changes and set up an environment for [[milieu therapy]], in which children could form strong attachments with adults within a structured but caring environment. He claimed considerable success in treating some of the emotionally disturbed children. He wrote books on both normal and abnormal [[child psychology]], and became a major influence in the field, widely respected during his lifetime. He was noted for his study of [[Feral child|feral children]], who revert to the animal stage without experiencing the benefits of belonging to a community.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Poplau|first=Ronald W.|title=A Living Classroom: Ideas for Student Creativity and Community Service|date=2018|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=|isbn=978-1-4758-4854-0|location=Lanham, MD|pages=74}}</ref> He discussed this phenomenon in the book ''The Informed Heart''.<ref name=\":0\" /> Even critics agree that, in his practice, Bettelheim was dedicated to helping these children using methods and practices that would enable them to lead happy lives.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Zipes|first=Jack|title=Breaking the Magic Spell: Radical Theories of Folk and Fairy Tales|date=2002|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|year=|isbn=0-8131-9030-4|location=Lexington|pages=179}}</ref> It is based on his position that psychotherapy could change humans and that they can adapt to their environment provided they are given proper care and attention.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBettelheim was elected a Fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1971.<ref name=\"AAAS\">{{cite web|title=Book of Members, 1780\u20132010: Chapter B|url=http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterB.pdf|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=June 24, 2011}}</ref>  After retiring in 1973, he and his wife moved to [[Portola Valley, California]], where he continued to write and taught at [[Stanford University]].  His wife died in 1984.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=msgABAAAQBAJ&pg=PA38&lpg=PA38&dq=bettelheim+retired+1973#v=onepage&q=bettelheim%2520retired%25201973&f=false |title=The Fame Lunches: On Wounded Icons, Money, Sex, the Bront\u00ebs, and the Importance of Handbags |last=Merkin |first=Daphne |date=2014-09-02 |publisher=Macmillan |isbn=9780374140373 |pages=38 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===''The Uses of Enchantment''===\nBettelheim analyzed [[fairy tale]]s in terms of Freudian psychology in ''[[The Uses of Enchantment]]'' (1976). He discussed the emotional and symbolic importance of [[fairy tale]]s for children, including traditional tales at one time{{Clarify|date=March 2012}}<!-- i suspect IN HIS TIME but i don't know --> considered too dark, such as those collected and published by the [[Brothers Grimm]]. Bettelheim suggested that traditional fairy tales, with the darkness of abandonment, death, witches, and injuries, allowed children to grapple with their fears in remote, symbolic terms. If they could read and interpret these fairy tales in their own way, he believed, they would get a greater sense of meaning and purpose. Bettelheim thought that by engaging with these [[social evolution|socially evolved]] stories, children would go through emotional growth that would better prepare them for their own futures. In the United States, Bettelheim won two major awards for ''The Uses of Enchantment'': the [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] for Criticism<ref name=nbcc>[http://bookcritics.org/awards/past_awards/#1976 \"All Past National Book Critics Circle Award Winners and Finalists\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604095541/http://bookcritics.org/awards/past_awards/#1976 |date=June 4, 2019 }}. [[National Book Critics Circle]]. Retrieved 2019-05-09.</ref>\nand the [[National Book Award]] in the category of [[List of winners of the National Book Award#Current|Contemporary Thought]].<ref name=nba1977>\n[https://www.nationalbook.org/awards-prizes/national-book-awards-1977/?cat=translation&sub-cat=contemporary-thought \"National Book Awards \u2013 1977\"]. [[National Book Foundation]]. Retrieved 2019-05-09. <br/>There was a \"Contemporary\" or \"Current\" award category from 1972 to 1980.</ref>\n\n===Death===\nAt the end of his life, Bettelheim suffered from depression. He appeared to have had difficulties with depression for much of his life.<ref name=\"nybooks.com\">[http://www.nybooks.com/articles/16083 Robert Gottlieb, \"The Strange Case of Dr. B.\", The New York ''Review of Books'', 27 Feb 2003]. Retrieved 2008-04-15.</ref> In 1990, widowed, in failing physical health, and suffering from the effects of a stroke which impaired his mental abilities and paralyzed part of his body, he committed suicide as a result of self-induced [[asphyxiation]] by placing a plastic bag over his head.<ref name=\"SAJ\"/><ref name=Suicidelaterlife>{{Cite book|last=Osgood|first=Nancy J.|publication-date=1992|title=Suicide in later life|page=4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=K202uE6QiDUC&lpg=PA4&vq=bruno&pg=PA4#v=snippet&q=bruno|accessdate=January 29, 2010|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-669-21214-3|date=July 1992}}</ref> He died on March 13, 1990, in Maryland.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-03-14/news/9001210549_1_sonia-shankman-orthogenic-school-jacquelyn-sanders-dr-Bettelheim Dr. Bruno Bettelheim, Child Psychology Expert], ''Chicago Tribune'', John W. Fountain, March 14, 1990.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nBettelheim was a [[public intellectual]], whose writing and many public appearances in popular media paralleled a growing post WWII interest in [[psychoanalysis]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Silverman |first1=Chloe |title=From Disorders of Affect to Mindblindness: Framing the History of Autism Spectrum Disorders \" |url=https://case.edu/affil/sce/Texts_2005/Autism%20and%20Representation%20Silverman.htm |website=The Society for Critical Exchange |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> For instance, he appeared multiple times on [[The Dick Cavett Show]] in the 70s to discuss theories of [[autism]] and psychoanalysis. <ref>{{cite web |title=The Dick Cavett Show - Guests |url=https://dickcavettshow.com/index.php/guests |website=dickcavettshow.com |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> Pollak's biography argues that such popular appearances shielded Bettelheim's unethical behavior from scrutiny.<ref name=\"Chicago Reader, review of Richard Pollak's The Creation of Dr. B, 1997\">[https://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/in-print-the-abominable-dr-bettelheim/Content?oid=892495 In Print: the abominable Dr. Bettelheim], ''Chicago Reader'', Cara Jepsen, Jan. 16, 1997.</ref>\n\nIn 1974, a four-part series featuring Bruno Bettelheim and directed by Daniel Carlin appeared on French television \u2014 ''Portrait de Bruno Bettelheim''.{{fact|date=March 2019}}\n\n[[Woody Allen]] included Bettelheim as himself in a cameo in the film ''[[Zelig]]'' (1983).{{fact|date=March 2019}}\n\nA [[BBC]] ''[[Horizon (BBC TV series)|Horizon]]'' documentary about Bettelheim was televised in 1987.<ref>{{cite web |title=Horizon - BBC Two England - 2 February 1987 |url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/157067cd458c4728bd2d46cf79bf8de2 |website=BBC Genome |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n<!--- [Does Kellerman state this clearly in his book, and if so where (Foreword, or Afterword, notes)? Please supply exact references, otherwise cannot be left here: libelous] --- Bettelheim and the controversy that arose after his death appeared to influence the character of Dr. Andres de Bosch in [[Jonathan Kellerman]]'s mystery ''Bad Love''. De Bosch is portrayed as a child psychiatrist who espouses great humanitarian ideals, while practicing bigotry, class prejudice and cruelty. In his life he is lionized for the man he seems to be, but after his death he is exposed as a tyrant and a fraud. --->\n\n==Controversies==\nBettelheim's life and work have come under increasing scrutiny since his death. \n\n===Misrepresented credentials===\n\nThough he spent most of his life working in psychology and psychiatry, Bettelheim's educational background in those fields is murky at best. Sources disagree whether Bettelheim's PhD was in art history<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beck |first1=Joan |title=SETTING THE RECORD STRAIGHT ABOUT A 'FALLEN GURU' |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1997-04-03-9704030057-story.html |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=chicagotribune.com |date=1997}}</ref> <ref name=\"Baltimore-Sun-Paul-McHugh-January-19-1997\">[http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1997-01-19/news/1997019010_1_bruno-bettelheim-richard-pollak-orthogenic-school Bruno Bettelheim: a cautionary life], ''Baltimore Sun'', Paul R. McHugh, Jan. 19, 1997.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=McHugh |first1=Paul R. |title=Bruno Bettelheim: a cautionary life |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1997-01-19-1997019010-story.html |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=baltimoresun.com |date=1997}}</ref> or in philosophy (aesthetics).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Winn |first1=Marie |title=BIOGRAPHY AS REVENGE. |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1997-02-23-9702230083-story.html |work=chicagotribune.com |date=1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lehmann-Haupt |first1=Christopher |title=An Icon of Psychology Falls From His Pedestal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/13/books/an-icon-of-psychology-falls-from-his-pedestal.html |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=13 January 1997}}</ref> When he was hired at the University of Chicago, [[Ralph W. Tyler| Ralph Tyler]] assumed that he had two PhDs, one in art history and the other in psychology.<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-11-11/features/9004030282_1_bruno-bettelheim-sonia-shankman-orthogenic-school-animal-terrorSolving The Puzzle That Was Bruno Bettelheim], ''Chicago Tribune'', Ron Grossman, November 11, 1990.</ref> He also believed, falsely, that Bettelheim was certified to conduct [[Psychoanalysis]] though Bettelheim never received such certification. <ref name=\"How Ralph W. Tyler Taught America to Teach, 2004\"/> A posthumous review of his transcript showed that Bettelheim had only taken three introductory classes in psychology. Bertram Cohler and Jacquelyn Sanders at the Orthogenic School believed Bettelheim had a PhD in art history.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grossman |first1=Ron |title=SOLVING THE PUZZLE THAT WAS BRUNO BETTELHEIM |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-11-11-9004030282-story.html |work=chicagotribune.com}}</ref> In some of his own writings, Bettelheim implied that he had written a dissertation on the philosophy of education.{{Citation Needed|date=May 2019}} \n\nDetermining Bettelheim's education is complicated by the fact that he routinely embellished or inflated aspects of his own biography. As an example, Bettelheim's first wife, Gina, took care of a troubled American child, Patsy, who lived in their home in Vienna for seven years. Although Bettelheim later claimed he himself had taken care of the child, there is general agreement that his wife actually provided most of the child care.<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997/><ref name=\"NeuroTribes, Silberman, Bettelheim's first wife Gina taking care of Patsy\"/>  There is disagreement, however, among sources regarding whether or not Patsy was autistic.<ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/><ref name=\"Weekly-Standard-1997\"/>  Bettelheim later claimed that it was Patsy who inspired him to study autism<ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/> and embellished her into two or even several autistic children in his home.<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/><ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997/><ref name=\"NeuroTribes, Silberman, Bettelheim's first wife Gina taking care of Patsy\">''NeuroTribes'', Steve Silberman, 2015, See [https://books.google.com/books?id=WRpPDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA201&lpg=PA201&dq=%22she+ended+up+taking+Patsy+into+the+household%22&source=bl&ots=QxQU-zDufa&sig=ACfU3U2AAURCnY7IyeWTfNCoudi8rvlMwA&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj7wIqQs_XnAhVnFTQIHRAUCVsQ6AEwAHoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22she%20ended%20up%20taking%20Patsy%20into%20the%20household%22&f=false pages 201 and 201] for Bettelheim's wife actually taking care of Patsy, who may or may not have been on the autism spectrum, and see [https://books.google.com/books?id=WRpPDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA203&lpg=PA203&dq=%22over+the+years+she+would+morph+into+several+autistic+children%22&source=bl&ots=QxQU-zDtlb&sig=ACfU3U3kl3Jp_kjvmLBgxPb3CctpFK9iIg&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjMweX9svXnAhUXJzQIHaWNCKgQ6AEwAHoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22over%20the%20years%20she%20would%20morph%20into%20several%20autistic%20children%22&f=false last paragraph of page 203] for Bettelheim later exaggerating her into several children.</ref>\n\nAdditionally, when he applied for a position at [[Rockford College]] in Illinois, he claimed in a r\u00e9sum\u00e9 that he had earned summa cum laude doctorates in philosophy, art history, and psychology, and he made such claims that he had run the art department at Lower Austria's library, that he had published two books on art, that he had excavated Roman antiquities, and that he had engaged in music studies with [[Arnold Schoenberg]].  When he applied at the University of Chicago for a professorship and as director of the Orthogenic School, he further claimed that he had training in psychology, experience raising autistic children, and personal encouragement from Sigmund Freud.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beck |first1=Joan |title=SETTING THE RECORD STRAIGHT ABOUT A 'FALLEN GURU' |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1997-04-03-9704030057-story.html |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=chicagotribune.com}}</ref> Posthumous biographies of Bettelheim have investigated these claims and came to no clear conclusions about his credentials<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sutton |first1=Nina |title=Bettelheim, a life and a legacy |date=1997 |publisher=WestView Press |isbn=0813390990 |edition=Pbk.}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book|last=Pollak|first=Richard|title=The creation of Dr. B: A biography of Bruno Bettelheim|url=https://books.google.com/?id=VklXDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT4&lpg=PT4&dq=%22Chapter+Six:++The+Orthogenic+School%22#v=onepage&q=%22Chapter%20Six%3A%20%20The%20Orthogenic%20School%22&f=false|year=1997|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=0-684-80938-9|pages=478}}</ref> A review in ''The Independent'' (UK) of Sutton's book stated that Bettelheim \"despite claims to the contrary, possessed no psychology qualifications of any sort.\"<ref name=The-Independent-December-9-1995>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/turbulent-dreams-of-a-damaged-saint-1524787.html Turbulent dreams of a damaged saint], ''The Independent'' [UK], Nicholas Tucker (review of ''Bruno Bettelheim: A Life and a Legacy'' by Nina Sutton), 8 December 1995.</ref>  A review of Pollak's book in ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated \"when all is said and done, Bettelheim seems to have re-enacted the archetypal American success story of inventing a false past, concocting a new formula for snake oil and selling it to the public with flummery. Under Mr. Pollak's magnifying glass, Bettelheim is seen in a new, harsh light, and stands exposed as a brilliant charlatan.\"<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Book-Review-January-13-1997\"/>  Another review in ''The New York Times'' by a different reviewer stated that Bettelheim \"began inventing degrees he never earned.\"<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/>  A review in the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' stated \"as Pollak demonstrates, Bettelheim was a snake-oil salesman of the first magnitude.\"<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997/>\n\n<ref name=\"LosAngeles-Times-1997-Book-Review-Howard-Gardner\"/><ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/>  In the ''[[New York Review of Books]]'', Robert Gottlieb describes Pollak as a \"relentlessly negative biographer,\" but Gottlieb still writes, \"The accusations against Bettelheim fall into several categories. First, he lied; that is, he both exaggerated his successes at the school and falsified aspects of his background, claiming a more elaborate academic and psychoanalytic history in Vienna than he had actually had. There is conclusive evidence to support both charges.\"  Gottlieb goes on to say that Bettelheim arrived in the United States as a Holocaust survivor and refugee without a job nor even a profession, and writes, \"I suspect he said what he thought it was necessary to say, and was then stuck with these claims later on, when he could neither confirm them (since they were false) nor, given his pride, acknowledge that he had lied.\"  This is Robert Gottlieb's judgment call for why Bettelheim lied.<ref name=\"nybooks.com\"/>\n\nIn a 1997 ''[[Weekly Standard]]'' article Peter Kramer, clinical professor of psychiatry at Brown University, summarized: \"There were snatches of truth in the tall tale, but not many. Bettelheim had earned a non-honors degree in philosophy, he had made acquaintances in the psychoanalytic community, and his first wife had helped raise a troubled child. But, from 1926 to 1938, -- the bulk of the '14 years' at university -- Bettelheim had worked as a lumber dealer in the family business.\"<ref name=\"Weekly-Standard-1997\">[http://www.weeklystandard.com/the-battle-over-bettelheim/article/9267 THE BATTLE OVER BETTELHEIM], ''Weekly Standard'', Peter D. Kramer, April 7, 1997.</ref>\n\nIn his 1997 review of Pollak's book in the ''Baltimore Sun'', [[Paul R. McHugh]], then director of Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences at Johns Hopkins, stated \"Bettelheim \u2013 with boldness, energy and luck \u2013 exploited American deference to Freudo-Nietzschean mind-sets and interpretation, especially when intoned in accents Viennese.\"<ref name=\"Baltimore-Sun-Paul-McHugh-January-19-1997\"/>\n\n===Plagiarism in Bettelheim's ''Uses of Enchantment''===\nWithin a year of Bettelheim's death, an article by [[Alan Dundes]] about [[The Uses of Enchantment]] appeared in the winter 1991 edition of ''The Journal of American Folklore'' which presented a case that Bettelheim had engaged in [[plagiarism]].<ref name=\"Journal-of-American-Folklore-Winter-1991\">Dundes, Alan: [https://www.jstor.org/pss/541135 \"Bruno Bettelheim's Uses of Enchantment and Abuses of Scholarship\"]. ''The Journal of American Folklore'', Vol. 104, N0. 411. (Winter, 1991): pages 74\u201383.</ref>  Dundes argued that Bettelheim had borrowed without acknowledgement from a number of sources, including  Dundes' own 1967 paper on Cinderella and from Dr. Julius E. Heuscher's book ''A Psychiatric Study of Fairy Tales'' published in 1963.<ref name=\"A-Psychiatric-Study-Of-Fairy-Tales-Julius-Heuscher\">[http://iucat.iu.edu/iub/2289829 A Psychiatric Study of Fairy Tales: Their Origin, Meaning and Usefulness] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026002751/http://iucat.iu.edu/iub/2289829 |date=October 26, 2016 }}, Julius E. Heuscher, illus. by Melba Bennett, Springfield, Illinois: Thomas pub., 1963, 224 pages. See also [https://books.google.com/books?id=QUMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA2313&lpg=PA2313&dq=%22A+psychiatric+study+of+fairy+tales%22+revised&source=bl&ots=ItgqMsBCNH&sig=brUePMQAfpJuPYV9HlNr4ON_pN4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiMxfe9tvbPAhVkxYMKHbaiBGEQ6AEINzAF#v=onepage&q=%22A%20psychiatric%20study%20of%20fairy%20tales%22%20revised&f=false A Psychiatric Study of Fairy Tales: Their Origin, Meaning and Usefulness; an enlarged and thoroughly revised second edition], Julius E. Heuscher, Springfield, Illinois: Charles C. Thomas, publisher, April 1974, 422 pages.</ref>  In part because of the widespread popularity of ''The Uses of Enchantment'' and Bettelheim's prominence, this academic controversy was discussed in print media and both Dundes and Heuscher spoke publicly about it.<ref name=\"Los-Angeles-Times-February-7-1991\">[https://articles.latimes.com/1991-02-07/news/mn-1024_1_fairy-tales Bettelheim Plagiarized Book Ideas, Scholar Says : Authors: The late child psychologist is accused of 'wholesale borrowing' for study of fairy tales], ''Los Angeles Times'', Anne C. Roark, Feb. 7, 1991.  This article includes a contrast-and-compare between a passage from Bettelheim and a passage from Julius Heuscher's previous book.</ref><ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/><ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-February-7-1991\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-02-07/news/9101110905_1_dundes-article-sonia-shankman-orthogenic-school-bruno-bettelheim Bettelheim Accused Of Plagiarizing Book], ''Chicago Tribune'', Sharman Stein, February 7, 1991.</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, Jacquelyn Sanders, who worked with Bettelheim and later became director of the Orthogenic School, stated that she had read Dundes' article but didn't believe many people would agree with his conclusions. She said, \"I would not call that plagiarism. I think the article is a reasonable scholarly endeavor, and calling it scholarly etiquette is appropriate. It is appropriate that this man deserved to be acknowledged and Bettelheim didn't... But I would not fail a student for doing that, and I don`t know anybody who would\".<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-February-7-1991\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-02-07/news/9101110905_1_dundes-article-sonia-shankman-orthogenic-school-bruno-bettelheim Bettelheim Accused Of Plagiarizing Book], ''Chicago Tribune'', Sharman Stein, February 7, 1991.</ref>\n\n===Abusive treatment of students===\n\nThere is some disagreement as to whether Bettelheim's use of [[corporal punishment]] rose to the level of abuse or was in keeping with the standards of his time. Some staff who worked at the Orthogenic School have spoken out that they saw Bettelheim's behavior as being corporal punishment, but not abuse.<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\"/><ref name=\"Chicago-Reader-Alida-Jatich-two-letters-1990-and-1991\"/><ref name=Washington-Post-Charles-Pekow-August-26-1990>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1990/08/26/the-other-dr-bettleheim/3d938d77-08f3-430a-98f9-dac1fb7b6fd9/ The Other Dr. Bettelheim], ''The Washington Post'', Charles Pekow, Editorial, Aug. 26, 1990.  \"  .  .  we could never tell when he would attack us for any arbitrary reason.  .  \"  See [https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1990/09/06/the-other-dr-bettelheim/0085be31-5f12-4ae8-9ebd-79cc29ecd4c0/ 'The Other Dr. Bettelheim'], Sept. 6, 1990, and [https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1990/10/06/the-bettelheim-we-knew-contd/3c8f4801-9e96-4a86-9f41-11d2ced99a06/ The Bettelheim We Know (Cont'd.)], Oct. 6, 1990, for the contrasting views of some counselors.</ref><ref name=\"Commentary-Magazine-Ron-Angres-October-1990\">Angres, Ronald: [https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/who-really-was-bruno-bettelheim/ \"Who, Really, Was Bruno Bettelheim?\"], personal essay, Commentary, 90, (4), October 1, 1990: 26\u201330.</ref> As an example, David Zwerdling, who was a counselor at the school for one year in 1969-70, wrote a Sept. 1990 response to ''The Washington Post'' in which he stated, \"I witnessed one occasion when an adolescent boy cursed at a female counselor. Incensed upon learning of this, Dr. Bettelheim proceeded to slap the boy two or three times across the face, while telling him sternly never to speak that way to a woman again. This was the only such incident I observed or heard of during my year at the school...until fairly recently, the near-consensus against corporal punishment in schools did not obtain.\"  However, Zwerdling also noted, \"He also was a man who, for whatever reasons, was capable of intense anger on occasion.\"<ref name=Washington-Post-Charles-Pekow-August-26-1990/>\n\nConversely, many students and staff at the school have argued that Bettelheim was abusive, violent, and cruel to them and to others. There are multiple newspaper accounts of abuse, in letters,<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Alida-Jatich-A-Personal-View-1990>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-10-29/news/9003300393_1_bruno-bettelheim-orthogenic-school-autistic A Personal View Of Bruno Bettelheim], ''Chicago Tribune'', Alida Jatich, Oct. 29, 1990.  '  .  .  Whenever Bettelheim called a young person ``autistic`` or ``psychotic`` or ``homicidal`` or ``suicidal`` or anything else, the staff believed him regardless of all evidence to the contrary. To them, the truth was whatever Bettelheim said it was, and their job was to get me and the other youngsters to accept it.  .  '</ref><ref>''Chicago Reader'', Letters to the Editor, [http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/the-cult-of-bettelheim/Content?oid=3835176 The Cult of Bettelheim], \"By WB A former counselor,\" July 5, 1990.</ref><ref name=Letter-to-the-Editor-Roberta-Redford-1990>[https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/20/opinion/l-bettelheim-became-the-very-evil-he-loathed-870890.html Letter to the Editor], ''The New York Times'', 'Bettelheim Became the Very Evil He Loathed,' Roberta Redford, Nov. 20, 1990 (written Nov. 9).  \"  .  .  I would like to believe that at the beginning his motives were pure. By the time I knew him, he was a megalomaniac, twisted and out of control. We were terrified of him, and lived for those days when he was out of town.  .  \"</ref><ref name=Washington-Post-Charles-Pekow-August-26-1990/><ref name=\"Chicago-Reader-Alida-Jatich-two-letters-1990-and-1991\">''Chicago Reader'', Letters to the Editor, [http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/brutal-bettelheim/Content?oid=875450 Brutal Bettelheim], Name Withheld, April 5, 1990. And, [http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/the-monster-of-the-midway/Content?oid=877368 The Monster of the Midway], Alida Jatich, April 4, 1991. The author lived at the \"Orthogenic School\" from 1966-1972, and in her second letter, she acknowledged authorship of the first.</ref> editorials<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Joan-Beck-October-1-1990>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-10-01/news/9003220135_1_orthogenic-school-bruno-bettelheim-animal-terror Bettelheim Led Us Cruelly Down Wrong Road For Children], ''Chicago Tribune'', Joan Beck, Editorial, Oct. 1, 1990.  \"  .  .  .  But autism is almost certainly caused by a genetic defect, not a cold style of mothering. (Even a quick look at children who are abused or neglected by parents should make it obvious that autism is a completely different kind of problem.)  .  .  .  \"</ref>articles,<ref name=New-York-Times-Richard-Bernstein-1990>Bernstein, Richard: [https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/04/weekinreview/ideas-trends-accusations-of-abuse-haunt-the-legacy-of-dr-bruno-bettelheim.html \"Accusations of Abuse Haunt the Legacy of Dr. Bruno Bettelheim\"], ''The New York Times'', November 4, 1990: \"The Week in Review\" section. \" . . not only of a tyrant but of a hypocrite as well. . \"</ref><ref name=\"Commentary-Magazine-Ron-Angres-October-1990\"/>A November 1990 ''Chicago Tribune'' article states:  \"Of the 19 alumni of the Orthogenic School interviewed for this story, some are still bitterly angry at Bettelheim, 20 or 30 years after leaving the institution due to the trauma they had suffered under him. Others say their stays did them good, and they express gratitude for having had the opportunity to be at the school. All agree that Bettelheim frequently struck his young and vulnerable patients.\"<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\"/> and memoirs.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=DyDbxBkeyQMC&pg=PA132&lpg=PA132&dq=%22Tom+Lyon's+(1983)+roman+a+clef+The+Pelican+and+After:+A+Novel+about+Emotional+Disturbance%22&source=bl&ots=Pq9-CFYZ5b&sig=ucj4Cp2SdwaD2kuHkWbEb18T-RM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2ooyCpMDTAhVrzlQKHW3UD2QQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=%22Tom%20Lyon's%20(1983)%20roman%20a%20clef%20The%20Pelican%20and%20After%3A%20A%20Novel%20about%20Emotional%20Disturbance%22&f=false The Positive Side of Special Education: Minimizing Its Fads, Fancies, and Follies], Kenneth A. Kavale, Mark P. Mostert, ScareCrow Education (an imprint of The Rowman & Littlefield Pub. Group), 2004, page 132.</ref><ref name=\"Not The Thing I Was, Stephen Eliot, 2003\">[http://www.torontopubliclibrary.ca/detail.jsp?R=704207 Not The Thing I Was: Thirteen Years at Bruno Bettelheim's Orthogenic School], Stephen Eliot, New York: St. Martin's Press, 2003, as listed for Toronto Public Library.</ref><ref name=\"Crazy-My-Seven-Years-At-Bruno-Bettelheim's-Orthgenic-School-Redford-2010\">[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11073285-crazy Crazy: My Seven Years At Bruno Bettelheim's Orthogenic School], Roberta Carly Redford, Trafford Publishing, 364 pages, 2010.  The author was a student at the school from 1967 to 1974, ages 16 to 23.</ref>\n\nA particularly evocative example came from Alida Jatich, who lived at the school from 1966 to 1972 from ages twelve to eighteen. She wrote an initially anonymous April 1990 letter to the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'' in which she stated that she \"lived in fear of Bettelheim's unpredictable temper tantrums, public beatings, hair pulling, wild accusations and threats and abuse in front of classmates and staff. One minute he could be smiling and joking, the next minute he could be exploding.\" She added, \u201cIn person, he was an evil man who set up his school as a private empire and himself as a demi-god or cultleader.\u201d Jatich said Bettelheim had \u201cbullied, awed, and terrorized\u201d the children at his school, their parents, school staff members, his graduate students, and anyone else who came into contact with him.<ref>Quoted in New York Times, November 4, 1990</ref> \n\nPublished books, memoirs, and biographies of Bettelheim have also taken up the question of his treatment of students.<ref>Adam Feinstein, A History of Autism Conversations, Wiley Blackwell, p.71</ref><ref name=\"And-They-Call-It-Help-Louise-Armstrong\">''And They Call it Help: The Psychiatric Policing of America's Children'', Louise Armstrong, Addison-Wesley, 1993, Chapter 3 \"Bart Simpson Meets Bruno Bettelheim.\" See pages 75 and following for Alida Jatich's reports of abuse at the school. See pages 77 and following for the overall nonresponse from the Chicago psychiatric community. See pages 80 and following for more of Jatich's recounts of her experiences and her thoughts regarding why more people didn't speak up.</ref> Richard Pollak's biography of Bettelheim was inspired by his brother's experience at the school, and Bettelheim's callous response to inquiries about that experience.<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/><ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997/><ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-April-3-1997-Joan-Beck\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-04-03/news/9704030057_1_bruno-bettelheim-richard-pollak-mental-illness Setting The Record Straight About A `Fallen Guru'], ''Chicago Tribune'', Joan Beck, Editorial, April 3, 1997. '  .  . claimed he had summa cum laude degrees in three disciplines,  .  .  '</ref> \n\nPollak's biography also states that two separate women reported that Bettelheim fondled their breasts and those of other female students at the school while he was ostensibly apologizing to each for beating her.<ref name=\"LosAngeles-Times-1997-Book-Review-Howard-Gardner\">[https://articles.latimes.com/1997-01-19/books/bk-19948_1_bruno-bettelheim The Confidence Man : THE CREATION OF DR. B.: A Biography of Bruno Bettelheim. By Richard Pollak. Simon & Schuster: 478 pages], ''Los Angeles Times'', review by Howard Gardner, Jan. 19, 1997. \" . . indicts those of his time who knew the man but kept their reservations to themselves.\"</ref><ref name=\"Weekly-Standard-1997\"/>\n\n===Institutional and professional responses===\nPerhaps in part because of Bettelheim's professional and public stature, there was little effort during his lifetime to curtail his behavior or intervene on behalf of his victims. His work at the [[University of Chicago]] seems to have been given less formal oversight by the University than other research entities under their purview.<ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/>\n\nProfessionals in the psychiatric and psychological communities likely knew there were allegations of abuse and maltreatment at the Orthogenic School.<ref name=\"Late-Talking-Children-Stephen-Camarata-2014\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=YxNmBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA82&lpg=PA82&dq=%22Chicago+analysts+scathingly+referred+to+the+doctor%22&source=bl&ots=mcDoha9kVj&sig=ZRXiVPrGzB3Lvx6QR1jLb5ccAFI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjthtSsofnPAhWDWz4KHfKxBCAQ6AEIKjAD#v=onepage&q=%22Chicago%20analysts%20scathingly%20referred%20to%20the%20doctor%22&f=false Late-Talking Children: A Symptom of a Stage?], Stephen M. Camarata, MIT Press, 2014. From \"Ch. 4: Lessons from Autism: Charlatans, False Cures, and Questionable Cures\", page 81 quotes a paragraph from ''Newsweek'' magazine.</ref><ref name=Newsweek-September-10-1990>''Newsweek'', \"'Beno Brutalheim'?,\" Nina Darnton, Sept. 10, 1990.</ref><ref name=\"Chicago-Reader-Alida-Jatich-two-letters-1990-and-1991\"/>. [[Howard Gardner]] a professor at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] wrote that many professionals knew of Bettelheim's behavior but did not confront him for various reasons including \"fear about Bettelheim's legendary capacity for retribution to the solidarity needed among the guild of healers to a feeling that, on balance, Bettelheim's positive attributes predominated and an unmasking would fuel more malevolent forces.\"<ref name=\"LosAngeles-Times-1997-Book-Review-Howard-Gardner\"/>\n\n===Autism controversy===\n\nBehavioral psychology and conditions in children and adolescents was little understood in the mid-twentieth century.  The concept of \"autism\" was first used as a term for [[schizophrenia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.uoregon.edu/autismhistoryproject/topics/childhood-psychosis-or-schizophrenia/ |title=Childhood Psychosis or Schizophrenia | website=The Autism History Project |last=Herman |first=Ellen |publisher=University of Oregon |access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> In the 1950s into the 1960s what may be understood as [[autism]] in children was regularly also referred to as \"childhood psychosis and childhood schizophrenia\". \"Psychogenesis\", the theory that childhood disorders had origins in early childhood events or trauma acting on the child from the outside was a prominent theory, and Bettelheim was a prominent proponent of a psychogenic basis for autism. For Bettelheim, the idea that outside forces cause individual behavior issues can be traced back to his earliest prominent article on the psychology of imprisoned persons.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.uoregon.edu/autismhistoryproject/archive/bruno-bettelheim-schizophrenia-as-a-reaction-to-extreme-situations-1956/ |title=Bruno Bettelheim, \u201cSchizophrenia as a Reaction to Extreme Situations,\u201d 1956 |website=The Autism History Project |last=Herman |first=Ellen |publisher=University of Oregon |access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>  Beginning in the 1960s and into the 1970s, \"biogensis\", the idea that such conditions had an inner-organic or biological basis overtook psychogenesis.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.uoregon.edu/autismhistoryproject/topics/psychogenesis/ |title=Psychogenesis  |website=The Autism History Project |last=Herman |first=Ellen |publisher=University of Oregon|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, many of Bettelheim's theories in which he attributes [[autism spectrum]] conditions to parenting style are considered to be discredited, not least because of the controversies relating to his academic and professional qualifications.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\"/><ref name=\"philly.com\"/><ref name=\"autisticadvocacy.org\"/>\n\nAutism spectrum conditions are now currently regarded as perhaps having multiple forms with a variety of genetic, epigenetic, and brain development causes influenced by such environmental factors as complications during pregnancy, viral infections, and perhaps even air pollution.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\">[https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/autism/documents/evaluatingchanges_workshopsummary.pdf Workshop on U.S. Data to Evaluate Changes in the Prevalence of Autism Spectrum Disorders (ASDs)], U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), February 1, 2011, Background: What Do We Know About ASD Prevalence?, M. Yeargin-Allsopp, page 7, ' . . There are likely multiple forms of ASDs with multiple causes that are poorly understood. . '</ref><ref name=Mayo-Clinic-June-3-2014>[http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/autism-spectrum-disorder/basics/causes/con-20021148 Autism spectrum disorder, Cause], Mayo Clinic Staff, June 3, 2014.  '  .  .  '''Genetic problems.''' Several different genes appear to be involved  .  .  .  .  .  '''Environmental factors.''' Researchers are currently exploring whether such factors as viral infections, complications during pregnancy or air pollutants play a role in triggering autism spectrum disorder.  .  .  '</ref><ref name=\"philly.com\">[http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/public_health/Why-are-the-French-still-blaming-mothers-for-autism-.html?c=r Why are the French still blaming mothers for autism?], Philly.com, Michael Yudell, Posted: Tuesday, January 31, 2012.</ref><ref name=\"autisticadvocacy.org\">[http://autisticadvocacy.org/2008/04/address-to-florida-autism-task-force-on-world-autism-day/ Address to Florida Autism Task Force on World Autism Day], Autistic Self Advocacy Network (ASAN), statement by Ari Ne'eman, founder of ASAN, April 2, 2008. ' . . the past few decades have resulted in a decrease in the stigmatization of parents of autistic children, as a result of the medical community moving away from the odious and damaging inaccuracy that autism is the result of \"refrigerator mothers.\" . . '</ref><ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/><ref name=\"New-York-Times-Book-Review-January-13-1997\"/><ref name=Scientific-Review-Mental-Health-Practice-2002>[http://www.srmhp.org/0101/autism.html Separating Fact from Fiction in the Etiology and Treatment of Autism], ''Scientific Review of Mental Health Practice'', James Herbert, Ian Sharp, Brandon Gaudiano (all three authors from Hahnemann University in Philadelphia, Penn.), Vol. 1: No. 1, Spring-Summer 2002.  \"  .  .  no controlled research has been produced to support the refrigerator mother theory of autism. For example, Allen, DeMeyer, Norton, Pontus, and Yang (1971) did not find differences between parents of autistic and mentally retarded children and matched comparison children on personality measures.  .  \"</ref>\n\nThe two biographies by Sutton (1995) and Pollak (1997) awakened interest and focus on Bettelheim's actual methods as distinct from his public persona.<ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/><ref name=\"New-York-Times-Book-Review-January-13-1997\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/13/books/an-icon-of-psychology-falls-from-his-pedestal.html?_r=0 An Icon of Psychology Falls From His Pedestal], ''The New York Times'', Books, Christopher Lehmann-Haupt (review of ''The Creation of Dr. B'' by Richard Pollak), Jan. 13, 1997.</ref><ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\">\n{{cite web|first=Sarah|last=Boxer|authorlink=|title=The Man He Always Wanted to Be|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/01/26/reviews/970126.boxer.html|work=The New York Times|publisher=|location=|page=|date=January 26, 1997|accessdate=Dec 2, 2016|quote=Bruno Bettelheim's new biographer lays his cards on the table right away: he thinks Bettelheim was a pathological liar.}}</ref> Bettelheim's theories on the causes of [[autism]] have been largely discredited, and his reporting rates of cure have been questioned, with critics stating that his patients were not actually autistic.<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997/><ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\">Finn, Molly, June/July 1997, ''First Things'', \"In the Case of Bruno Bettelheim\" {{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/article/2008/08/006-in-the-case-of-bruno-bettelheim-15 |title=Archived copy |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220025609/http://www.firstthings.com/article/2008/08/006-in-the-case-of-bruno-bettelheim-15 |archivedate=February 20, 2012|df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=Raising-America-Ann-Hulbert-2003>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fDaODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA279&lpg=PA279&dq=%22boys+and+girls+for+whom+the+label+autistic+was+a+stretch%22&source=bl&ots=qEUF8Z7SPD&sig=l1KfOUoxZwURNsjFcqVzNCP59_s&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj8y-3JuoPRAhUpiVQKHQS9CjYQ6AEIGjAA#v=onepage&q=%22boys%20and%20girls%20for%20whom%20the%20label%20autistic%20was%20a%20stretch%22&f=false Raising America: Experts, Parents, and a Century of Advice about Children], Ann Hulbert, Random House, 2003.  \"  .  .  An evocative case history approach like his allowed for fudging of samples, methods, and final results, and Bettelheim did so quite brazenly.  .  \"</ref> In a favorable review of Pollak's biography, Christopher Lehmann-Haupt of ''The New York Times'' wrote, \"What scanty evidence remains suggests that his patients were not even autistic in the first place.\"<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Book-Review-January-13-1997\"/>\n\nIn 1997 the psychiatrist [[Peter D. Kramer|Peter Kramer]] wrote, \"The Ford Foundation was willing to underwrite innovative treatments for autistic children, so Bettelheim labeled his children autistic. Few actually met the definition of the newly minted syndrome.\"<ref name=\"Weekly-Standard-1997\"/>\n\nBettelheim believed that autism did not have an organic basis, but resulted when mothers withheld appropriate affection from their children and failed to make a good connection with them. Bettelheim also blamed absent or weak fathers. One of his most famous books, ''The Empty Fortress'' (1967), contains a complex and detailed explanation of this dynamic in psychoanalytical and psychological terms. These views were disputed at the time by mothers of autistic children and by researchers.<ref name=\"Lehmann-Haupt-1997\">Lehmann-Haupt, Christopher, \"An Icon of Psychology Falls From His Pedestal,\" ''The New York Times,'' 13 Jan. 1997.</ref> He derived his thinking from the qualitative investigation of clinical cases.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} He also related the world of autistic children to conditions in concentration camps.\n\nIt appears that Leo Kanner first came up with the term \"refrigerator mother,\" although Bettelheim did a lot to popularize the term.  \"Although it now seems beyond comprehension that anyone would believe that autism is caused by deep-seated issues arising in early childhood relationships, virtually every psychiatric condition was attributed to parent-child relationships in the 1940s and 1950s, when Freudian psychoanalytic theory was in its heyday.\"<ref name=\"Autism, Lisa, Benaron, 2009\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=qK9zCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=%22virtually+every+psychiatric+condition+was+attributed+to+parent-child+relationships+in+the+1940s+and+1950s%22&source=bl&ots=n2HD-15pPv&sig=ACfU3U0xo6y4-g7NyyeLn_ZgytexwzSb8Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjivpqq0PPgAhVBXawKHb6YAQQQ6AEwAHoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22virtually%20every%20psychiatric%20condition%20was%20attributed%20to%20parent-child%20relationships%20in%20the%201940s%20and%201950s%22&f=false Autism], Lisa D. Benaron, Greenwood Press, 2009, page 4.</ref>\n\nIn ''A Good Enough Parent'', published in 1987, he had come to the view that children had considerable resilience and that most parents could be \"good enough\" to help their children make a good start.<ref>\n[https://www.amazon.com/Good-Enough-Parent-Child-Rearing/review/product/0394757769/ref=dp_db_cm_cr_acr_txt?ie=UTF8&showViewpoints=1 Amazon reviews]{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2009}}</ref>\n\nPrior to this, Bettelheim subscribed to and became an early prominent proponent of the \"[[refrigerator mother]]\" theory of autism: the theory that autistic behaviors stem from the emotional frigidity of the children's mothers. He adapted and transformed the Orthogenic School at the University of Chicago as a residential treatment [[Milieu therapy|milieu]] for such children, who he felt would benefit from a \"[[parentectomy]]\". This marked the apex of autism viewed as a disorder of parenting.<ref name=Scientific-Review-Mental-Health-Practice-2002/><ref>{{cite book|title=Contemporary Directions in Psychopathology. Scientific Foundations of the DSM-V and ICD-11|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gVhgEMyIDUAC&printsec=frontcover|editor1-link=Theodore Millon|editor1-first=Theodore|editor1-last=Millon|editor2-first=Robert F.|editor2-last=Krueger|editor3-first=Erik|editor3-last=Simonsen|publisher=[[Guilford Press]]|location=New York City|year=2011|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=gVhgEMyIDUAC&pg=555&dq=%22Bettelheim+founded+the+Orthogenic+School+at+the+University+of+Chicago+as+a+residential+treatment+milieu+for+such+children,+whom+he+felt+would+benefit+from+a%22%22parent-ectomy%22%22This+marked+the+apex+of+autism+viewed+as+a+disorder+of+parenting.%22 555]|isbn=978-1-60623-533-1}}</ref>\n\nA 2002 book on autism spectrum stated, \"At the time, few people knew that Bettelheim had faked his credentials and was using fictional data to support his research.\"<ref name=\"Elijah's-Cup-2002\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=SexSzvwO-k4C&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72&dq=%22At+the+time,+few+people+knew+that+Bettelheim+had+faked+his+credentials+and+was+using+fictional+data%22&source=bl&ots=zj2ZZN-XG5&sig=NRaG8fSXL47-MI3yNVNlGhgVpEU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2pOO9murPAhUH4IMKHcw0BrEQ6AEIIzAB#v=onepage&q=%22At%20the%20time%2C%20few%20people%20knew%20that%20Bettelheim%20had%20faked%20his%20credentials%20and%20was%20using%20fictional%20data%22&f=false Elijah's Cup: A Family's Journey into the Community and Culture of High-Functioning Autism and Asperger's Syndrome, Revised Edition], Valerie Paradiz, Free Press, 2002; UK: Jessica Kingsley Publishers, 2005, pages 72-73: \"At the time, few people knew that Bettelheim had faked his credentials and was using fictional data to support his research. In 1944, with a forged resum\u00e9 that suggested a stellar academic career in psychoanalysis in Austria, Bettelheim had made his way into a post as the director of the Orthgenic School for Disturbed Children at the University of Chicago.\"</ref> [[Michael Rutter]] has observed, \"Many people made a mistake in going from a statement which is undoubtedly true\u2014that there is no evidence that autism has been caused by poor parenting\u2014to the statement that it has been disproven. It has not actually been disproven. It has faded away simply because, on the one hand, of a lack of convincing evidence and on the other hand, an awareness that autism was a neurodevelopmental disorder of some kind.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Feinstein|first=Adam|title=A History of Autism: Conversations with the Pioneers|year=2010|publisher=Blackwell's: Oxford, UK|page=68}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1997 review of two books on Bettelheim, Molly Finn wrote \"I am the mother of an autistic daughter, and have considered Bettelheim a charlatan since ''The Empty Fortress'', his celebrated study of autism, came out in 1967. I have nothing personal against Bettelheim, if it is not personal to resent being compared to a devouring witch, an infanticidal king, and an SS guard in a concentration camp, or to wonder what could be the basis of Bettelheim's statement that 'the precipitating factor in infantile autism is the parent's wish that his child should not exist.'\"<ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/>\n\nAlthough Bettelheim foreshadowed the modern interest in the causal influence of genetics in the section ''Parental Background,'' he consistently emphasised nurture over nature. For example: \"When at last the once totally frozen affects begin to emerge, and a much richer human personality to evolve, then convictions about the psychogenic nature of the disturbance become stronger still.\"; ''On Treatability,'' p.&nbsp;412. The rates of recovery claimed for the Orthogenic School are set out in ''Follow-up Data,'' with a recovery good enough to be considered a 'cure' of 43%., ps. 414\u2013415.\n\nSubsequently, medical research has provided greater understanding of the biological basis of autism and other illnesses. Scientists such as [[Bernard Rimland]] challenged Bettelheim's view of autism by arguing that autism is a [[Neural development|neurodevelopmental]] issue. As late as 2009, the \"refrigerator mother\" theory retained some prominent supporters,<ref name=\"SAJ\">{{cite book|last1=Severson|first1=Katherine DeMaria|last2=Aune|first2=James Arnt|last3=Jodlowski|first3=Denise|editor1-first=Mark|editor1-last=Osteen|title=Autism and Representation|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=188XgDxmdbEC&pg=PA65|accessdate=August 28, 2009|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|series=Routledge research in cultural and media studies|isbn=978-0-415-95644-4|pages=65\u201377|chapter=Bruno Bettelheim, Autism, and the Rhetoric of Scientific Authority}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Refrigerator mother' tosh must go into cold storage|author=Feinstein, Adam|publisher=autismconnect|url=http://autismconnect.org/news.asp?section=00010001&itemtype=adam&page=9&id=4540|accessdate=July 29, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927200621/http://autismconnect.org/news.asp?section=00010001&itemtype=adam&page=9&id=4540|archivedate=September 27, 2007}}\n</ref> including the prominent Irish psychologist [[Tony Humphreys]].<ref>\n{{cite news|author=Tony Humphreys|title=Core connection: A diagnosis of Asperger's syndrome does little to help a child troubled by unhappy relationships|work=Irish Examiner|date=February 3, 2012|page=7}}</ref> His theory still enjoys widespread support in France.<ref>{{cite web|last=Heurtevent|first=David|title=Introduction to Autism in France: A Really Silly Psychiatric System !|url=http://www.supportthewall.org/2012/01/introduction-to-autism-in-france-a-really-silly-psychiatric-system/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121220110003/http://www.supportthewall.org/2012/01/introduction-to-autism-in-france-a-really-silly-psychiatric-system/|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 20, 2012|work=Support The Wall \u2013 Autism|accessdate=February 25, 2012|date=January 2, 2012}}</ref>{{Dubious|date=November 2016}}\n\nIn his book ''Unstrange Minds'' (2007), Roy Richard Grinker wrote:{{Quote|\"Two other books on autism, published at about the same time [as Bettelheim's ''Empty Fortress'' (1967)], got little mention in the press: Bernard Rimland's ''Autism: The Syndrome and Its Implications for a Neural Theory of Behavior'' (1964), which outlined the biological and neurological aspects of autism, and Clara Clairborne Park's ''The Siege'' (1967), a beautifully written memoir of raising an autistic child.  Though they were more accurate depictions of autism, they couldn't compete with Bettelheim. He was simply too good a writer, and with his Viennese accent\u2014the sign of an authentic expert in psychology\u2014too good a self promoter.\"<ref name=\"Unstrange Minds, Roy Richard Grinker, 2007\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=1RICHy3FpYkC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=%22Two+other+books+on+autism,+published+at+about+the+same+time%22&source=bl&ots=5u04KY3hBM&sig=Xw3HnarRHFYiDzPoOX9j1T71oIQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjgray32qTeAhUKlawKHWXpB_YQ6AEwAHoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Two%20other%20books%20on%20autism%2C%20published%20at%20about%20the%20same%20time%22&f=false Unstrange Minds: Remapping the World of Autism: A Father, a Daughter, and a Search for New Answers], Finalist for the Victor Turner Prize for Ethnographic Writing, Roy Richard Grinker, New York: Basic Books (Perseus Books Group), 2007.</ref>}}\n\nJordynn Jack writes that Bettelheim's ideas gained currency and became popular in large part because society already tended to blame a mother first and foremost for her child's difficulties.<ref name=\"Autism and Gender, Jordynn Jack, 2014\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=DroPBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=%22The+commonplace+of+the+absent,+anxious,+or+cold+mother+became+a+heuristic%22&source=bl&ots=1C9dsLrgAg&sig=tXGsReHs0M8NTl1sFDyOvfDgvdc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiNxrik16TeAhVMY6wKHbKKCa4Q6AEwAHoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22The%20commonplace%20of%20the%20absent%2C%20anxious%2C%20or%20cold%20mother%20became%20a%20heuristic%22&f=false Autism and Gender: From Refrigerator Mothers to Computer Geeks], Jordynn Jack, University of Illinois Press, 2014.</ref>\n\n===Remarks about Jews and the Holocaust===\n\nBettelheim's experiences during the [[Holocaust]] shaped his personal and professional life for years after. His first publication was \"Individual and Mass Behavior in Extreme Situations\" derived from his experiences at [[Dachau]] and [[Buchenwald]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bettelheim |first1=Bruno |title=Individual and Mass Behavior in Extreme Situations |journal=Journal of Abnormal Psychology |date=1943 |volume=38 |issue=4 |pages=417\u2013452 |url=https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1944-00789-001 |language=en |doi=10.1037/h0061208}}</ref> His later work frequently compared emotionally disturbed childhood to prison or confinement, and according to Sutton, his professional work attempted to operationalize the lessons about human nature he learned during his confinement.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sutton |first1=Nina |title=Bettelheim: A Life and a Legacy |date=1997 |publisher=Westview Press |isbn=9780813390994 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBettelheim became one of the most prominent defenders of [[Hannah Arendt]]'s book ''[[Eichmann in Jerusalem]]''. He wrote a positive review for ''[[The New Republic]]''.<ref>\"The New Republic\", June 15, 1963</ref> This review prompted a letter from a writer, [[Harry Golden]], who alleged that both Bettelheim and Arendt suffered from \"an essentially Jewish phenomenon \u2026 self-hatred\".<ref>''The New Republic'', July 20, 1963</ref><ref>\"The Eichmann Polemics: Hannah Arendt and Her Critics\", Book Review in ''Democratiya'', Michael Ezra, London, 2007. {{cite web |url=http://www.democratiya.com/review.asp?reviews_id=102 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-20 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090120040641/http://www.democratiya.com/review.asp?reviews_id=102 |archivedate=January 20, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \n\nBettelheim would later speak critically of [[Jewish]] people who were killed during the [[Holocaust]]. He has been criticized for promoting the myth that Jews went \"[[like sheep to the slaughter]]\" and for blaming [[Anne Frank]] and her family for their own deaths due to not owning firearms, fleeing, or hiding more effectively.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tec |first1=Nechama |authorlink1=Nechama Tec |title=Did Jews Go Like Sheep to the Slaughter? |url=https://reformjudaismmag.org/past-issues/winter-2013/did-jews-go-like-sheep-to-slaughter |accessdate=5 December 2018 |work=Reform Judaism Magazine |date=Winter 2013 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Middleton-Kaplan |first1=Richard |editor1-last=Henry |editor1-first=Patrick |title=Jewish Resistance Against the Nazis |date=2014 |publisher=[[Catholic University of America Press]] |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=9780813225890 |page=10 |ref=harv |language=en |chapter=The Myth of Jewish Passivity}}</ref>  In an introduction he wrote to an account by [[Miklos Nyiszli]], Bettelheim stated, discussing Frank that \"Everybody who recognized the obvious knew that the hardest way to go underground was to do it as a family; that to hide as a family made detection by the SS most likely. The Franks, with their excellent connections among gentile Dutch families should have had an easy time hiding out singly, each with a different family. But instead of planning for this, the main principle of their planning was to continue as much as possible with the kind of family life they were accustomed to.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auschwitz: A Doctor's Eyewitness Account|last=Nyiszli|first=Miklos|publisher=Arcade Publishing|year=2011 |origyear=1960|isbn=978-1628729269|location=|pages=xiii}}</ref>\n\nRichard Pollak's biography, ''The Creation of Dr. B'', portrays Bettelheim as an anti-Semite even though he was raised in a secular Jewish household, and asserts that Bettelheim criticized in others the same cowardice he himself had displayed in the concentration camps.<ref name=\"LosAngeles-Times-1997-Book-Review-Howard-Gardner\"/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Major works by Bettelheim===\n*1943 \"Individual and Mass Behavior in Extreme Situations\", ''Journal of Abnormal and Social Psychology'', 38: 417\u2013452.\n*1950 Bettleheim, Bruno and Janowitz, Morris, ''Dynamics of Prejudice: A Psychological & Sociological Study of Veterans'', Harper & Bros.\n*1950 ''Love Is Not Enough: The Treatment of Emotionally Disturbed Children'', Free Press, Glencoe, Ill.\n*1954 ''Symbolic Wounds; Puberty Rites and the Envious Male'', Free Press, Glencoe, Ill.\n*1955 ''Truants From Life; The Rehabilitation of Emotionally Disturbed Children'', Free Press, Glencoe, Ill.\n*1959 \"Joey: A 'Mechanical Boy'\", ''Scientific American'', 200, March 1959: 117\u2013126. (About a boy who believes himself to be a robot.)\n*1960 ''The Informed Heart: Autonomy in a Mass Age'', The Free Press, Glencoe, Ill.\n*1962 ''Dialogues with Mothers'', The Free Press, Glencoe, Ill.\n*1967 ''The Empty Fortress: Infantile Autism and the Birth of the Self'', The Free Press, New York\n*1969 ''The Children of the Dream'', Macmillan, London & New York (About the raising of children in a [[kibbutz]] environment.)\n*1974 ''A Home for the Heart'', Knopf, New York. (About Bettelheim's Orthogenic School at the University of Chicago for schizophrenic and autistic children.)\n*1976 ''[[The Uses of Enchantment|The Uses of Enchantment: The Meaning and Importance of Fairy Tales]]'', Knopf, New York. {{ISBN|0-394-49771-6}}\n*1979 ''Surviving and Other Essays'', Knopf, New York (Includes the essay \"The Ignored Lesson of [[Anne Frank]]\".)\n*1982 ''On Learning to Read: The Child's Fascination with Meaning'' (with Karen Zelan), Knopf, New York\n*1982 ''Freud and Man's Soul'', Knopf, 1983, {{ISBN|0-394-52481-0}}\n*1987 ''A Good Enough Parent: A Book on Child-Rearing'', Knopf, New York\n*1990 ''Freud's Vienna and Other Essays'', Knopf, New York\n*1993, Bettelheim, Bruno and Rosenfeld, Alvin A, \"The Art of the Obvious\" Knopf.\n*1994 Bettelheim, Bruno & Ekstein, Rudolf: Grenzg\u00e4nge zwischen den Kulturen. ''Das letzte Gespr\u00e4ch zwischen Bruno Bettelheim und {{Interlanguage link multi|Rudolf Ekstein|de}}''. In: Kaufhold, Roland (ed.) (1994): ''Ann\u00e4herung an Bruno Bettelheim''. Mainz (Gr\u00fcnewald): 49\u201360.\n\n===Critical reviews of Bettelheim (works and person)===\n*Angres, Ronald: [https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/who-really-was-bruno-bettelheim/ \"Who, Really, Was Bruno Bettelheim?\"], personal essay, ''Commentary'', 90, (4), October 1990: 26\u201330.\n*Bernstein, Richard: [https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/04/weekinreview/ideas-trends-accusations-of-abuse-haunt-the-legacy-of-dr-bruno-bettelheim.html \"Accusations of Abuse Haunt the Legacy of Dr. Bruno Bettelheim\"], ''The New York Times'', November 4, 1990: \"The Week in Review\" section.\n*{{cite book|last=Bersihand|first=Genevi\u00e8ve|title=Bettelheim|trans-title=Bettelheim|year=1977|publisher=R. Jauze|location=Champigny-sur-Marne|language=|isbn=2-86214-001-5|pages=199}}\n*Dundes, Alan: [https://www.jstor.org/pss/541135 \"Bruno Bettelheim's Uses of Enchantment and Abuses of Scholarship\"]. ''The Journal of American Folklore'', Vol. 104, N0. 411. (Winter, 1991): 74\u201383.\n*Ekstein, Rudolf (1994): Mein Freund Bruno (1903\u20131990). Wie ich mich an ihn erinnere. In: Kaufhold, Roland (ed.) (1994): Ann\u00e4herung an Bruno Bettelheim. Mainz (Gr\u00fcnewald), S. 87\u201394.\n*Eliot, Stephen: ''Not the Thing I Was: Thirteen Years at Bruno Bettelheim's Orthogenic School'', St. Martin's Press, 2003.\n*Federn, Ernst (1994): Bruno Bettelheim und das \u00dcberleben im Konzentrationslager. In: Kaufhold, Roland (ed.) (1999): Ernst Federn: Versuche zur Psychologie des Terrors. Gie\u00dfen (Psychosozial-Verlag): 105\u2013108.\n*{{cite journal|journal=First Things|issue=74|pages=44\u20138|author=Finn M|title=In the case of Bruno Bettelheim|year=1997|url=http://www.firstthings.com/article.php3?id_article=3709}}\n*Fisher, David James: Psychoanalytische Kulturkritik und die Seele des Menschen. Essays \u00fcber Bruno Bettelheim (co-editor: Roland Kaufhold), Gie\u00dfen (Psychosozial-Verlag)\n*Fisher, David James: ''Bettelheim: Living and Dying'', Contemporary Psychoanalytic Studies, Amsterdam, New York: Brill/Rodopi, 2008.\n*Frattaroli, Elio: \"Bruno Bettelheim's Unrecognized Contribution to Psychoanalytic Thought\", ''Psychoanalytic Review'', 81:379\u2013409, 1994.\n*Heisig, James W.: \"Bruno Bettelheim and the Fairy Tales\", ''Children's Literature'', 6, 1977: 93\u2013115.\n*Kaufhold, Roland (ed.): Pioniere der psychoanalytischen P\u00e4dagogik: Bruno Bettelheim, Rudolf Ekstein, Ernst Federn und Siegfried Bernfeld, psychosozial Nr. 53 (1/1993)\n*Kaufhold, Roland (Ed.): Ann\u00e4herung an Bruno Bettelheim. Mainz, 1994 (Gr\u00fcnewald)\n*Kaufhold, Roland (1999): \"Falsche Fabeln vom Guru?\" Der \"Spiegel\" und sein M\u00e4rchen vom b\u00f6sen Juden Bruno Bettelheim, Behindertenp\u00e4dagogik, 38. Jhg., Heft 2/1999, S. 160\u2013187.\n*Kaufhold, Roland: Bettelheim, Ekstein, Federn: Impulse f\u00fcr die psychoanalytisch-p\u00e4dagogische Bewegung. Gie\u00dfen, 2001 (Psychosozial-Verlag).\n*Kaufhold, Roland/L\u00f6ffelholz, Michael (Ed.) (2003): \"So k\u00f6nnen sie nicht leben\" \u2013 Bruno Bettelheim (1903\u20131990). Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Politische Psychologie 1-3/2003.\n*Lyons, Tom W. (1983), ''The Pelican and After: A Novel about Emotional Disturbance'', Richmond, Virginia: Prescott, Durrell, and Company.  This is a roman \u00e0 clef novel in which the author lived at the Orthogenic School for almost twelve years.  The novel's head of the institution is a \"Dr. V.\"\n*Marcus, Paul: ''Autonomy in the Extreme Situation. Bruno Bettelheim, the Nazi Concentration Camps and the Mass Society'', Praeger, Westport, Conn., 1999.\n*[http://richardpollak.com/work3.htm Pollak, Richard]: ''The Creation of Dr. B: A Biography of Bruno Bettelheim'', Simon & Schuster, New York, 1997.\n*{{cite book|last=Raines|first=Theron|title=Rising to the light : a portrait of Bruno Bettelheim|edition=1|year=2002|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|location=New York|isbn=0-679-40196-2|url=https://archive.org/details/risingtolight00ther}}\n*Redford, Roberta Carly (2010) [https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11073285-crazy Crazy: My Seven Years At Bruno Bettelheim's Orthogenic School], Trafford Publishing, 364 pages.\n*Sutton, Nina: ''Bruno Bettelheim: The Other Side of Madness'', Duckworth Press, London, 1995. (Translated from the French by David Sharp in collaboration with the author. Subsequently, published with the title ''Bruno Bettelheim, a Life and a Legacy''.)\n*[[Jack Zipes|Zipes, Jack]]: \"On the Use and Abuse of Folk and Fairy Tales with Children: Bruno Bettelheim's Moralistic Magic Wand\", in Zipes, Jack: ''Breaking the Magic Spell: Radical Theories of Folk and Fairy Tales'', University of Texas Press, Austin, 1979.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://alexfiles.com/jinny.shtml Missing the Message: A Critique of Bettelheim's Analysis of ''The Jinny and the Fisherman'']\n*[http://www.suesske.de/kaufhold-1.htm Reviews of Dr. Roland Kaufhold's Bettelheim, Ekstein, Federn] (in German)\n*[http://www.suesske.de/buch_fisher.htm Thomas Aichhorn, ''Essays \u00fcber Bruno Bettelheim''] (in German)\n*{{IMDb name|id=0079291|name=Bruno Bettelheim}}\n*[http://www.edithbuxbaum.com/HamidaBosmajian.html The Edith Buxbaum Journal] by Roland Kaufhold\n*[http://www.ibe.unesco.org/fileadmin/user_upload/archive/publications/ThinkersPdf/bettelhe.pdf Bruno Bettelheim 1903\u20131990] Zehan, Karen, Prospects: the quarterly review of comparative education, UNESCO, 1993.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bettelheim, Bruno}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American psychologists]]\n[[Category:Austrian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish emigrants from Austria after the Anschluss]]\n[[Category:Autism researchers]]\n[[Category:Buchenwald concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:Child psychologists]]\n[[Category:Dachau concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:Fairy tale scholars]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Holocaust survivors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American social scientists]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:National Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:Jewish concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n[[Category:People involved in scientific misconduct incidents]]\n[[Category:Scientists who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Suicides by asphyxiation]]\n[[Category:Suicides in Maryland]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Vienna alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Austrian Jews]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Austrian-American child psychologist and writer}}\n<nowiki></nowiki>{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name=Bruno Bettelheim\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=Bruno Bettelheim\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1903|8|28}}\n|birth_place=[[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n|death_date={{Death date and age|1990|3|13|1903|8|28}}\n|death_place=[[Silver Spring, Maryland]], United States\n|residence=\n|citizenship=United States\n|nationality=Austrian\n|field=Director of Orthogenic School (1944\u20131973)\n|work_institutions=\n|alma_mater=\n|doctoral_advisor=\n|doctoral_students=[[Benjamin Drake Wright]]\n|known_for=[[child psychology]]; <br>[[Autism]]; <br>''[[The Uses of Enchantment]]''\n|influences=\n|influenced=\n|prizes=\n|religion=\n|footnotes=\n|signature=\n|spouse=Gina Alstadt (1930\u2013?; divorced)<br>Gertrude Weinfeld (1941\u20131984; her death; 3 children)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=6VIYAAAAIAAJ&q=Gertrude+Weinfeld+Bettelheim&dq=Gertrude+Weinfeld+Bettelheim|title=The Annual Obituary|publisher=|last1=Andrews|first1=Deborah|last2=Turner|first2=Roland|year=1990|isbn=9781558620926}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Bruno Bettelheim''' (August 28, 1903 \u2013 March 13, 1990) was an [[Austria|Austrian-born]] [[psychologist]], [[scholar]], [[public intellectual]] and author who spent most of his academic and clinical career in the United States. An early writer on [[autism]], Bettelheim's work focused on the education of [[Emotional and behavioral disorders|emotionally disturbed]] children, as well as Freudian psychology more generally. In the U.S., he later gained a position as professor at the [[University of Chicago]] and director of the [[Sonia Shankman Orthogenic School|Sonia Shankman Orthogenic School for Disturbed Children]], and after 1973 taught at [[Stanford University]].<ref name=\"Biographical Dictionary of American Educators, 1978\"/> \n\nBettelheim's ideas, which grew out of [[Freud's psychoanalytic theories|those of Sigmund Freud]], theorized that children with behavioral and emotional disorders were not born that way, and could be treated through extended psychoanalytic therapy, treatment that rejected the use of [[psychotropic drugs]] and [[Shock therapy (psychiatry)|shock therapy]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-03-14-9001210549-story.html |title=Dr. Bruno Bettleheim, child psychology expert |last=Fountain |first=John W. |date=March 14, 1990 |work=Chicago Tribune |access-date=2019-05-12 |language=en-US}}</ref> During the 1960s and 1970s he had an international reputation in such fields as autism, [[Child and adolescent psychiatry|child psychiatry]], and [[psychoanalysis]].<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/><ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\"/> \n\nMuch of his work was discredited after his death due to fraudulent academic credentials, allegations of abusive treatment of patients under his care,  accusations of [[plagiarism]], and lack of oversight by institutions and psychological community.  \n\n==Background in Austria==\nBruno Bettelheim was born in [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]], on August 28, 1903. When his father died, Bettelheim left his studies at the [[University of Vienna]] to look after his family's sawmill. Having discharged his obligations to his family's business, Bettelheim returned as a mature student in his thirties to the University of Vienna.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Sources disagree about his education (see section [[Bruno_Bettelheim#Misrepresented_credentials|Misrepresented credentials]]).\n\nBettelheim's first wife, Gina, took care of a troubled American child, Patsy, who lived in their home in Vienna for seven years, and who may or may not have been on the autism spectrum.<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-02-23/entertainment/9702230083_1_bruno-bettelheim-orthogenic-school-richard-pollak Biography As Revenge], ''Chicago Tribune'', Marie Winn (who writes regularly for ''The Wall Street Journal's'' Leisure & Arts Page), Feb. 23, 1997.  \"  .  .  He was familiar with this disease because his first wife, Gina, had cared for an autistic child in their home for several years.  .  \"</ref><ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/><ref name=\"Weekly-Standard-1997\"/>\n\nIn the Austrian academic culture of Bettelheim's time, one could not study the history of art without mastering aspects of [[psychology]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} Candidates for the doctoral dissertation in the History of Art in 1938 at Vienna University had to fulfill prerequisites in the formal study of the role of [[Archetypes#Jungian archetypes|Jungian archetypes]] in art, and in art as an expression of the unconscious.\n\nThough Jewish by birth, Bettelheim grew up in a secular family. After the [[Nazi]] invasion and ''[[Anschluss]]'' (political annexation) of [[Austria]] on March 12, 1938, the Nazi authorities sent Bettelheim, other [[Austrian Jews]] and political opponents to the [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] and [[Buchenwald]] [[concentration camp]]s where they were brutally treated, and tortured or killed. Bettelheim was arrested on May 28, 1938 and was imprisoned in both these camps for ten and half months before being released on April 14, 1939.<ref name=\"NeuroTribes, Silberman, pages 202-03, Bettelheim's 10 and a 1/2 months in Dachau and Buchenwald\">''NeuroTribes: The Legacy of Autism and the Future of Neurodiversity'', Steve Silberman, Foreword by Oliver Sacks, Penguin Random House, 2015, [https://books.google.com/books?id=w3XoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT128&lpg=PT128&dq=%22On+May+28,+1938,+policemen+acting+on+orders+from+Berlin+arrived+at+Bettelheim's+door%22&source=bl&ots=qC4YMwdm-p&sig=ooaToQPrzuTq5LAv-3wP2w5wKr0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiW1-vQq8XTAhVFOhQKHQXwA8oQ6AEIIjAA#v=onepage&q=%22On%20May%2028%2C%201938%2C%20policemen%20acting%20on%20orders%20from%20Berlin%20arrived%20at%20Bettelheim's%20door%22&f=false pages 202-203].</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=rgGA91skoP4C&pg=PA39&lpg=PA39&dq=bettelheim+released+Nazis&source=bl&ots=S9ohBY_Twz&sig=mWk4HLedB4J3Xd_SFXXk99AtEQM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjxyoTV_qzUAhUL64MKHUVaAtIQ6AEIUDAJ#v=onepage&q=bettelheim%20released%20Nazis&f=false Dictionary of Genocide, Volume 1: A\u2013L], \"Bettelheim, Bruno (1903\u20131990),\" Samuel Totten, Paul R. Bartrop, with contributions by Steven Leonard Jacobs, Westport, Connecticut, U.S. and London, UK: Greenwood Publishing Group, 2008.</ref> While at the Buchenwald camp, he met and befriended the social psychologist [[Ernst Federn]]. As a result of an amnesty declared for [[Adolf Hitler]]'s birthday (which occurred slightly later on April 20, 1939), Bettelheim and hundreds of other prisoners were released. Bettelheim drew on the experience of the concentration camps for some of his later work.\n\n==Life and career in the United States==\nBettelheim arrived by ship as a refugee in New York City in late 1939 to join his wife Gina, who had already emigrated. They divorced because she had become involved with someone else during their separation.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} He soon moved to Chicago, became a naturalized U.S. citizen in 1944, and married an Austrian woman, Gertrude ('Trudi') Weinfeld, also an emigrant from Vienna.\n\n===Psychology===\nThe [[Rockefeller Foundation]] sponsored a wartime project to help resettle European scholars by circulating their resumes to American universities.  Through this process, Ralph Tyler hired Bettelheim to be his research assistant at the University of Chicago from 1939-1941 with funding from the [[Progressive Education Association]] to evaluate how high schools taught art. Once this funding ran out, Bettelheim found a job at Rockford College, Illinois, where he taught from 1942-1944.<ref name=\"Biographical Dictionary of American Educators, 1978\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=Z5YNz-kNZgsC&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&dq=Bettelheim+%22Progressive+Education+Association%22&source=bl&ots=_3BXp8Jzlq&sig=18cw_k46fLQgTtY-smixWcAQLiM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5_bqLrsbXAhXBYiYKHUBEAIAQ6AEIKzAB#v=onepage&q=Bettelheim%20%22Progressive%20Education%20Association%22&f=false Biographical Dictionary of American Educators, Vol. 1]\nedited by John F. Ohles, London, England and Westport, Connecticut: Greenwood Press, 1978.</ref><ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\"/><ref name=\"How Ralph W. Tyler Taught America to Teach, 2004\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ckIaTAr5yMkC&pg=PA41&lpg=PA41&dq=%22was+at+the+time+seeking+a+specialist+to+assess+art+appreciation%22&source=bl&ots=veq8m6hckb&sig=coaCMqgmt3l7Z91Sdc-rfTBiKLg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja6OH80ozYAhXC4yYKHUc_DuIQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=%22was%20at%20the%20time%20seeking%20a%20specialist%20to%20assess%20art%20appreciation%22&f=false Educating America: How Ralph W. Tyler Taught America to Teach], Morris Finder, Foreword by Henry Louis Gates, Jr., Westport, Connecticut, London: Praeger, 2004, page 41.</ref>\n\nIn 1943, he published the paper \"Individual and Mass Behavior in Extreme Situations\" about his experiences in the concentration camps, a paper which was highly regarded by Dwight Eisenhower among others.<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/>  Bettelheim claimed he had interviewed 1,500 fellow prisoners, although this was unlikely.<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/><ref name=\"NeuroTribes, Steve Silberman, 2015\">''NeuroTribes'', Silberman, 2015, [https://books.google.com/books?id=w3XoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT129&dq=%22exactly+the+person+we+need+for+psychoanalysis+to+grow+and+develop%22+intitle:NeuroTribes&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJ2abc87jTAhUHthQKHUTuBYsQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=%22exactly%20the%20person%20we%20need%20for%20psychoanalysis%20to%20grow%20and%20develop%22%20intitle%3ANeuroTribes&f=false pages 199-208].  \"  .  .  (The closest he ever came to meeting Freud was walking past his house.)  .  .  \"</ref> He stated that the Viennese psychoanalyst [[Richard Sterba]] had analyzed him, as well as implying in several of his writings that he had written a PhD dissertation in the philosophy of education. His actual PhD was in art history, and he had only taken three introductory courses in psychology.<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-January-23-1997\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-01-23/features/9701230196_1_orthogenic-school-bruno-bettelheim-pollak Genius Or Fraud? Bettelheim's Biographers Can't Seem To Decide], ''Chicago Tribune'', Ron Grossman, January 23, 1997, page 2: \" . . . he evidently gambled that because of the war no one would be able to check on his credentials. . . \"</ref>\n\nThrough Ralph Tyler's recommendation, the [[University of Chicago]] appointed Bettelheim as a professor of psychology, as well as director of the [[Sonia Shankman Orthogenic School]] for emotionally disturbed children.<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\"/>  He held both positions from 1944 until his retirement in 1973. He wrote a number of books on psychology and, for a time, had an international reputation for his work on [[Sigmund Freud]], [[psychoanalysis]], and [[Serious emotional disturbance|emotionally disturbed]] children.  \n\nAt the Orthogenic School, Bettelheim made changes and set up an environment for [[milieu therapy]], in which children could form strong attachments with adults within a structured but caring environment. He claimed considerable success in treating some of the emotionally disturbed children. He wrote books on both normal and abnormal [[child psychology]], and became a major influence in the field, widely respected during his lifetime. He was noted for his study of [[Feral child|feral children]], who revert to the animal stage without experiencing the benefits of belonging to a community.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Poplau|first=Ronald W.|title=A Living Classroom: Ideas for Student Creativity and Community Service|date=2018|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=|isbn=978-1-4758-4854-0|location=Lanham, MD|pages=74}}</ref> He discussed this phenomenon in the book ''The Informed Heart''.<ref name=\":0\" /> Even critics agree that, in his practice, Bettelheim was dedicated to helping these children using methods and practices that would enable them to lead happy lives.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Zipes|first=Jack|title=Breaking the Magic Spell: Radical Theories of Folk and Fairy Tales|date=2002|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|year=|isbn=0-8131-9030-4|location=Lexington|pages=179}}</ref> It is based on his position that psychotherapy could change humans and that they can adapt to their environment provided they are given proper care and attention.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBettelheim was elected a Fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1971.<ref name=\"AAAS\">{{cite web|title=Book of Members, 1780\u20132010: Chapter B|url=http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterB.pdf|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=June 24, 2011}}</ref>  After retiring in 1973, he and his wife moved to [[Portola Valley, California]], where he continued to write and taught at [[Stanford University]].  His wife died in 1984.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=msgABAAAQBAJ&pg=PA38&lpg=PA38&dq=bettelheim+retired+1973#v=onepage&q=bettelheim%2520retired%25201973&f=false |title=The Fame Lunches: On Wounded Icons, Money, Sex, the Bront\u00ebs, and the Importance of Handbags |last=Merkin |first=Daphne |date=2014-09-02 |publisher=Macmillan |isbn=9780374140373 |pages=38 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===''The Uses of Enchantment''===\nBettelheim analyzed [[fairy tale]]s in terms of Freudian psychology in ''[[The Uses of Enchantment]]'' (1976). He discussed the emotional and symbolic importance of [[fairy tale]]s for children, including traditional tales at one time{{Clarify|date=March 2012}}<!-- i suspect IN HIS TIME but i don't know --> considered too dark, such as those collected and published by the [[Brothers Grimm]]. Bettelheim suggested that traditional fairy tales, with the darkness of abandonment, death, witches, and injuries, allowed children to grapple with their fears in remote, symbolic terms. If they could read and interpret these fairy tales in their own way, he believed, they would get a greater sense of meaning and purpose. Bettelheim thought that by engaging with these [[social evolution|socially evolved]] stories, children would go through emotional growth that would better prepare them for their own futures. In the United States, Bettelheim won two major awards for ''The Uses of Enchantment'': the [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] for Criticism<ref name=nbcc>[http://bookcritics.org/awards/past_awards/#1976 \"All Past National Book Critics Circle Award Winners and Finalists\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604095541/http://bookcritics.org/awards/past_awards/#1976 |date=June 4, 2019 }}. [[National Book Critics Circle]]. Retrieved 2019-05-09.</ref>\nand the [[National Book Award]] in the category of [[List of winners of the National Book Award#Current|Contemporary Thought]].<ref name=nba1977>\n[https://www.nationalbook.org/awards-prizes/national-book-awards-1977/?cat=translation&sub-cat=contemporary-thought \"National Book Awards \u2013 1977\"]. [[National Book Foundation]]. Retrieved 2019-05-09. <br/>There was a \"Contemporary\" or \"Current\" award category from 1972 to 1980.</ref>\n\n===Death===\nAt the end of his life, Bettelheim suffered from depression. He appeared to have had difficulties with depression for much of his life.<ref name=\"nybooks.com\">[http://www.nybooks.com/articles/16083 Robert Gottlieb, \"The Strange Case of Dr. B.\", The New York ''Review of Books'', 27 Feb 2003]. Retrieved 2008-04-15.</ref> In 1990, widowed, in failing physical health, and suffering from the effects of a stroke which impaired his mental abilities and paralyzed part of his body, he committed suicide as a result of self-induced [[asphyxiation]] by placing a plastic bag over his head.<ref name=\"SAJ\"/><ref name=Suicidelaterlife>{{Cite book|last=Osgood|first=Nancy J.|publication-date=1992|title=Suicide in later life|page=4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=K202uE6QiDUC&lpg=PA4&vq=bruno&pg=PA4#v=snippet&q=bruno|accessdate=January 29, 2010|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-669-21214-3|date=July 1992}}</ref> He died on March 13, 1990, in Maryland.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-03-14/news/9001210549_1_sonia-shankman-orthogenic-school-jacquelyn-sanders-dr-Bettelheim Dr. Bruno Bettelheim, Child Psychology Expert], ''Chicago Tribune'', John W. Fountain, March 14, 1990.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nBettelheim was a [[public intellectual]], whose writing and many public appearances in popular media paralleled a growing post WWII interest in [[psychoanalysis]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Silverman |first1=Chloe |title=From Disorders of Affect to Mindblindness: Framing the History of Autism Spectrum Disorders \" |url=https://case.edu/affil/sce/Texts_2005/Autism%20and%20Representation%20Silverman.htm |website=The Society for Critical Exchange |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> For instance, he appeared multiple times on [[The Dick Cavett Show]] in the 70s to discuss theories of [[autism]] and psychoanalysis. <ref>{{cite web |title=The Dick Cavett Show - Guests |url=https://dickcavettshow.com/index.php/guests |website=dickcavettshow.com |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> Pollak's biography argues that such popular appearances shielded Bettelheim's unethical behavior from scrutiny.<ref name=\"Chicago Reader, review of Richard Pollak's The Creation of Dr. B, 1997\">[https://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/in-print-the-abominable-dr-bettelheim/Content?oid=892495 In Print: the abominable Dr. Bettelheim], ''Chicago Reader'', Cara Jepsen, Jan. 16, 1997.</ref>\n\nIn 1974, a four-part series featuring Bruno Bettelheim and directed by Daniel Carlin appeared on French television \u2014 ''Portrait de Bruno Bettelheim''.{{fact|date=March 2019}}\n\n[[Woody Allen]] included Bettelheim as himself in a cameo in the film ''[[Zelig]]'' (1983).{{fact|date=March 2019}}\n\nA [[BBC]] ''[[Horizon (BBC TV series)|Horizon]]'' documentary about Bettelheim was televised in 1987.<ref>{{cite web |title=Horizon - BBC Two England - 2 February 1987 |url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/157067cd458c4728bd2d46cf79bf8de2 |website=BBC Genome |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n<!--- [Does Kellerman state this clearly in his book, and if so where (Foreword, or Afterword, notes)? Please supply exact references, otherwise cannot be left here: libelous] --- Bettelheim and the controversy that arose after his death appeared to influence the character of Dr. Andres de Bosch in [[Jonathan Kellerman]]'s mystery ''Bad Love''. De Bosch is portrayed as a child psychiatrist who espouses great humanitarian ideals, while practicing bigotry, class prejudice and cruelty. In his life he is lionized for the man he seems to be, but after his death he is exposed as a tyrant and a fraud. --->\n\n==Controversies==\nBettelheim's life and work have come under increasing scrutiny since his death. \n\n===Misrepresented credentials===\n\nThough he spent most of his life working in psychology and psychiatry, Bettelheim's educational background in those fields is murky at best. Sources disagree whether Bettelheim's PhD was in art history<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beck |first1=Joan |title=SETTING THE RECORD STRAIGHT ABOUT A 'FALLEN GURU' |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1997-04-03-9704030057-story.html |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=chicagotribune.com |date=1997}}</ref> <ref name=\"Baltimore-Sun-Paul-McHugh-January-19-1997\">[http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1997-01-19/news/1997019010_1_bruno-bettelheim-richard-pollak-orthogenic-school Bruno Bettelheim: a cautionary life], ''Baltimore Sun'', Paul R. McHugh, Jan. 19, 1997.</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=McHugh |first1=Paul R. |title=Bruno Bettelheim: a cautionary life |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1997-01-19-1997019010-story.html |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=baltimoresun.com |date=1997}}</ref> or in philosophy (aesthetics).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Winn |first1=Marie |title=BIOGRAPHY AS REVENGE. |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1997-02-23-9702230083-story.html |work=chicagotribune.com |date=1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lehmann-Haupt |first1=Christopher |title=An Icon of Psychology Falls From His Pedestal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/13/books/an-icon-of-psychology-falls-from-his-pedestal.html |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=13 January 1997}}</ref> When he was hired at the University of Chicago, [[Ralph W. Tyler| Ralph Tyler]] assumed that he had two PhDs, one in art history and the other in psychology.<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-11-11/features/9004030282_1_bruno-bettelheim-sonia-shankman-orthogenic-school-animal-terrorSolving The Puzzle That Was Bruno Bettelheim], ''Chicago Tribune'', Ron Grossman, November 11, 1990.</ref> He also believed, falsely, that Bettelheim was certified to conduct [[Psychoanalysis]] though Bettelheim never received such certification. <ref name=\"How Ralph W. Tyler Taught America to Teach, 2004\"/> A posthumous review of his transcript showed that Bettelheim had only taken three introductory classes in psychology. Bertram Cohler and Jacquelyn Sanders at the Orthogenic School believed Bettelheim had a PhD in art history.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grossman |first1=Ron |title=SOLVING THE PUZZLE THAT WAS BRUNO BETTELHEIM |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-11-11-9004030282-story.html |work=chicagotribune.com}}</ref> In some of his own writings, Bettelheim implied that he had written a dissertation on the philosophy of education.{{Citation Needed|date=May 2019}} \n\nDetermining Bettelheim's education is complicated by the fact that he routinely embellished or inflated aspects of his own biography. As an example, Bettelheim's first wife, Gina, took care of a troubled American child, Patsy, who lived in their home in Vienna for seven years. Although Bettelheim later claimed he himself had taken care of the child, there is general agreement that his wife actually provided most of the child care.<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997/><ref name=\"NeuroTribes, Silberman, Bettelheim's first wife Gina taking care of Patsy\"/>  There is disagreement, however, among sources regarding whether or not Patsy was autistic.<ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/><ref name=\"Weekly-Standard-1997\"/>  Bettelheim later claimed that it was Patsy who inspired him to study autism<ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/> and embellished her into two or even several autistic children in his home.<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/><ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997/><ref name=\"NeuroTribes, Silberman, Bettelheim's first wife Gina taking care of Patsy\">''NeuroTribes'', Steve Silberman, 2015, See [https://books.google.com/books?id=WRpPDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA201&lpg=PA201&dq=%22she+ended+up+taking+Patsy+into+the+household%22&source=bl&ots=QxQU-zDufa&sig=ACfU3U2AAURCnY7IyeWTfNCoudi8rvlMwA&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj7wIqQs_XnAhVnFTQIHRAUCVsQ6AEwAHoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22she%20ended%20up%20taking%20Patsy%20into%20the%20household%22&f=false pages 201 and 201] for Bettelheim's wife actually taking care of Patsy, who may or may not have been on the autism spectrum, and see [https://books.google.com/books?id=WRpPDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA203&lpg=PA203&dq=%22over+the+years+she+would+morph+into+several+autistic+children%22&source=bl&ots=QxQU-zDtlb&sig=ACfU3U3kl3Jp_kjvmLBgxPb3CctpFK9iIg&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjMweX9svXnAhUXJzQIHaWNCKgQ6AEwAHoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22over%20the%20years%20she%20would%20morph%20into%20several%20autistic%20children%22&f=false last paragraph of page 203] for Bettelheim later exaggerating her into several children.</ref>\n\nAdditionally, when he applied for a position at [[Rockford College]] in Illinois, he claimed in a r\u00e9sum\u00e9 that he had earned summa cum laude doctorates in philosophy, art history, and psychology, and he made such claims that he had run the art department at Lower Austria's library, that he had published two books on art, that he had excavated Roman antiquities, and that he had engaged in music studies with [[Arnold Schoenberg]].  When he applied at the University of Chicago for a professorship and as director of the Orthogenic School, he further claimed that he had training in psychology, experience raising autistic children, and personal encouragement from Sigmund Freud.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beck |first1=Joan |title=SETTING THE RECORD STRAIGHT ABOUT A 'FALLEN GURU' |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1997-04-03-9704030057-story.html |accessdate=7 May 2019 |work=chicagotribune.com}}</ref> Posthumous biographies of Bettelheim have investigated these claims and came to no clear conclusions about his credentials<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sutton |first1=Nina |title=Bettelheim, a life and a legacy |date=1997 |publisher=WestView Press |isbn=0813390990 |edition=Pbk.}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book|last=Pollak|first=Richard|title=The creation of Dr. B: A biography of Bruno Bettelheim|url=https://books.google.com/?id=VklXDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT4&lpg=PT4&dq=%22Chapter+Six:++The+Orthogenic+School%22#v=onepage&q=%22Chapter%20Six%3A%20%20The%20Orthogenic%20School%22&f=false|year=1997|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=0-684-80938-9|pages=478}}</ref> A review in ''The Independent'' (UK) of Sutton's book stated that Bettelheim \"despite claims to the contrary, possessed no psychology qualifications of any sort.\"<ref name=The-Independent-December-9-1995>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/turbulent-dreams-of-a-damaged-saint-1524787.html Turbulent dreams of a damaged saint], ''The Independent'' [UK], Nicholas Tucker (review of ''Bruno Bettelheim: A Life and a Legacy'' by Nina Sutton), 8 December 1995.</ref>  A review of Pollak's book in ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated \"when all is said and done, Bettelheim seems to have re-enacted the archetypal American success story of inventing a false past, concocting a new formula for snake oil and selling it to the public with flummery. Under Mr. Pollak's magnifying glass, Bettelheim is seen in a new, harsh light, and stands exposed as a brilliant charlatan.\"<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Book-Review-January-13-1997\"/>  Another review in ''The New York Times'' by a different reviewer stated that Bettelheim \"began inventing degrees he never earned.\"<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/>  A review in the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' stated \"as Pollak demonstrates, Bettelheim was a snake-oil salesman of the first magnitude.\"<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997/>\n\n<ref name=\"LosAngeles-Times-1997-Book-Review-Howard-Gardner\"/><ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/>  In the ''[[New York Review of Books]]'', Robert Gottlieb describes Pollak as a \"relentlessly negative biographer,\" but Gottlieb still writes, \"The accusations against Bettelheim fall into several categories. First, he lied; that is, he both exaggerated his successes at the school and falsified aspects of his background, claiming a more elaborate academic and psychoanalytic history in Vienna than he had actually had. There is conclusive evidence to support both charges.\"  Gottlieb goes on to say that Bettelheim arrived in the United States as a Holocaust survivor and refugee without a job nor even a profession, and writes, \"I suspect he said what he thought it was necessary to say, and was then stuck with these claims later on, when he could neither confirm them (since they were false) nor, given his pride, acknowledge that he had lied.\"  This is Robert Gottlieb's judgment call for why Bettelheim lied.<ref name=\"nybooks.com\"/>\n\nIn a 1997 ''[[Weekly Standard]]'' article Peter Kramer, clinical professor of psychiatry at Brown University, summarized: \"There were snatches of truth in the tall tale, but not many. Bettelheim had earned a non-honors degree in philosophy, he had made acquaintances in the psychoanalytic community, and his first wife had helped raise a troubled child. But, from 1926 to 1938, -- the bulk of the '14 years' at university -- Bettelheim had worked as a lumber dealer in the family business.\"<ref name=\"Weekly-Standard-1997\">[http://www.weeklystandard.com/the-battle-over-bettelheim/article/9267 THE BATTLE OVER BETTELHEIM], ''Weekly Standard'', Peter D. Kramer, April 7, 1997.</ref>\n\nIn his 1997 review of Pollak's book in the ''Baltimore Sun'', [[Paul R. McHugh]], then director of Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences at Johns Hopkins, stated \"Bettelheim \u2013 with boldness, energy and luck \u2013 exploited American deference to Freudo-Nietzschean mind-sets and interpretation, especially when intoned in accents Viennese.\"<ref name=\"Baltimore-Sun-Paul-McHugh-January-19-1997\"/>\n\n===Plagiarism in Bettelheim's ''Uses of Enchantment''===\nWithin a year of Bettelheim's death, an article by [[Alan Dundes]] about [[The Uses of Enchantment]] appeared in the winter 1991 edition of ''The Journal of American Folklore'' which presented a case that Bettelheim had engaged in [[plagiarism]].<ref name=\"Journal-of-American-Folklore-Winter-1991\">Dundes, Alan: [https://www.jstor.org/pss/541135 \"Bruno Bettelheim's Uses of Enchantment and Abuses of Scholarship\"]. ''The Journal of American Folklore'', Vol. 104, N0. 411. (Winter, 1991): pages 74\u201383.</ref>  Dundes argued that Bettelheim had borrowed without acknowledgement from a number of sources, including  Dundes' own 1967 paper on Cinderella and from Dr. Julius E. Heuscher's book ''A Psychiatric Study of Fairy Tales'' published in 1963.<ref name=\"A-Psychiatric-Study-Of-Fairy-Tales-Julius-Heuscher\">[http://iucat.iu.edu/iub/2289829 A Psychiatric Study of Fairy Tales: Their Origin, Meaning and Usefulness] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026002751/http://iucat.iu.edu/iub/2289829 |date=October 26, 2016 }}, Julius E. Heuscher, illus. by Melba Bennett, Springfield, Illinois: Thomas pub., 1963, 224 pages. See also [https://books.google.com/books?id=QUMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA2313&lpg=PA2313&dq=%22A+psychiatric+study+of+fairy+tales%22+revised&source=bl&ots=ItgqMsBCNH&sig=brUePMQAfpJuPYV9HlNr4ON_pN4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiMxfe9tvbPAhVkxYMKHbaiBGEQ6AEINzAF#v=onepage&q=%22A%20psychiatric%20study%20of%20fairy%20tales%22%20revised&f=false A Psychiatric Study of Fairy Tales: Their Origin, Meaning and Usefulness; an enlarged and thoroughly revised second edition], Julius E. Heuscher, Springfield, Illinois: Charles C. Thomas, publisher, April 1974, 422 pages.</ref>  In part because of the widespread popularity of ''The Uses of Enchantment'' and Bettelheim's prominence, this academic controversy was discussed in print media and both Dundes and Heuscher spoke publicly about it.<ref name=\"Los-Angeles-Times-February-7-1991\">[https://articles.latimes.com/1991-02-07/news/mn-1024_1_fairy-tales Bettelheim Plagiarized Book Ideas, Scholar Says : Authors: The late child psychologist is accused of 'wholesale borrowing' for study of fairy tales], ''Los Angeles Times'', Anne C. Roark, Feb. 7, 1991.  This article includes a contrast-and-compare between a passage from Bettelheim and a passage from Julius Heuscher's previous book.</ref><ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/><ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-February-7-1991\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-02-07/news/9101110905_1_dundes-article-sonia-shankman-orthogenic-school-bruno-bettelheim Bettelheim Accused Of Plagiarizing Book], ''Chicago Tribune'', Sharman Stein, February 7, 1991.</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, Jacquelyn Sanders, who worked with Bettelheim and later became director of the Orthogenic School, stated that she had read Dundes' article but didn't believe many people would agree with his conclusions. She said, \"I would not call that plagiarism. I think the article is a reasonable scholarly endeavor, and calling it scholarly etiquette is appropriate. It is appropriate that this man deserved to be acknowledged and Bettelheim didn't... But I would not fail a student for doing that, and I don`t know anybody who would\".<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-February-7-1991\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-02-07/news/9101110905_1_dundes-article-sonia-shankman-orthogenic-school-bruno-bettelheim Bettelheim Accused Of Plagiarizing Book], ''Chicago Tribune'', Sharman Stein, February 7, 1991.</ref>\n\n===Abusive treatment of students===\n\nThere is some disagreement as to whether Bettelheim's use of [[corporal punishment]] rose to the level of abuse or was in keeping with the standards of his time. Some staff who worked at the Orthogenic School have spoken out that they saw Bettelheim's behavior as being corporal punishment, but not abuse.<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\"/><ref name=\"Chicago-Reader-Alida-Jatich-two-letters-1990-and-1991\"/><ref name=Washington-Post-Charles-Pekow-August-26-1990>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1990/08/26/the-other-dr-bettleheim/3d938d77-08f3-430a-98f9-dac1fb7b6fd9/ The Other Dr. Bettelheim], ''The Washington Post'', Charles Pekow, Editorial, Aug. 26, 1990.  \"  .  .  we could never tell when he would attack us for any arbitrary reason.  .  \"  See [https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1990/09/06/the-other-dr-bettelheim/0085be31-5f12-4ae8-9ebd-79cc29ecd4c0/ 'The Other Dr. Bettelheim'], Sept. 6, 1990, and [https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1990/10/06/the-bettelheim-we-knew-contd/3c8f4801-9e96-4a86-9f41-11d2ced99a06/ The Bettelheim We Know (Cont'd.)], Oct. 6, 1990, for the contrasting views of some counselors.</ref><ref name=\"Commentary-Magazine-Ron-Angres-October-1990\">Angres, Ronald: [https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/who-really-was-bruno-bettelheim/ \"Who, Really, Was Bruno Bettelheim?\"], personal essay, Commentary, 90, (4), October 1, 1990: 26\u201330.</ref> As an example, David Zwerdling, who was a counselor at the school for one year in 1969-70, wrote a Sept. 1990 response to ''The Washington Post'' in which he stated, \"I witnessed one occasion when an adolescent boy cursed at a female counselor. Incensed upon learning of this, Dr. Bettelheim proceeded to slap the boy two or three times across the face, while telling him sternly never to speak that way to a woman again. This was the only such incident I observed or heard of during my year at the school...until fairly recently, the near-consensus against corporal punishment in schools did not obtain.\"  However, Zwerdling also noted, \"He also was a man who, for whatever reasons, was capable of intense anger on occasion.\"<ref name=Washington-Post-Charles-Pekow-August-26-1990/>\n\nConversely, many students and staff at the school have argued that Bettelheim was abusive, violent, and cruel to them and to others. There are multiple newspaper accounts of abuse, in letters,<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Alida-Jatich-A-Personal-View-1990>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-10-29/news/9003300393_1_bruno-bettelheim-orthogenic-school-autistic A Personal View Of Bruno Bettelheim], ''Chicago Tribune'', Alida Jatich, Oct. 29, 1990.  '  .  .  Whenever Bettelheim called a young person ``autistic`` or ``psychotic`` or ``homicidal`` or ``suicidal`` or anything else, the staff believed him regardless of all evidence to the contrary. To them, the truth was whatever Bettelheim said it was, and their job was to get me and the other youngsters to accept it.  .  '</ref><ref>''Chicago Reader'', Letters to the Editor, [http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/the-cult-of-bettelheim/Content?oid=3835176 The Cult of Bettelheim], \"By WB A former counselor,\" July 5, 1990.</ref><ref name=Letter-to-the-Editor-Roberta-Redford-1990>[https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/20/opinion/l-bettelheim-became-the-very-evil-he-loathed-870890.html Letter to the Editor], ''The New York Times'', 'Bettelheim Became the Very Evil He Loathed,' Roberta Redford, Nov. 20, 1990 (written Nov. 9).  \"  .  .  I would like to believe that at the beginning his motives were pure. By the time I knew him, he was a megalomaniac, twisted and out of control. We were terrified of him, and lived for those days when he was out of town.  .  \"</ref><ref name=Washington-Post-Charles-Pekow-August-26-1990/><ref name=\"Chicago-Reader-Alida-Jatich-two-letters-1990-and-1991\">''Chicago Reader'', Letters to the Editor, [http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/brutal-bettelheim/Content?oid=875450 Brutal Bettelheim], Name Withheld, April 5, 1990. And, [http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/the-monster-of-the-midway/Content?oid=877368 The Monster of the Midway], Alida Jatich, April 4, 1991. The author lived at the \"Orthogenic School\" from 1966-1972, and in her second letter, she acknowledged authorship of the first.</ref> editorials<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Joan-Beck-October-1-1990>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-10-01/news/9003220135_1_orthogenic-school-bruno-bettelheim-animal-terror Bettelheim Led Us Cruelly Down Wrong Road For Children], ''Chicago Tribune'', Joan Beck, Editorial, Oct. 1, 1990.  \"  .  .  .  But autism is almost certainly caused by a genetic defect, not a cold style of mothering. (Even a quick look at children who are abused or neglected by parents should make it obvious that autism is a completely different kind of problem.)  .  .  .  \"</ref>articles,<ref name=New-York-Times-Richard-Bernstein-1990>Bernstein, Richard: [https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/04/weekinreview/ideas-trends-accusations-of-abuse-haunt-the-legacy-of-dr-bruno-bettelheim.html \"Accusations of Abuse Haunt the Legacy of Dr. Bruno Bettelheim\"], ''The New York Times'', November 4, 1990: \"The Week in Review\" section. \" . . not only of a tyrant but of a hypocrite as well. . \"</ref><ref name=\"Commentary-Magazine-Ron-Angres-October-1990\"/>A November 1990 ''Chicago Tribune'' article states:  \"Of the 19 alumni of the Orthogenic School interviewed for this story, some are still bitterly angry at Bettelheim, 20 or 30 years after leaving the institution due to the trauma they had suffered under him. Others say their stays did them good, and they express gratitude for having had the opportunity to be at the school. All agree that Bettelheim frequently struck his young and vulnerable patients.\"<ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-November-11-1990-Ron-Grossman\"/> and memoirs.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=DyDbxBkeyQMC&pg=PA132&lpg=PA132&dq=%22Tom+Lyon's+(1983)+roman+a+clef+The+Pelican+and+After:+A+Novel+about+Emotional+Disturbance%22&source=bl&ots=Pq9-CFYZ5b&sig=ucj4Cp2SdwaD2kuHkWbEb18T-RM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2ooyCpMDTAhVrzlQKHW3UD2QQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=%22Tom%20Lyon's%20(1983)%20roman%20a%20clef%20The%20Pelican%20and%20After%3A%20A%20Novel%20about%20Emotional%20Disturbance%22&f=false The Positive Side of Special Education: Minimizing Its Fads, Fancies, and Follies], Kenneth A. Kavale, Mark P. Mostert, ScareCrow Education (an imprint of The Rowman & Littlefield Pub. Group), 2004, page 132.</ref><ref name=\"Not The Thing I Was, Stephen Eliot, 2003\">[http://www.torontopubliclibrary.ca/detail.jsp?R=704207 Not The Thing I Was: Thirteen Years at Bruno Bettelheim's Orthogenic School], Stephen Eliot, New York: St. Martin's Press, 2003, as listed for Toronto Public Library.</ref><ref name=\"Crazy-My-Seven-Years-At-Bruno-Bettelheim's-Orthgenic-School-Redford-2010\">[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11073285-crazy Crazy: My Seven Years At Bruno Bettelheim's Orthogenic School], Roberta Carly Redford, Trafford Publishing, 364 pages, 2010.  The author was a student at the school from 1967 to 1974, ages 16 to 23.</ref>\n\nA particularly evocative example came from Alida Jatich, who lived at the school from 1966 to 1972 from ages twelve to eighteen. She wrote an initially anonymous April 1990 letter to the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'' in which she stated that she \"lived in fear of Bettelheim's unpredictable temper tantrums, public beatings, hair pulling, wild accusations and threats and abuse in front of classmates and staff. One minute he could be smiling and joking, the next minute he could be exploding.\" She added, \u201cIn person, he was an evil man who set up his school as a private empire and himself as a demi-god or cultleader.\u201d Jatich said Bettelheim had \u201cbullied, awed, and terrorized\u201d the children at his school, their parents, school staff members, his graduate students, and anyone else who came into contact with him.<ref>Quoted in New York Times, November 4, 1990</ref> \n\nPublished books, memoirs, and biographies of Bettelheim have also taken up the question of his treatment of students.<ref>Adam Feinstein, A History of Autism Conversations, Wiley Blackwell, p.71</ref><ref name=\"And-They-Call-It-Help-Louise-Armstrong\">''And They Call it Help: The Psychiatric Policing of America's Children'', Louise Armstrong, Addison-Wesley, 1993, Chapter 3 \"Bart Simpson Meets Bruno Bettelheim.\" See pages 75 and following for Alida Jatich's reports of abuse at the school. See pages 77 and following for the overall nonresponse from the Chicago psychiatric community. See pages 80 and following for more of Jatich's recounts of her experiences and her thoughts regarding why more people didn't speak up.</ref> Richard Pollak's biography of Bettelheim was inspired by his brother's experience at the school, and Bettelheim's callous response to inquiries about that experience.<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\"/><ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997/><ref name=\"Chicago-Tribune-April-3-1997-Joan-Beck\">[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-04-03/news/9704030057_1_bruno-bettelheim-richard-pollak-mental-illness Setting The Record Straight About A `Fallen Guru'], ''Chicago Tribune'', Joan Beck, Editorial, April 3, 1997. '  .  . claimed he had summa cum laude degrees in three disciplines,  .  .  '</ref> \n\nPollak's biography also states that two separate women reported that Bettelheim fondled their breasts and those of other female students at the school while he was ostensibly apologizing to each for beating her.<ref name=\"LosAngeles-Times-1997-Book-Review-Howard-Gardner\">[https://articles.latimes.com/1997-01-19/books/bk-19948_1_bruno-bettelheim The Confidence Man : THE CREATION OF DR. B.: A Biography of Bruno Bettelheim. By Richard Pollak. Simon & Schuster: 478 pages], ''Los Angeles Times'', review by Howard Gardner, Jan. 19, 1997. \" . . indicts those of his time who knew the man but kept their reservations to themselves.\"</ref><ref name=\"Weekly-Standard-1997\"/>\n\n===Institutional and professional responses===\nPerhaps in part because of Bettelheim's professional and public stature, there was little effort during his lifetime to curtail his behavior or intervene on behalf of his victims. His work at the [[University of Chicago]] seems to have been given less formal oversight by the University than other research entities under their purview.<ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/>\n\nProfessionals in the psychiatric and psychological communities likely knew there were allegations of abuse and maltreatment at the Orthogenic School.<ref name=\"Late-Talking-Children-Stephen-Camarata-2014\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=YxNmBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA82&lpg=PA82&dq=%22Chicago+analysts+scathingly+referred+to+the+doctor%22&source=bl&ots=mcDoha9kVj&sig=ZRXiVPrGzB3Lvx6QR1jLb5ccAFI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjthtSsofnPAhWDWz4KHfKxBCAQ6AEIKjAD#v=onepage&q=%22Chicago%20analysts%20scathingly%20referred%20to%20the%20doctor%22&f=false Late-Talking Children: A Symptom of a Stage?], Stephen M. Camarata, MIT Press, 2014. From \"Ch. 4: Lessons from Autism: Charlatans, False Cures, and Questionable Cures\", page 81 quotes a paragraph from ''Newsweek'' magazine.</ref><ref name=Newsweek-September-10-1990>''Newsweek'', \"'Beno Brutalheim'?,\" Nina Darnton, Sept. 10, 1990.</ref><ref name=\"Chicago-Reader-Alida-Jatich-two-letters-1990-and-1991\"/>. [[Howard Gardner]] a professor at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] wrote that many professionals knew of Bettelheim's behavior but did not confront him for various reasons including \"fear about Bettelheim's legendary capacity for retribution to the solidarity needed among the guild of healers to a feeling that, on balance, Bettelheim's positive attributes predominated and an unmasking would fuel more malevolent forces.\"<ref name=\"LosAngeles-Times-1997-Book-Review-Howard-Gardner\"/>\n\n===Autism controversy===\n\nBehavioral psychology and conditions in children and adolescents was little understood in the mid-twentieth century.  The concept of \"autism\" was first used as a term for [[schizophrenia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.uoregon.edu/autismhistoryproject/topics/childhood-psychosis-or-schizophrenia/ |title=Childhood Psychosis or Schizophrenia | website=The Autism History Project |last=Herman |first=Ellen |publisher=University of Oregon |access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> In the 1950s into the 1960s what may be understood as [[autism]] in children was regularly also referred to as \"childhood psychosis and childhood schizophrenia\". \"Psychogenesis\", the theory that childhood disorders had origins in early childhood events or trauma acting on the child from the outside was a prominent theory, and Bettelheim was a prominent proponent of a psychogenic basis for autism. For Bettelheim, the idea that outside forces cause individual behavior issues can be traced back to his earliest prominent article on the psychology of imprisoned persons.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.uoregon.edu/autismhistoryproject/archive/bruno-bettelheim-schizophrenia-as-a-reaction-to-extreme-situations-1956/ |title=Bruno Bettelheim, \u201cSchizophrenia as a Reaction to Extreme Situations,\u201d 1956 |website=The Autism History Project |last=Herman |first=Ellen |publisher=University of Oregon |access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>  Beginning in the 1960s and into the 1970s, \"biogensis\", the idea that such conditions had an inner-organic or biological basis overtook psychogenesis.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.uoregon.edu/autismhistoryproject/topics/psychogenesis/ |title=Psychogenesis  |website=The Autism History Project |last=Herman |first=Ellen |publisher=University of Oregon|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, many of Bettelheim's theories in which he attributes [[autism spectrum]] conditions to parenting style are considered to be discredited, not least because of the controversies relating to his academic and professional qualifications.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\"/><ref name=\"philly.com\"/><ref name=\"autisticadvocacy.org\"/>\n\nAutism spectrum conditions are now currently regarded as perhaps having multiple forms with a variety of genetic, epigenetic, and brain development causes influenced by such environmental factors as complications during pregnancy, viral infections, and perhaps even air pollution.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\">[https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/autism/documents/evaluatingchanges_workshopsummary.pdf Workshop on U.S. Data to Evaluate Changes in the Prevalence of Autism Spectrum Disorders (ASDs)], U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), February 1, 2011, Background: What Do We Know About ASD Prevalence?, M. Yeargin-Allsopp, page 7, ' . . There are likely multiple forms of ASDs with multiple causes that are poorly understood. . '</ref><ref name=Mayo-Clinic-June-3-2014>[http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/autism-spectrum-disorder/basics/causes/con-20021148 Autism spectrum disorder, Cause], Mayo Clinic Staff, June 3, 2014.  '  .  .  '''Genetic problems.''' Several different genes appear to be involved  .  .  .  .  .  '''Environmental factors.''' Researchers are currently exploring whether such factors as viral infections, complications during pregnancy or air pollutants play a role in triggering autism spectrum disorder.  .  .  '</ref><ref name=\"philly.com\">[http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/public_health/Why-are-the-French-still-blaming-mothers-for-autism-.html?c=r Why are the French still blaming mothers for autism?], Philly.com, Michael Yudell, Posted: Tuesday, January 31, 2012.</ref><ref name=\"autisticadvocacy.org\">[http://autisticadvocacy.org/2008/04/address-to-florida-autism-task-force-on-world-autism-day/ Address to Florida Autism Task Force on World Autism Day], Autistic Self Advocacy Network (ASAN), statement by Ari Ne'eman, founder of ASAN, April 2, 2008. ' . . the past few decades have resulted in a decrease in the stigmatization of parents of autistic children, as a result of the medical community moving away from the odious and damaging inaccuracy that autism is the result of \"refrigerator mothers.\" . . '</ref><ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/><ref name=\"New-York-Times-Book-Review-January-13-1997\"/><ref name=Scientific-Review-Mental-Health-Practice-2002>[http://www.srmhp.org/0101/autism.html Separating Fact from Fiction in the Etiology and Treatment of Autism], ''Scientific Review of Mental Health Practice'', James Herbert, Ian Sharp, Brandon Gaudiano (all three authors from Hahnemann University in Philadelphia, Penn.), Vol. 1: No. 1, Spring-Summer 2002.  \"  .  .  no controlled research has been produced to support the refrigerator mother theory of autism. For example, Allen, DeMeyer, Norton, Pontus, and Yang (1971) did not find differences between parents of autistic and mentally retarded children and matched comparison children on personality measures.  .  \"</ref>\n\nThe two biographies by Sutton (1995) and Pollak (1997) awakened interest and focus on Bettelheim's actual methods as distinct from his public persona.<ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/><ref name=\"New-York-Times-Book-Review-January-13-1997\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/13/books/an-icon-of-psychology-falls-from-his-pedestal.html?_r=0 An Icon of Psychology Falls From His Pedestal], ''The New York Times'', Books, Christopher Lehmann-Haupt (review of ''The Creation of Dr. B'' by Richard Pollak), Jan. 13, 1997.</ref><ref name=\"New-York-Times-Sarah-Boxer-January-26-1997\">\n{{cite web|first=Sarah|last=Boxer|authorlink=|title=The Man He Always Wanted to Be|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/01/26/reviews/970126.boxer.html|work=The New York Times|publisher=|location=|page=|date=January 26, 1997|accessdate=Dec 2, 2016|quote=Bruno Bettelheim's new biographer lays his cards on the table right away: he thinks Bettelheim was a pathological liar.}}</ref> Bettelheim's theories on the causes of [[autism]] have been largely discredited, and his reporting rates of cure have been questioned, with critics stating that his patients were not actually autistic.<ref name=Chicago-Tribune-Marie-Winn-February-23-1997/><ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\">Finn, Molly, June/July 1997, ''First Things'', \"In the Case of Bruno Bettelheim\" {{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/article/2008/08/006-in-the-case-of-bruno-bettelheim-15 |title=Archived copy |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220025609/http://www.firstthings.com/article/2008/08/006-in-the-case-of-bruno-bettelheim-15 |archivedate=February 20, 2012|df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=Raising-America-Ann-Hulbert-2003>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fDaODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA279&lpg=PA279&dq=%22boys+and+girls+for+whom+the+label+autistic+was+a+stretch%22&source=bl&ots=qEUF8Z7SPD&sig=l1KfOUoxZwURNsjFcqVzNCP59_s&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj8y-3JuoPRAhUpiVQKHQS9CjYQ6AEIGjAA#v=onepage&q=%22boys%20and%20girls%20for%20whom%20the%20label%20autistic%20was%20a%20stretch%22&f=false Raising America: Experts, Parents, and a Century of Advice about Children], Ann Hulbert, Random House, 2003.  \"  .  .  An evocative case history approach like his allowed for fudging of samples, methods, and final results, and Bettelheim did so quite brazenly.  .  \"</ref> In a favorable review of Pollak's biography, Christopher Lehmann-Haupt of ''The New York Times'' wrote, \"What scanty evidence remains suggests that his patients were not even autistic in the first place.\"<ref name=\"New-York-Times-Book-Review-January-13-1997\"/>\n\nIn 1997 the psychiatrist [[Peter D. Kramer|Peter Kramer]] wrote, \"The Ford Foundation was willing to underwrite innovative treatments for autistic children, so Bettelheim labeled his children autistic. Few actually met the definition of the newly minted syndrome.\"<ref name=\"Weekly-Standard-1997\"/>\n\nBettelheim believed that autism did not have an organic basis, but resulted when mothers withheld appropriate affection from their children and failed to make a good connection with them. Bettelheim also blamed absent or weak fathers. One of his most famous books, ''The Empty Fortress'' (1967), contains a complex and detailed explanation of this dynamic in psychoanalytical and psychological terms. These views were disputed at the time by mothers of autistic children and by researchers.<ref name=\"Lehmann-Haupt-1997\">Lehmann-Haupt, Christopher, \"An Icon of Psychology Falls From His Pedestal,\" ''The New York Times,'' 13 Jan. 1997.</ref> He derived his thinking from the qualitative investigation of clinical cases.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} He also related the world of autistic children to conditions in concentration camps.\n\nIt appears that Leo Kanner first came up with the term \"refrigerator mother,\" although Bettelheim did a lot to popularize the term.  \"Although it now seems beyond comprehension that anyone would believe that autism is caused by deep-seated issues arising in early childhood relationships, virtually every psychiatric condition was attributed to parent-child relationships in the 1940s and 1950s, when Freudian psychoanalytic theory was in its heyday.\"<ref name=\"Autism, Lisa, Benaron, 2009\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=qK9zCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=%22virtually+every+psychiatric+condition+was+attributed+to+parent-child+relationships+in+the+1940s+and+1950s%22&source=bl&ots=n2HD-15pPv&sig=ACfU3U0xo6y4-g7NyyeLn_ZgytexwzSb8Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjivpqq0PPgAhVBXawKHb6YAQQQ6AEwAHoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22virtually%20every%20psychiatric%20condition%20was%20attributed%20to%20parent-child%20relationships%20in%20the%201940s%20and%201950s%22&f=false Autism], Lisa D. Benaron, Greenwood Press, 2009, page 4.</ref>\n\nIn ''A Good Enough Parent'', published in 1987, he had come to the view that children had considerable resilience and that most parents could be \"good enough\" to help their children make a good start.<ref>\n[https://www.amazon.com/Good-Enough-Parent-Child-Rearing/review/product/0394757769/ref=dp_db_cm_cr_acr_txt?ie=UTF8&showViewpoints=1 Amazon reviews]{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2009}}</ref>\n\nPrior to this, Bettelheim subscribed to and became an early prominent proponent of the \"[[refrigerator mother]]\" theory of autism: the theory that autistic behaviors stem from the emotional frigidity of the children's mothers. He adapted and transformed the Orthogenic School at the University of Chicago as a residential treatment [[Milieu therapy|milieu]] for such children, who he felt would benefit from a \"[[parentectomy]]\". This marked the apex of autism viewed as a disorder of parenting.<ref name=Scientific-Review-Mental-Health-Practice-2002/><ref>{{cite book|title=Contemporary Directions in Psychopathology. Scientific Foundations of the DSM-V and ICD-11|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gVhgEMyIDUAC&printsec=frontcover|editor1-link=Theodore Millon|editor1-first=Theodore|editor1-last=Millon|editor2-first=Robert F.|editor2-last=Krueger|editor3-first=Erik|editor3-last=Simonsen|publisher=[[Guilford Press]]|location=New York City|year=2011|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=gVhgEMyIDUAC&pg=555&dq=%22Bettelheim+founded+the+Orthogenic+School+at+the+University+of+Chicago+as+a+residential+treatment+milieu+for+such+children,+whom+he+felt+would+benefit+from+a%22%22parent-ectomy%22%22This+marked+the+apex+of+autism+viewed+as+a+disorder+of+parenting.%22 555]|isbn=978-1-60623-533-1}}</ref>\n\nA 2002 book on autism spectrum stated, \"At the time, few people knew that Bettelheim had faked his credentials and was using fictional data to support his research.\"<ref name=\"Elijah's-Cup-2002\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=SexSzvwO-k4C&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72&dq=%22At+the+time,+few+people+knew+that+Bettelheim+had+faked+his+credentials+and+was+using+fictional+data%22&source=bl&ots=zj2ZZN-XG5&sig=NRaG8fSXL47-MI3yNVNlGhgVpEU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2pOO9murPAhUH4IMKHcw0BrEQ6AEIIzAB#v=onepage&q=%22At%20the%20time%2C%20few%20people%20knew%20that%20Bettelheim%20had%20faked%20his%20credentials%20and%20was%20using%20fictional%20data%22&f=false Elijah's Cup: A Family's Journey into the Community and Culture of High-Functioning Autism and Asperger's Syndrome, Revised Edition], Valerie Paradiz, Free Press, 2002; UK: Jessica Kingsley Publishers, 2005, pages 72-73: \"At the time, few people knew that Bettelheim had faked his credentials and was using fictional data to support his research. In 1944, with a forged resum\u00e9 that suggested a stellar academic career in psychoanalysis in Austria, Bettelheim had made his way into a post as the director of the Orthgenic School for Disturbed Children at the University of Chicago.\"</ref> [[Michael Rutter]] has observed, \"Many people made a mistake in going from a statement which is undoubtedly true\u2014that there is no evidence that autism has been caused by poor parenting\u2014to the statement that it has been disproven. It has not actually been disproven. It has faded away simply because, on the one hand, of a lack of convincing evidence and on the other hand, an awareness that autism was a neurodevelopmental disorder of some kind.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Feinstein|first=Adam|title=A History of Autism: Conversations with the Pioneers|year=2010|publisher=Blackwell's: Oxford, UK|page=68}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1997 review of two books on Bettelheim, Molly Finn wrote \"I am the mother of an autistic daughter, and have considered Bettelheim a charlatan since ''The Empty Fortress'', his celebrated study of autism, came out in 1967. I have nothing personal against Bettelheim, if it is not personal to resent being compared to a devouring witch, an infanticidal king, and an SS guard in a concentration camp, or to wonder what could be the basis of Bettelheim's statement that 'the precipitating factor in infantile autism is the parent's wish that his child should not exist.'\"<ref name=\"Molly-Finn-1997\"/>\n\nAlthough Bettelheim foreshadowed the modern interest in the causal influence of genetics in the section ''Parental Background,'' he consistently emphasised nurture over nature. For example: \"When at last the once totally frozen affects begin to emerge, and a much richer human personality to evolve, then convictions about the psychogenic nature of the disturbance become stronger still.\"; ''On Treatability,'' p.&nbsp;412. The rates of recovery claimed for the Orthogenic School are set out in ''Follow-up Data,'' with a recovery good enough to be considered a 'cure' of 43%., ps. 414\u2013415.\n\nSubsequently, medical research has provided greater understanding of the biological basis of autism and other illnesses. Scientists such as [[Bernard Rimland]] challenged Bettelheim's view of autism by arguing that autism is a [[Neural development|neurodevelopmental]] issue. As late as 2009, the \"refrigerator mother\" theory retained some prominent supporters,<ref name=\"SAJ\">{{cite book|last1=Severson|first1=Katherine DeMaria|last2=Aune|first2=James Arnt|last3=Jodlowski|first3=Denise|editor1-first=Mark|editor1-last=Osteen|title=Autism and Representation|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=188XgDxmdbEC&pg=PA65|accessdate=August 28, 2009|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|series=Routledge research in cultural and media studies|isbn=978-0-415-95644-4|pages=65\u201377|chapter=Bruno Bettelheim, Autism, and the Rhetoric of Scientific Authority}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Refrigerator mother' tosh must go into cold storage|author=Feinstein, Adam|publisher=autismconnect|url=http://autismconnect.org/news.asp?section=00010001&itemtype=adam&page=9&id=4540|accessdate=July 29, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927200621/http://autismconnect.org/news.asp?section=00010001&itemtype=adam&page=9&id=4540|archivedate=September 27, 2007}}\n</ref> including the prominent Irish psychologist [[Tony Humphreys]].<ref>\n{{cite news|author=Tony Humphreys|title=Core connection: A diagnosis of Asperger's syndrome does little to help a child troubled by unhappy relationships|work=Irish Examiner|date=February 3, 2012|page=7}}</ref> His theory still enjoys widespread support in France.<ref>{{cite web|last=Heurtevent|first=David|title=Introduction to Autism in France: A Really Silly Psychiatric System !|url=http://www.supportthewall.org/2012/01/introduction-to-autism-in-france-a-really-silly-psychiatric-system/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121220110003/http://www.supportthewall.org/2012/01/introduction-to-autism-in-france-a-really-silly-psychiatric-system/|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 20, 2012|work=Support The Wall \u2013 Autism|accessdate=February 25, 2012|date=January 2, 2012}}</ref>{{Dubious|date=November 2016}}\n\nIn his book ''Unstrange Minds'' (2007), Roy Richard Grinker wrote:{{Quote|\"Two other books on autism, published at about the same time [as Bettelheim's ''Empty Fortress'' (1967)], got little mention in the press: Bernard Rimland's ''Autism: The Syndrome and Its Implications for a Neural Theory of Behavior'' (1964), which outlined the biological and neurological aspects of autism, and Clara Clairborne Park's ''The Siege'' (1967), a beautifully written memoir of raising an autistic child.  Though they were more accurate depictions of autism, they couldn't compete with Bettelheim. He was simply too good a writer, and with his Viennese accent\u2014the sign of an authentic expert in psychology\u2014too good a self promoter.\"<ref name=\"Unstrange Minds, Roy Richard Grinker, 2007\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=1RICHy3FpYkC&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=%22Two+other+books+on+autism,+published+at+about+the+same+time%22&source=bl&ots=5u04KY3hBM&sig=Xw3HnarRHFYiDzPoOX9j1T71oIQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjgray32qTeAhUKlawKHWXpB_YQ6AEwAHoECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Two%20other%20books%20on%20autism%2C%20published%20at%20about%20the%20same%20time%22&f=false Unstrange Minds: Remapping the World of Autism: A Father, a Daughter, and a Search for New Answers], Finalist for the Victor Turner Prize for Ethnographic Writing, Roy Richard Grinker, New York: Basic Books (Perseus Books Group), 2007.</ref>}}\n\nJordynn Jack writes that Bettelheim's ideas gained currency and became popular in large part because society already tended to blame a mother first and foremost for her child's difficulties.<ref name=\"Autism and Gender, Jordynn Jack, 2014\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=DroPBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=%22The+commonplace+of+the+absent,+anxious,+or+cold+mother+became+a+heuristic%22&source=bl&ots=1C9dsLrgAg&sig=tXGsReHs0M8NTl1sFDyOvfDgvdc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiNxrik16TeAhVMY6wKHbKKCa4Q6AEwAHoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22The%20commonplace%20of%20the%20absent%2C%20anxious%2C%20or%20cold%20mother%20became%20a%20heuristic%22&f=false Autism and Gender: From Refrigerator Mothers to Computer Geeks], Jordynn Jack, University of Illinois Press, 2014.</ref>\n\n===Remarks about Jews and the Holocaust===\n\nBettelheim's experiences during the [[Holocaust]] shaped his personal and professional life for years after. His first publication was \"Individual and Mass Behavior in Extreme Situations\" derived from his experiences at [[Dachau]] and [[Buchenwald]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bettelheim |first1=Bruno |title=Individual and Mass Behavior in Extreme Situations |journal=Journal of Abnormal Psychology |date=1943 |volume=38 |issue=4 |pages=417\u2013452 |url=https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1944-00789-001 |language=en |doi=10.1037/h0061208}}</ref> His later work frequently compared emotionally disturbed childhood to prison or confinement, and according to Sutton, his professional work attempted to operationalize the lessons about human nature he learned during his confinement.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sutton |first1=Nina |title=Bettelheim: A Life and a Legacy |date=1997 |publisher=Westview Press |isbn=9780813390994 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBettelheim became one of the most prominent defenders of [[Hannah Arendt]]'s book ''[[Eichmann in Jerusalem]]''. He wrote a positive review for ''[[The New Republic]]''.<ref>\"The New Republic\", June 15, 1963</ref> This review prompted a letter from a writer, [[Harry Golden]], who alleged that both Bettelheim and Arendt suffered from \"an essentially Jewish phenomenon \u2026 self-hatred\".<ref>''The New Republic'', July 20, 1963</ref><ref>\"The Eichmann Polemics: Hannah Arendt and Her Critics\", Book Review in ''Democratiya'', Michael Ezra, London, 2007. {{cite web |url=http://www.democratiya.com/review.asp?reviews_id=102 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-20 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090120040641/http://www.democratiya.com/review.asp?reviews_id=102 |archivedate=January 20, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \n\nBettelheim would later speak critically of [[Jewish]] people who were killed during the [[Holocaust]]. He has been criticized for promoting the myth that Jews went \"[[like sheep to the slaughter]]\" and for blaming [[Anne Frank]] and her family for their own deaths due to not owning firearms, fleeing, or hiding more effectively.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tec |first1=Nechama |authorlink1=Nechama Tec |title=Did Jews Go Like Sheep to the Slaughter? |url=https://reformjudaismmag.org/past-issues/winter-2013/did-jews-go-like-sheep-to-slaughter |accessdate=5 December 2018 |work=Reform Judaism Magazine |date=Winter 2013 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Middleton-Kaplan |first1=Richard |editor1-last=Henry |editor1-first=Patrick |title=Jewish Resistance Against the Nazis |date=2014 |publisher=[[Catholic University of America Press]] |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=9780813225890 |page=10 |ref=harv |language=en |chapter=The Myth of Jewish Passivity}}</ref>  In an introduction he wrote to an account by [[Miklos Nyiszli]], Bettelheim stated, discussing Frank that \"Everybody who recognized the obvious knew that the hardest way to go underground was to do it as a family; that to hide as a family made detection by the SS most likely. The Franks, with their excellent connections among gentile Dutch families should have had an easy time hiding out singly, each with a different family. But instead of planning for this, the main principle of their planning was to continue as much as possible with the kind of family life they were accustomed to.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auschwitz: A Doctor's Eyewitness Account|last=Nyiszli|first=Miklos|publisher=Arcade Publishing|year=2011 |origyear=1960|isbn=978-1628729269|location=|pages=xiii}}</ref>\n\nRichard Pollak's biography, ''The Creation of Dr. B'', portrays Bettelheim as an anti-Semite even though he was raised in a secular Jewish household, and asserts that Bettelheim criticized in others the same cowardice he himself had displayed in the concentration camps.<ref name=\"LosAngeles-Times-1997-Book-Review-Howard-Gardner\"/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Major works by Bettelheim===\n*1943 \"Individual and Mass Behavior in Extreme Situations\", ''Journal of Abnormal and Social Psychology'', 38: 417\u2013452.\n*1950 Bettleheim, Bruno and Janowitz, Morris, ''Dynamics of Prejudice: A Psychological & Sociological Study of Veterans'', Harper & Bros.\n*1950 ''Love Is Not Enough: The Treatment of Emotionally Disturbed Children'', Free Press, Glencoe, Ill.\n*1954 ''Symbolic Wounds; Puberty Rites and the Envious Male'', Free Press, Glencoe, Ill.\n*1955 ''Truants From Life; The Rehabilitation of Emotionally Disturbed Children'', Free Press, Glencoe, Ill.\n*1959 \"Joey: A 'Mechanical Boy'\", ''Scientific American'', 200, March 1959: 117\u2013126. (About a boy who believes himself to be a robot.)\n*1960 ''The Informed Heart: Autonomy in a Mass Age'', The Free Press, Glencoe, Ill.\n*1962 ''Dialogues with Mothers'', The Free Press, Glencoe, Ill.\n*1967 ''The Empty Fortress: Infantile Autism and the Birth of the Self'', The Free Press, New York\n*1969 ''The Children of the Dream'', Macmillan, London & New York (About the raising of children in a [[kibbutz]] environment.)\n*1974 ''A Home for the Heart'', Knopf, New York. (About Bettelheim's Orthogenic School at the University of Chicago for schizophrenic and autistic children.)\n*1976 ''[[The Uses of Enchantment|The Uses of Enchantment: The Meaning and Importance of Fairy Tales]]'', Knopf, New York. {{ISBN|0-394-49771-6}}\n*1979 ''Surviving and Other Essays'', Knopf, New York (Includes the essay \"The Ignored Lesson of [[Anne Frank]]\".)\n*1982 ''On Learning to Read: The Child's Fascination with Meaning'' (with Karen Zelan), Knopf, New York\n*1982 ''Freud and Man's Soul'', Knopf, 1983, {{ISBN|0-394-52481-0}}\n*1987 ''A Good Enough Parent: A Book on Child-Rearing'', Knopf, New York\n*1990 ''Freud's Vienna and Other Essays'', Knopf, New York\n*1993, Bettelheim, Bruno and Rosenfeld, Alvin A, \"The Art of the Obvious\" Knopf.\n*1994 Bettelheim, Bruno & Ekstein, Rudolf: Grenzg\u00e4nge zwischen den Kulturen. ''Das letzte Gespr\u00e4ch zwischen Bruno Bettelheim und {{Interlanguage link multi|Rudolf Ekstein|de}}''. In: Kaufhold, Roland (ed.) (1994): ''Ann\u00e4herung an Bruno Bettelheim''. Mainz (Gr\u00fcnewald): 49\u201360.\n\n===Critical reviews of Bettelheim (works and person)===\n*Angres, Ronald: [https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/who-really-was-bruno-bettelheim/ \"Who, Really, Was Bruno Bettelheim?\"], personal essay, ''Commentary'', 90, (4), October 1990: 26\u201330.\n*Bernstein, Richard: [https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/04/weekinreview/ideas-trends-accusations-of-abuse-haunt-the-legacy-of-dr-bruno-bettelheim.html \"Accusations of Abuse Haunt the Legacy of Dr. Bruno Bettelheim\"], ''The New York Times'', November 4, 1990: \"The Week in Review\" section.\n*{{cite book|last=Bersihand|first=Genevi\u00e8ve|title=Bettelheim|trans-title=Bettelheim|year=1977|publisher=R. Jauze|location=Champigny-sur-Marne|language=|isbn=2-86214-001-5|pages=199}}\n*Dundes, Alan: [https://www.jstor.org/pss/541135 \"Bruno Bettelheim's Uses of Enchantment and Abuses of Scholarship\"]. ''The Journal of American Folklore'', Vol. 104, N0. 411. (Winter, 1991): 74\u201383.\n*Ekstein, Rudolf (1994): Mein Freund Bruno (1903\u20131990). Wie ich mich an ihn erinnere. In: Kaufhold, Roland (ed.) (1994): Ann\u00e4herung an Bruno Bettelheim. Mainz (Gr\u00fcnewald), S. 87\u201394.\n*Eliot, Stephen: ''Not the Thing I Was: Thirteen Years at Bruno Bettelheim's Orthogenic School'', St. Martin's Press, 2003.\n*Federn, Ernst (1994): Bruno Bettelheim und das \u00dcberleben im Konzentrationslager. In: Kaufhold, Roland (ed.) (1999): Ernst Federn: Versuche zur Psychologie des Terrors. Gie\u00dfen (Psychosozial-Verlag): 105\u2013108.\n*{{cite journal|journal=First Things|issue=74|pages=44\u20138|author=Finn M|title=In the case of Bruno Bettelheim|year=1997|url=http://www.firstthings.com/article.php3?id_article=3709}}\n*Fisher, David James: Psychoanalytische Kulturkritik und die Seele des Menschen. Essays \u00fcber Bruno Bettelheim (co-editor: Roland Kaufhold), Gie\u00dfen (Psychosozial-Verlag)\n*Fisher, David James: ''Bettelheim: Living and Dying'', Contemporary Psychoanalytic Studies, Amsterdam, New York: Brill/Rodopi, 2008.\n*Frattaroli, Elio: \"Bruno Bettelheim's Unrecognized Contribution to Psychoanalytic Thought\", ''Psychoanalytic Review'', 81:379\u2013409, 1994.\n*Heisig, James W.: \"Bruno Bettelheim and the Fairy Tales\", ''Children's Literature'', 6, 1977: 93\u2013115.\n*Kaufhold, Roland (ed.): Pioniere der psychoanalytischen P\u00e4dagogik: Bruno Bettelheim, Rudolf Ekstein, Ernst Federn und Siegfried Bernfeld, psychosozial Nr. 53 (1/1993)\n*Kaufhold, Roland (Ed.): Ann\u00e4herung an Bruno Bettelheim. Mainz, 1994 (Gr\u00fcnewald)\n*Kaufhold, Roland (1999): \"Falsche Fabeln vom Guru?\" Der \"Spiegel\" und sein M\u00e4rchen vom b\u00f6sen Juden Bruno Bettelheim, Behindertenp\u00e4dagogik, 38. Jhg., Heft 2/1999, S. 160\u2013187.\n*Kaufhold, Roland: Bettelheim, Ekstein, Federn: Impulse f\u00fcr die psychoanalytisch-p\u00e4dagogische Bewegung. Gie\u00dfen, 2001 (Psychosozial-Verlag).\n*Kaufhold, Roland/L\u00f6ffelholz, Michael (Ed.) (2003): \"So k\u00f6nnen sie nicht leben\" \u2013 Bruno Bettelheim (1903\u20131990). Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Politische Psychologie 1-3/2003.\n*Lyons, Tom W. (1983), ''The Pelican and After: A Novel about Emotional Disturbance'', Richmond, Virginia: Prescott, Durrell, and Company.  This is a roman \u00e0 clef novel in which the author lived at the Orthogenic School for almost twelve years.  The novel's head of the institution is a \"Dr. V.\"\n*Marcus, Paul: ''Autonomy in the Extreme Situation. Bruno Bettelheim, the Nazi Concentration Camps and the Mass Society'', Praeger, Westport, Conn., 1999.\n*[http://richardpollak.com/work3.htm Pollak, Richard]: ''The Creation of Dr. B: A Biography of Bruno Bettelheim'', Simon & Schuster, New York, 1997.\n*{{cite book|last=Raines|first=Theron|title=Rising to the light : a portrait of Bruno Bettelheim|edition=1|year=2002|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|location=New York|isbn=0-679-40196-2|url=https://archive.org/details/risingtolight00ther}}\n*Redford, Roberta Carly (2010) [https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11073285-crazy Crazy: My Seven Years At Bruno Bettelheim's Orthogenic School], Trafford Publishing, 364 pages.\n*Sutton, Nina: ''Bruno Bettelheim: The Other Side of Madness'', Duckworth Press, London, 1995. (Translated from the French by David Sharp in collaboration with the author. Subsequently, published with the title ''Bruno Bettelheim, a Life and a Legacy''.)\n*[[Jack Zipes|Zipes, Jack]]: \"On the Use and Abuse of Folk and Fairy Tales with Children: Bruno Bettelheim's Moralistic Magic Wand\", in Zipes, Jack: ''Breaking the Magic Spell: Radical Theories of Folk and Fairy Tales'', University of Texas Press, Austin, 1979.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://alexfiles.com/jinny.shtml Missing the Message: A Critique of Bettelheim's Analysis of ''The Jinny and the Fisherman'']\n*[http://www.suesske.de/kaufhold-1.htm Reviews of Dr. Roland Kaufhold's Bettelheim, Ekstein, Federn] (in German)\n*[http://www.suesske.de/buch_fisher.htm Thomas Aichhorn, ''Essays \u00fcber Bruno Bettelheim''] (in German)\n*{{IMDb name|id=0079291|name=Bruno Bettelheim}}\n*[http://www.edithbuxbaum.com/HamidaBosmajian.html The Edith Buxbaum Journal] by Roland Kaufhold\n*[http://www.ibe.unesco.org/fileadmin/user_upload/archive/publications/ThinkersPdf/bettelhe.pdf Bruno Bettelheim 1903\u20131990] Zehan, Karen, Prospects: the quarterly review of comparative education, UNESCO, 1993.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bettelheim, Bruno}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American psychologists]]\n[[Category:Austrian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish emigrants from Austria after the Anschluss]]\n[[Category:Autism researchers]]\n[[Category:Buchenwald concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:Child psychologists]]\n[[Category:Dachau concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:Fairy tale scholars]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Holocaust survivors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American social scientists]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:National Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:Jewish concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n[[Category:People involved in scientific misconduct incidents]]\n[[Category:Scientists who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Suicides by asphyxiation]]\n[[Category:Suicides in Maryland]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Vienna alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n", "name_user": "BerlinFR2503", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bruno_Bettelheim"}
{"title_page": "Titanium foam", "text_new": "'''[[Titanium]] foams''' exhibit high specific strength, high energy absorption, excellent corrosion resistance and [[biocompatibility]]. These materials are ideally suited for application moo s within the [[aerospace]] industry.<ref name=\"r1\" >{{cite journal|author=A. Ermachenko, R.Y. Lutfullin, R. Mulyukov|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/287453168|title= Advanced technologies of processing titanium alloys and their applications in industry|journal= Rev. Adv. Mater. Sci|volume=29 |year=2011|pages= 68\u201382}}</ref><ref name=\"r2\">{{cite journal|author=K. Hurysz, J. Clark, A. Nagel, C. Hardwicke, K. Lee, J. Cochran, T. Sanders|doi=10.1557/PROC-521-191|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/231901144|title= Steel and titanium hollow sphere foams|journal= MRS Online Proceedings Library Archive |volume=521 |year=1998}}</ref><ref name=\"r3\">{{cite journal|author=A. Salimon, Y. Brechet, M. Ashby, A. Greer|title= Potential applications for steel and titanium metal foams|journal= Journal of Materials Science |volume= 40|issue=22 |year=2005|pages= 5793\u20135799|doi= 10.1007/s10853-005-4993-x|bibcode= 2005JMatS..40.5793S}}</ref> An inherent resistance to corrosion allows the foam to be a desirable candidate for various filtering applications.<ref name=\"r4\">{{cite journal|author=L. Gauckler, M. Waeber, C. Conti, M. Jacob-Duliere|title= Ceramic foam for molten metal filtration|journal= JOM Journal of the Minerals, Metals and Materials Society 37|volume= 37|issue=9 |year=1985|pages= 47\u201350|doi= 10.1007/BF03258640|bibcode= 1985JOM....37i..47G}}</ref><ref name=\"r5\">{{cite journal|author=L.P. Lefebvre, J. Banhart, D.C. Dunand|title= Porous Metals and Metallic Foams: Current Status and Recent Developments|journal= Advanced Engineering Materials|volume=10|issue=9 |year=2008|pages= 775\u2013787|doi= 10.1002/adem.200800241}}</ref> Further, titanium's physiological inertness makes its porous form a promising candidate for [[biomedical]] implantation devices.<ref name=\"r6\">{{cite journal|author=J.R. Bush, B.K. Nayak, L.S. Nair, M.C. Gupta, C.T. Laurencin|title= Improved bio\u2010implant using ultrafast laser induced self\u2010assembled nanotexture in titanium|journal= Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part B: Applied Biomaterials |volume= 97|issue=2 |year=2011|pages= 299\u2013305|doi= 10.1002/jbm.b.31815|pmid= 21394901}}</ref><ref name=\"r7\">{{cite journal|author=N. Cheung, I. Ferreira, M. Pariona, J. Quaresma, A. Garcia|title= Melt characteristics and solidification growth direction with respect to gravity affecting the interfacial heat transfer coefficient of chill castings|journal= Materials & Design |volume=30|issue=9 |year=2009|pages= 3592\u20133601|doi= 10.1016/j.matdes.2009.02.025}}</ref><ref name=\"r8\">{{cite journal|author=F.B. Christensen|title= Lumbar spinal fusion. Outcome in relation to surgical methods, choice of implant and postoperative rehabilitation|journal= Acta Orthopaedica Scandinavica|volume=75|issue=313 |year=2004|pages= 2\u201343|doi= 10.1080/03008820410002057}}</ref><ref name=\"r9\">{{cite journal|author=F.B. Christensen, M. Dalstra, F. Sejling, S. Overgaard, C. B\u00fcnger|title= Titanium-alloy enhances bone-pedicle screw fixation: mechanical and histomorphometrical results of titanium-alloy versus stainless steel|journal= European Spine Journal |volume= 9|issue=2 |year=2000|pages= 97\u2013103|doi= 10.1007/s005860050218|pmid= 10823424|pmc= 3611362}}</ref><ref name=\"r10\">{{cite journal|author=R. Kanaparthy, A. Kanaparthy|title= The changing face of dentistry: nanotechnology|journal= International Journal of Nanomedicine  |volume= 6|year=2011|pages= 2799\u2013804|doi= 10.2147/IJN.S24353|pmid= 22131826|pmc= 3224707}}</ref><ref name=\"r11\">{{cite journal|author=E.K. Simpson, R.A. James, D.A. Eitzen, R.W. Byard|title= Role of orthopedic implants and bone morphology in the identification of human remains|journal= Journal of Forensic Sciences |volume=52|issue=2 |year=2007|pages= 442\u2013448|doi= 10.1111/j.1556-4029.2006.00370.x|pmid= 17316248}}</ref> The largest advantage in fabricating titanium foams is that the mechanical and functional properties can be adjusted through manufacturing manipulations that vary [[porosity]] and cell morphology. The high appeal of titanium foams is directly correlated to a multi-industry demand for advancement in this technology.\n\n== Characterization ==\n\nBanhart<ref name=\"r12\">{{cite journal|author=J. Banhart|title= Manufacture, characterization and application of cellular metals and metal foams|journal= Progress in Materials Science|volume= 46|issue=6 |year=2001|pages= 559\u2013632|doi= 10.1016/S0079-6425(00)00002-5}}</ref> describes two dominating perspectives in which cellular metals are characterized, referring to them as atomistic and macroscopic. The atomistic (or molecular) perspective holds that a cellular material is a construction of struts, membranes, and other elements which possess mechanical properties of their bulk metal counterpart. Indeed, the physical, mechanical, and thermal properties of titanium foams are commonly measured using the same methods as that of their solid counterparts. However, special precautions must be taken due to the cellular structure of metal foams.<ref name=\"r13\">{{cite book|author=M.F. Ashby|title= Metal foams: a design guide|publisher= Butterworth-Heinemann|year=2000}}</ref> From a macroscopic perspective, the cellular structure is perceived as a homogenous structure and characterized by considering the effective (or averaged) material parameters.<ref name = \"r12\" />\n\n== Microstructure ==\n\nTitanium foams are characterized structurally by their pore topology (relative percentage of open vs. closed pores), [[porosity]] (the multiplicative inverse of relative density), pore size and shape, and anisotropy.<ref name = \"r13\" /> Microstructures are most often examined by [[optical microscopy]],<ref name=\"r14\">{{cite journal|author=J.C. Li, D.C. Dunand|title= Mechanical properties of directionally freeze-cast titanium foams|journal= Acta Materialia |volume=59|issue=1 |year=2011|pages= 146\u2013158|doi= 10.1016/j.actamat.2010.09.019}}</ref> [[scanning electron microscopy]] <ref name=\"r15\">{{cite journal|author=B. Ye, D.C. Dunand|title= Titanium foams produced by solid-state replication of NaCl powders|journal= Materials Science and Engineering A|volume=528|issue=2 |year=2010|pages= 691\u2013697|doi= 10.1016/j.msea.2010.09.054}}</ref> and [[X-ray tomography]].<ref name=\"r16\">{{cite journal|author=J.L. Fife, J.C. Li, D.C. Dunand, P.W. Voorhees|title= Morphological analysis of pores in directionally freeze-cast titanium foams|journal= J. Mater. Res.|volume=24|issue=1 |year=2009|pages= 117\u2013124|doi= 10.1557/JMR.2009.0023|bibcode= 2009JMatR..24..117F|url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/43a0585841f5705f8160bf6f6e81d25465a6139c}}</ref>\n\nCategorizing titanium foams in terms of pore structure (as either open- or close-celled) is the most basic form of differentiation. In close-celled foams, pores are composed of bubbles entrapped in the metallic solid. These foams consist of a continuous network of sealed pores wherein interconnections between the pores are virtually non-existent. Alternatively, in open-celled foams, the pores are interconnected and solid struts allow fluid to pass through.<ref name = \"r17\">{{cite journal|author=L.J. Gibson|title= Cellular solids|journal= MRS Bulletin|volume=28|issue=4 |year=2003|pages= 270\u2013271|doi= 10.1557/mrs2003.79|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nMost manufactured foams contain both types of pores, although in many cases the subtype is minimal.<ref name = \"r18\">{{cite journal|author=J. Luyten, S. Mullens, I. Thijs|title= Designing with pores-synthesis and applications|journal= KONA Powder and Particle Journal|volume=28 |year=2010|pages= 131\u2013142|doi= 10.14356/kona.2010012|doi-access= free}}</ref>\nAccording to the [[IUPAC]], pore sizes are classified into three categories: micro (less than 2&nbsp;nm), meso (between 2 and 50&nbsp;nm) and macro (larger than 50&nbsp;nm) pores.<ref name = \"r18\" />\n\n== Mechanical properties ==\n\nAs with other metal foams, the properties of titanium foams depend mostly on the properties of the starting material and the relative density of the resultant foam. Thermal properties in foams \u2013 such as melting point, specific heat and expansion coefficient \u2013 remain constant for both the foams and the metals from which they are composed. However, the mechanical properties of foams are greatly influenced by [[microstructure]], which include the aforementioned properties as well as anisotropy and defects within the foam's structure.<ref name = \"r21\">{{cite journal|author=P. Kelly, D. Nowell|title= Three-dimensional cracks with Dugdale-type plastic zones|journal= International Journal of Fracture|volume=106|issue=4 |year=2000|pages= 291\u2013309|doi= 10.1023/A:1026557509000}}</ref>\n\n=== Sensitivity to impurities ===\nThe [[mechanical properties]] of titanium foams are sensitive to the presence of interstitial solutes, which present limitations to processing routes and utilization. Titanium has a high affinity for [[atmospheric gases]]. In foams, this is evidenced by the metal's tendency to trap oxides within cell edges.<ref name = \"r22\">{{cite journal|author=M. Barrab\u00e9s, A. Michiardi, C. Aparicio, P. Sevilla, J.A. Planell, F.J. Gil|title= Oxidized nickel\u2013titanium foams for bone reconstructions: chemical and mechanical characterization|journal= Journal of Materials Science: Materials in Medicine|volume=18|issue=11 |year=2007|pages= 2123\u20132129|doi= 10.1007/s10856-007-3012-y|pmid= 17619983}}</ref><ref name = \"r23\">{{cite journal|author=D.C. Dunand|title= Processing of titanium foams|journal= Advanced Engineering Materials |volume= 6|issue= 6|year=2004|pages= 369\u2013376|doi= 10.1002/adem.200405576}}</ref><ref name = \"r24\">{{cite journal|author=L.-P. Lefebvre, E. Baril|title= Effect of oxygen concentration and distribution on the compression properties on titanium foams|journal= Advanced Engineering Materials|volume=10|issue=9 |year=2008|pages= 868\u2013876|doi= 10.1002/adem.200800122|url=https://nrc-publications.canada.ca/eng/view/fulltext/?id=bbf9fdc9-0320-4a33-bda4-624e9ee59772}}</ref>\nMicro-hardness of cell walls, [[elastic modulus]], and [[yield strength]] increase as a result of interstitial solutes; [[ductility]], which is a function of the quantity of interstitial impurities, is consequently reduced.<ref name = \"r25\">{{cite journal|author=N. Jha, D. Mondal, J. Dutta Majumdar, A. Badkul, A. Jha, A. Khare|title= Highly porous open cell Ti-foam using NaCl as temporary space holder through powder metallurgy route|journal= Materials & Design |volume=47 |year=2013|pages= 810\u2013819|doi= 10.1016/j.matdes.2013.01.005}}</ref> Of the atmospheric gases, nitrogen has the most significant impact, followed by oxygen and carbon.<ref name = \"r27\">{{cite journal|author=J. Luyten, S. Mullens, I. Thijs|title= Designing with pores\u2014synthesis and applications|journal= KONA Powder Part J|volume=28 |year=2010|pages= 131\u2013142|doi= 10.14356/kona.2010012|doi-access= free}}</ref>\nThese impurities are often present in the precursor mixture and also introduced during processing.\n\n=== Theoretical models for predicting mechanical properties ===\n==== Gibson & Ashby models ====\n\nGibson & Ashby<ref name = \"r17\"/> micromechanical models for [[porous materials]] provide mathematical equations for the prediction of mechanical parameters based on experimentally determined geometric constants. The constants of proportionality are determined by fitting experimental data to various mathematical models for structures consisting of cubes and solid struts and are dependent upon cell geometry. A limitation of the Gibson & Ashby <ref name=\"r17\" /> model is that it is most accurate for foams exhibiting porosities higher than 70%, although experimental comparisons for lower porosity foams have shown agreement with this model. Ye & Dunand found reasonable agreement to the Gibson & Ashby model for titanium foams exhibiting 42% porosity. Ultrasonic measurements provided an average [[Young's modulus]] value of 39 GPa, which is in relatively good agreement with the Gibson & Ashby prediction of 35 GPa.<ref name=\"r15\"/>\n\nThe Gibson & Ashby<ref name=\"r17\" /> models assume ideal structures; microstructural irregularities (e.g. inhomogeneous pore distribution; defects) are not considered. Additionally, experimental results from which the predetermined proportionality constants were based on experimental values that were obtained from simple compression tests. Consequently, they may not be applicable for multiaxial loads.<ref name = \"r28\">{{cite journal|author=S. Maiti, L. Gibson, M. Ashby|title= Deformation and energy absorption diagrams for cellular solids|journal= Acta Metallurgica|volume= 32|issue=11 |year=1984|pages= 1963\u20131975|doi= 10.1016/0001-6160(84)90177-9}}</ref>\n\n==== Minimum solid area (MSA) models ====\n\nMinimum solid area models assume that the load bearing area (cross-sectional area normal to the stress) is the logical basis for modeling mechanical behavior. MSA models assume pore interaction results in reduction of stress. Therefore, the minimum solid areas are the carriers of stress. As a result, predicted mechanical properties fluctuate based on the quantification of the solid area of the foam. For titanium foams consisting of partially sintered powders, the minimum solid area consists of the neck area between powders through the cross-section of cell walls between macropores.<ref name = \"r31\">{{cite journal|author=Z. Esen, \u015e. Bor|title= Processing of titanium foams using magnesium spacer particles|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=56|issue=5 |year=2007|pages= 341\u2013344|doi= 10.1016/j.scriptamat.2006.11.010}}</ref>\nThe mathematical relationships in MSA models<ref name = \"r32\">{{cite journal|author=R. Rice|title= Evaluation and extension of physical property-porosity models based on minimum solid area|journal= Journal of Materials Science |volume=31|issue=1 |year=1996|pages= 102\u2013118|doi= 10.1007/BF00355133|bibcode= 1996JMatS..31..102R}}</ref>\nare relatively consistent with the Gibson & Ashby model.<ref name = \"r17\" /><ref name = \"r33\">{{cite journal|author=R. Rice|title= Comparison of stress concentration versus minimum solid area based mechanical property-porosity relations|journal= Journal of Materials Science |volume= 28|issue=8 |year=1993|pages= 2187\u20132190|doi= 10.1007/BF00367582|bibcode= 1993JMatS..28.2187R}}</ref>\nHowever, the MSA models are designed to predict mechanical property parameters over a broader range of porosity levels. Like the Gibson & Ashby models, MSA models were derived assuming idealized (defect-free) structures containing uniform pore shapes, size and distribution.\n\n=== Compressive properties ===\n\nThe most frequently reported mechanical property of titanium foams is compressive strength.<ref name = \"r34\" /> It was generally accepted that the compressive properties of metal foams depended on the properties of the cell wall rather than on pore size. However, more recent research has indicated that smaller pore sizes equate to higher compressive strength. As pore sizes reach nano-dimensions, the relationship is even more clear due to changes in deformation mechanism.<ref name = \"r35\">{{cite journal|author=X. Wang, X. Wei, C. Wen, F. Han|title= Fabrication and characterisation of microporous titanium|journal= Powder Metallurgy |volume=54|issue=1 |year=2011|pages= 56\u201358|doi= 10.1179/174329009X409660}}</ref>\n\nTuncer & Arslan fabricated titanium foams via the space-holder method using various shaped space-holders to elucidate the effect of cell morphology on mechanical properties. They found that foams created with needle-like urea space-holders exhibited a decrease in elastic modulus and yield strength when compared to spherical pores.<ref name = \"r36\">{{cite journal|author=N. Tuncer and G. Arslan|title= Designing compressive properties of titanium foams|journal= Journal of Materials Science |volume=44|issue=6 |year=2009|pages= 1477\u20131484|doi= 10.1007/s10853-008-3167-z|bibcode= 2009JMatS..44.1477T}}</ref>\n\n== Processing methods ==\n\nMany metal foam manufacturing techniques are accomplished by the introduction of a gaseous phase into a precursor matrix, which can occur in either molten metal or a powdered metal form. Due to titanium's high melting point (1670&nbsp;\u00b0C) and high chemical affinity with oxygen, nitrogen, carbon and hydrogen (which dissolve rapidly either in liquid or solid titanium at a temperature above 400&nbsp;\u00b0C<ref name = \"r23\" />), solid-state processes based on powder densification are the preferred method of fabrication.<ref name = \"r15\" /><ref name = \"r23\" /><ref name = \"r31\" /><ref name = \"r34\">{{cite journal|author=M.M. Shbeh, R. Goodall|title= Open Celled Porous Titanium|journal= Advanced Engineering Materials|volume=19|issue=11 |pages= 1600664|year=2017|doi= 10.1002/adem.201600664|url= http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/116328/3/Open%20Celled%20Porous%20Ti%20Review.pdf}}</ref><ref name = \"r40\">{{cite journal|author=N. Davis, J. Teisen, C. Schuh, D. Dunand|title= Solid-state foaming of titanium by superplastic expansion of argon-filled pores|journal= Journal of Materials Research|volume=16|issue=5 |year=2001|pages= 1508\u20131519|doi= 10.1557/JMR.2001.0210|bibcode= 2001JMatR..16.1508D|url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/2bda2e4ec9f05d05d4943280f18a218a1e0c1539}}</ref><ref name = \"r41\">{{cite journal|author=D. Elzey, H. Wadley|title= The limits of solid state foaming|journal= Acta Materialia |volume=49|issue=5 |year=2001|pages= 849\u2013859|doi= 10.1016/S1359-6454(00)00395-5}}</ref>\nProcessing methods must also be designed to avoid exposure to air or moisture; vacuum or inert gas sintering processes are usually sufficient for preventing contamination.<ref name = \"r23\" /><ref name = \"r42\">{{cite journal|author=L.P. Lefebvre, E. Baril|title= Effect of oxygen concentration and distribution on the compression properties on titanium foams|journal= Advanced Engineering Materials|volume=10|issue=9 |year=2008|pages= 868\u2013876|doi= 10.1002/adem.200800122}}</ref>\n\n=== Loose-powder (gravity) sintering ===\n[[File: TitaniumUSGOV.jpg |thumb|Titanium powder]]\n[[File:Tisponge.png|thumb|Titanium sponge cylinder produced via powder metallurgy, 120 grams, 3\u00d74 cm.]]\n\nUtilizing [[powder metallurgy]] routes<ref name = \"r43\">{{cite book|author=W.D. Callister, D.G. Rethwisch|title= Materials science and engineering: an introduction|publisher= Wiley New York|year=2007}}</ref> for titanium foam fabrication allows for production at lower temperatures than those required through a melt process and reduces overall risks for contamination. In loose-powder sintering (also known as gravity sintering), pores are created through diffusion bonding arising from the voids existing between packed powder particles. Axial compaction followed by sintering follows the same procedure as above, but pressures is applied for compaction of the precursor material.<ref name = \"r44\">{{cite book|author=C. Leyens, M. Peters|title= Titanium and titanium alloys|publisher= Wiley |year=2003}}</ref> For both compaction methods, the resulting pore morphology is dependent upon the morphology of the metallic powder, making it difficult to control the size, shape, and distribution of the pores.<ref name = \"r43\" /> Another disadvantage includes the relatively high probability of pore collapse and limited achievable porosity levels.<ref name = \"r46\">{{cite journal|author=L. Zhang, Y. Zhao|title= Fabrication of high melting-point porous metals by lost carbonate sintering process via decomposition route|journal= Proceedings of the Institution of Mechanical Engineers, Part B: Journal of Engineering Manufacture |volume=222|issue=2 |year=2008|pages= 267\u2013271|doi= 10.1243/09544054JEM832|url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/78115c7fd8112c6a9f48eb8111476d8e30135e5e}}</ref>\n\n=== Expansion of pressurized bubbles ===\n[[File:Tiargon.png|thumb|Titanium foamed with argon]]\nTo produce titanium foams via expansion of pressurized gas, the titanium precursor mixture is placed within a gas-tight metal can, which is evacuated after filling. The metal can is pressurized with inert gas\u2014most commonly argon \u2013 and is pressed isostatically. The gas-filled pores are contained within the compacted matrix, and upon exposure to elevated temperatures, these bubbles expand through creep of the surrounding metal matrix.<ref name = \"r47\">{{cite journal|author=A. Kennedy, S. Asavavisitchai|title= Effects of TiB<sub>2</sub> particle addition on the expansion, structure and mechanical properties of PM Al foams|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=50|issue=1 |year=2004|pages= 115\u2013119|doi= 10.1016/j.scriptamat.2003.09.026}}</ref> Since processing titanium foams using [[hot isostatic pressing]] (HIP) eliminates the need for separate compaction and sintering processes, a wider variety of custom shapes and sizes are possible than via loose powder sintering techniques.<ref name = \"r48\">{{cite journal|author=M. Sharma, G. Gupta, O. Modi, B. Prasad|title= PM processed titanium foam: influence of morphology and content of space holder on microstructure and mechanical properties|journal= Powder Metallurgy|volume= 56|issue=1 |year=2013|pages= 55\u201360|doi= 10.1179/1743290112Y.0000000036}}</ref> Disadvantages of this process include reduced pore connectivity, limited achievable porosity, and a complicated experimental set-up.<ref name = \"r48\" /> However, a unique aspect of the HIP process with respect to titanium (and other polymorphic materials) is that transformation superplasticity can be enhanced through the HIP process by way of thermal cycling, or by cycling around the alpha/beta allotropic temperature boundaries of the metal.<ref name = \"r40\" />\n\n=== Superplastic expansion ===\nTitanium undergoes allotropic transformation from its \u03b1-phase (hexagonal close-packed (hcp) structure at temperatures less than 882.5&nbsp;\u00b0C) to its \u03b2-phase (body centered cubic, bcc) structure at temperatures above 882.3&nbsp;\u00b0C). Alpha-phase titanium products typically exhibit medium to high strength with excellent creep strength, whereas beta-phase titanium products typically exhibit very high strength and low ductility.<ref name = \"r40\" /><ref name = \"r44\" /> Foams created under thermal cycling conditions have been shown to exhibit increased porosity due to the density difference between allotropic phases. Davis et al. produced titanium foams with 41% porosity (as compared to 27% porosity through the normal HIP creep mechanism).<ref name = \"r40\" /> Increases in overall ductility were also observed in foams created through thermal cycling. In a similar experiment, porosity of 44% was achieved and determined as the maximum achievable porosity under thermal cycling conditions.<ref name = \"r49\">{{cite journal|author=N. Murray, D. Dunand|title= Microstructure evolution during solid-state foaming of titanium|journal= Composites Science and Technology |volume=63|issue=16 |year=2003|pages= 2311\u20132316|doi= 10.1016/S0266-3538(03)00264-1}}</ref> A later study also utilized exploitation of transformation superplasticity conditions through HIP, but in this case, the titanium powder in the precursor matrix was replaced with titanium wires to create anisotropic pores. The resulting anisotropic pores showed closer correlation with natural bone in that the foams exhibited higher elastic moduli, yield strength and deformation when subjected to longitudinally loaded forces than when loads were applied transversely.<ref name = \"r50\">{{cite journal|author=E.D. Spoerke, N.G. Murray, H. Li, L.C. Brinson, D.C. Dunand, S.I. Stupp|title= A bioactive titanium foam scaffold for bone repair|journal= Acta Biomaterialia|volume=1|issue=5 |year=2005|pages= 523\u2013533|doi= 10.1016/j.actbio.2005.04.005|pmid= 16701832}}</ref>\n\n=== Space-holder technique ===\nThe space-holder technique is the most commonly employed method for producing titanium foams. The space-holder technique allows for the fabrication of higher porosity foams (35\u201380% <ref name = \"r90\">{{cite journal|author=N. Murray, C. Schuh, D. Dunand|title= Solid-state foaming of titanium by hydrogen-induced internal-stress superplasticity|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=49|issue=9 |year=2003|pages= 879\u2013883|doi= 10.1016/S1359-6462(03)00438-X}}</ref>) than other techniques, while also giving the engineer more control over pore fraction, shape and connectivity.<ref name = \"r47\" /> Mechanical properties can be adjusted through the size, shape and quantity of space-holders employed. The space-holder technique was first demonstrated by Zhao and Sun<ref name = \"r91\">{{cite journal|author=Y. Zhao, D. Sun|title= A novel sintering-dissolution process for manufacturing Al foams|doi=10.1016/S1359-6462(00)00548-0|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=44|issue=1 |year=2001|pages= 105\u2013110}}</ref> for the fabrication of aluminum foams in a powder metallurgical method, which consisted of the incorporation of NaCl as a space-holder. The space-holder was mixed into the powder mixture and dissolved prior to sintering. The same method was used to create titanium foams for the first time when Wen et al. utilized ammonium hydrogen carbonate spacers.<ref name = \"r87\">{{cite journal|author=C. Wen, Y. Yamada, K. Shimojima, Y. Chino, H. Hosokawa, M. Mabuchi|title= Novel titanium foam for bone tissue engineering|journal= Journal of Materials Research|volume=17|issue=10 |year=2002|pages= 2633\u20132639|doi= 10.1557/JMR.2002.0382|bibcode= 2002JMatR..17.2633W}}</ref>\n\n==== Powder selection ====\nThe size and shape of the metal powder has a direct impact on the stability of the precursor as well as the resulting foam. For this purpose, powders that increase packing efficiency are most advantageous.<ref name = \"r36\" /> The use of spherical particles may result in less contact of particles which consequently leads to larger secondary pores and a higher probability of pore collapse prior to complete sintering.<ref name = \"r92\">{{cite journal|author=N. Jha, D. Mondal, J.D. Majumdar, A. Badkul, A. Jha, A. Khare|title= Highly porous open cell Ti-foam using NaCl as temporary space holder through powder metallurgy route|journal= Materials & Design |volume=47 |year=2013|pages= 810\u2013819|doi= 10.1016/j.matdes.2013.01.005}}</ref> This factor can be limited through different compaction techniques that decrease the degree of interstitial sites around the titanium particles. However, this method also has limitations; for example, the powders cannot be compacted to such a degree that would promote deformation of the spacer (unless anisotropic pore shape is desired).<ref name = \"r15\" /><ref name = \"r61\">{{cite journal|author=T. Imwinkelried|title= Mechanical properties of open\u2010pore titanium foam|journal= Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part A |volume=81|issue=4 |year=2007|pages= 964\u2013970|doi= 10.1002/jbm.a.31118|pmid= 17252551}}</ref>\n\n==== Space-holder selection ====\n[[File:Tisugar.png|thumb|Computer tomography (a) and electron micrograph (b) of the Ti foam made with saccharose as a space holder, showing two types of pores in titanium foam]]\nThe selection of the space-holder is one of the most crucial steps because it defines many of the properties of the resulting foam, including cell shape, cell size and macroporosity. The space-holder should be inert and represent the size and shape of the desired pores. The porosity may be adjusted anywhere between 50 and 85% without the filler material becoming a part of the resultant foam.<ref name = \"r10\" /> It is also important to select a spacer that has limited or no solubility in titanium, as this incorporation will affect the mechanical properties of the resulting foam.<ref name = \"r94\">{{cite journal|author=A. Mansourighasri, N. Muhamad, A.B. Sulong|title= Processing titanium foams using tapioca starch as a space holder|journal= Journal of Materials Processing Technology |volume=212|issue=1 |year=2012|pages= 83\u201389|doi= 10.1016/j.jmatprotec.2011.08.008}}</ref> \n\n==== Space-holder size and shape ====\nThe degree of homogeneity in pore distribution of the final product is primarily dependent on the adequacy of mixing of the precursor. The difference in particle size between the titanium powders and the spacers directly impacts the ability to adequately mix the preform. The greater the size difference, the more difficult it is to control this process.<ref name = \"r94\" /> Nonhomogeneous mixing resulting from the use of spacers considerably larger than the titanium particles employed and has shown adverse effects in the stability of the precursor after removal of spacer and in the distribution of porosity.<ref name = \"r36\" /><ref name = \"r95\">{{cite journal|author=G. Ryan, A. Pandit, D.P. Apatsidis|title= Fabrication methods of porous metals for use in orthopaedic applications|journal= Biomaterials |volume=27|issue=13 |year=2006|pages= 2651\u20132670|doi= 10.1016/j.biomaterials.2005.12.002|pmid= 16423390}}</ref>\nSpacer size has been investigated.<ref name = \"r36\" /><ref name = \"r48\" /><ref name = \"r85\" /> It was shown that the use of a coarse spacer results in thicker pore walls while the use of finer spacers results in enhanced compaction, leading to increased densification. Increased densification is evidenced by a monomodal pore distribution with the employment of fine spacers and a bimodal distribution using coarse spacers. Further, finer spacers result in a more homogenous pore distribution. Sharma et al.<ref name = \"r77\" /> utilized acicular spacers and achieved porosities up to 60% where pores were undistorted. In samples employing fine particles, porosities up to 70% were achievable before noting distortion in the pores.<ref name = \"r85\" /> However, the bimodal pore distribution observed in coarse-spacer samples showed to be beneficial in terms of mechanical properties in that higher compressive strengths were observed, beyond those that might exist due to the inverse relationship of porosity and compressive strength alone.<ref name = \"r85\">{{cite journal|author=N. Tuncer, G. Arslan, E. Maire, L. Salvo|title= Investigation of spacer size effect on architecture and mechanical properties of porous titanium|journal= Materials Science and Engineering: A|volume= 530 |year=2011|pages= 633\u2013642|doi= 10.1016/j.msea.2011.10.036}}</ref>\n\n==== Compaction ====\nThe precursor mixture of powders and space-holders are compacted into a mold under a specified pressure. This can be achieved through uniaxial or isostatic processes. The pores resulting from this method are open and interconnected via windows between neighboring pores with the size of the pores partially dependent upon the coordination number and contact area of the resulting compact. Compaction pressure must be high enough to ensure sufficient mechanical strength for retention of pore geometry specified by the space-holder, but not too high enough as to cause deformation of the space-holder.<ref name = \"r94\" />\n\n==== Sintering and space-holder removal ====\nWhen employing dissolvable spacers, it is possible to remove the spacer after sintering, which reduces the risk of pore collapse. \nIn most cases, foams created using space-holders contain bimodal pore distributions with macro-sized pores resulting from the space-holder particles and micro-sized pores located on the pore walls and resulting from incomplete sintering of the powder matrix. As a result, the macropores typically exhibit rough internal surfaces.<ref name = \"r96\">{{cite journal|author=A. Bansiddhi, T. Sargeant, S. Stupp, D. Dunand|title= Porous NiTi for bone implants: a review|journal= Acta Biomaterialia |volume=4|issue=4 |year=2008|pages= 773\u2013782|doi= 10.1016/j.actbio.2008.02.009|pmid= 18348912|pmc= 3068602}}</ref> In some applications, such as for the use of bio-medical implants, this is an advantageous property. Inner porosity (or micro-porosity) has been shown to reduce stiffness; thus, reduce the risk of stress-shielding effects, while also offering improved osseointegration.<ref name=\"r14\"/><ref name = \"r77\">{{cite journal|author=M. Sharma, G. Gupta, O. Modi, B. Prasad, A.K. Gupta|title= Titanium foam through powder metallurgy route using acicular urea particles as space holder|journal= Materials Letters |volume=65|issue=21 |year=2011|pages= 3199\u20133201|doi= 10.1016/j.matlet.2011.07.004}}</ref><ref name = \"r96\" />\n\n==== Space-holder materials ====\n\n===== Sodium chloride (NaCl) =====\nSodium chloride is the most commonly chosen space-holder for titanium foams because it is highly soluble in water and inert with respect to titanium. This inertness prevents contamination and degradation of the mechanical properties of the resulting foam. Moreover, NaCl is non-toxic; any residuals are bioinert.<ref name = \"r77\" /><ref name = \"r80\" />\n\nBansiddhi & Dunand pioneered the use of NaCl as a permanent space-holder for the fabrication of NiTi foams.<ref name = \"r102\">{{cite journal|author=A. Bansiddhi, D.C. Dunand|title= Shape-memory NiTi foams produced by replication of NaCl space-holders|journal= Acta Biomaterialia |volume= 4|issue=6 |year=2008|pages= 1996\u20132007|doi= 10.1016/j.actbio.2008.06.005|pmid= 18678532}}</ref> The resulting foams consisted of 32-36% porosity with more complete densification than they observed when producing NiTi foams using a sodium fluoride (NaF) space-holder.<ref name = \"r103\">{{cite journal|author=A. Bansiddhi, D.C. Dunand|title= Shape-memory NiTi foams produced by solid-state replication with NaF|journal= Intermetallics|volume=15|issue=12 |year=2007|pages= 1612\u20131622|doi= 10.1016/j.intermet.2007.06.013}}</ref> However, processing parameters resulted in molten NaCl and a metal/salt blend in the cavities of the foam. Certain risks are associated with using a molten space-holder including reaction with the metal, dissolving of the space-holder in the metal and prevention of densification through the creation of a thin layer of liquid between the metal and particles.<ref name = \"r96\" /> Near complete densification was achieved when NaCl was used as a permanent space-holder in pure titanium foam.<ref name = \"r15\" /> In this case, a temperature below the melting point of NaCl was used; titanium is less creep resistant than NiTi, which allows for densification at lower temperatures. The resulting foams achieved porosity of 50\u201367% with minimal observable microporosity. Anisotropic pore shape in some areas alluded to NaCl's deformation during HIP, which is desirable for some applications.<ref name = \"r88\">{{cite journal|author=B. Ye, D.C. Dunand|title= Titanium foams produced by solid-state replication of NaCl powders|journal= Materials Science and Engineering: A |volume=528|issue=2 |year=2010|pages= 691\u2013697|doi= 10.1016/j.msea.2010.09.054}}</ref> Additionally, an observed, rough inner surface of the pores holds advantages for biomedical implant applications. \nJha et al.<ref name = \"r92\" /> achieved 65-80% porosity through the use of NaCl as a space-holder and a cold compaction process at various pressures with two-stage sintering. In this case, NaCl was removed through dissolution after the second stage of sintering. Resulting Young's moduli (8\u201315 GPa) were considerably lower than the Young's modulus of 29 GPa achieved for 50% porosity foams.<ref name = \"r25\" /><ref name = \"r88\" /> This illustrates the known relationship between porosity and Young's modulus wherein Young's modulus decreases linearly with increasing porosity. Achievable porosity through the space-holder method is directly related to the type and amount of space-holder utilized (up to a threshold maximum achievable porosity level).\n\n===== Magnesium =====\n\nMagnesium can be removed either thermally or by reactive measures through the dissolution in acid.<ref name = \"r31\" /><ref name = \"r104\">{{cite journal|author=T. Aydo\u011fmu\u015f, \u015e. Bor|title= Processing of porous TiNi alloys using magnesium as space holder|journal= Journal of Alloys and Compounds |volume=478|issue=1 |year=2009|pages= 705\u2013710|doi= 10.1016/j.jallcom.2008.11.141}}</ref>\n<ref name = \"r105\">{{cite journal|author=S.W. Kim, H.-D. Jung, M.-H. Kang, H.-E. Kim, Y.-H. Koh, Y. Estrin|title= Fabrication of porous titanium scaffold with controlled porous structure and net-shape using magnesium as spacer|journal= Materials Science and Engineering: C |volume=33|issue=5 |year=2013|pages= 2808\u20132815|doi= 10.1016/j.msec.2013.03.011|pmid= 23623100}}</ref> Esen & Bor <ref name = \"r31\" /> found a critical content of magnesium as a space holder to be 55-60%, above which compacts shrink excessively during sintering. Foams ranging in porosity from 45 to 70% with a bimodal pore distribution and compressive strength of 15 MPa (for 70% porosity) were demonstrated. Kim et al. fabricated foams with anisotropic pores through the intentional deformation of Mg particles during compaction in an effort to enhance mechanical properties. A final porosity of 70% equated to a yield strength of 38 MPa for normal orientation of pores and 59 MPa when pores were aligned with the direction of compression.<ref name = \"r105\" />\n\n===== Urea =====\n\nAnother commonly employed space-holder for titanium foams is [[urea]], which yilded porosities from 20 to 75%.<ref name = \"r36\" /><ref name = \"r77\" /><ref name = \"r84\" /><ref name = \"r85\" /><ref name = \"r87\" /> Wen et al.<ref name = \"r87\" /> produced foams exhibiting a bimodal pore distribution with porosities ranging from 55 to 75%, Young's moduli between 3\u20136.4 GPa, and a plateau stress of 10\u201335 MPa. An inverse relationship between plateau stress and porosity was observed with increased porosity resulting in decreased plateau stress.<ref name = \"r87\" /> Tuncer et al. utilized urea in combination with irregularly shaped titanium powders in an effort to increase green strength through increased packing efficiency (of particles). This also eliminated the need for the incorporation of a binder.<ref name = \"r84\">{{cite journal|author=N. Tuncer, G. Arslan, E. Maire, L. Salvo|title= Influence of cell aspect ratio on architecture and compressive strength of titanium foams|journal= Materials Science and Engineering: A |volume=528|issue=24 |year=2011|pages= 7368\u20137374|doi= 10.1016/j.msea.2011.06.028}}</ref>\n\n===== Tapioca starch =====\n[[Tapioca]] starch can be burnt off easily through the sintering process and is insoluble in titanium. Titanium foams consisting of a bimodal pore distribution (macropores ranging from 100 to 300 \u03bcm) and 64\u201379% porosity, exhibited yield strengths of 23\u201341 MPa and Young's moduli of 1.6\u20133.7 GPa.<ref name = \"r72\">{{cite journal|author=A. Mansourighasri, N. Muhamad, A. Sulong|title= Processing titanium foams using tapioca starch as a space holder|journal= Journal of Materials Processing Technology |volume=212|issue=1 |year=2012|pages= 83\u201389|doi= 10.1016/j.jmatprotec.2011.08.008}}</ref>\n\n===== Ammonium bicarbonate =====\nAlthough ammonium bicarbonate has been utilized in the manufacturing of titanium foams,<ref name = \"r87\" /> it is not an ideal spacer in that it has a low melting/dissociation point and some solubility in titanium. This results in considerable shrinkage which makes control of pore shape difficult. Furthermore, the decomposition releases environmentally harmful gases.<ref name = \"r51\">{{cite book|author=V. Amig\u00f3 Borr\u00e1s, L. Reig Cerd\u00e1, D.J. Busquets Mataix, J. Ortiz|title= Analysis of bending strength of porous titanium processed by space holder method |year=2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Freeze-casting ===\n[[File: Photos_LSM25_anim_small.gif|thumb|Freeze-casting solidification set-up.]]\n\n[[File:Tifreeze.png|thumb|Compressive strength of freeze-cast titanium materials created via freeze-casting.]]\n\n[[Freeze-casting]] is a directional solidification technique that is utilized to fabricate materials exhibiting anisotropic, elongated pore structures.<ref name = \"r108\">{{cite journal|author=K. Scotti, D. Dunand|title=Freeze casting \u2013 A review of processing, microstructure and properties via the open data repository, Freeze ''Casting''.net|journal=Progress in Materials Science|volume=94|pages=243\u2013305|doi=10.1016/j.pmatsci.2018.01.001|arxiv=1710.00037|year=2018}}</ref> Pore morphology is defined, in large part, by the morphology of the solidified fluid.\nTitanium foams exhibiting [[Dendrite (metal)|dendritic]]<ref name = \"r111\">{{cite journal|author=H. Jung, S. Yook, T. Jang, Y. Li, H. Kim, Y. Koh|title= Dynamic freeze casting for the production of porous titanium (Ti) scaffolds|journal= Mater. Sci. Eng. C|volume= 33|issue=1 |year=2013|pages= 59\u201363|doi= 10.1016/j.msec.2012.08.004|pmid= 25428042}}</ref><ref name = \"r113\">{{cite journal|author=S. Yook, H. Jung, C. Park, K. Shin, Y. Koh, Y. Estrin, H. Kim|title= Reverse freeze casting: A new method for fabricating highly porous titanium scaffolds, with aligned large pores|journal= Acta Biomater.|volume= 8|issue=6 |year=2012|pages= 2401\u20132410|doi= 10.1016/j.actbio.2012.03.020|pmid= 22421310}}</ref> and [[lamellar]]<ref name = \"r109\">{{cite journal|author=Y. Chino, D.C. Dunand|title= Directionally freeze-cast titanium foam with aligned, elongated pores|journal= Acta Mater. |volume=56|issue=1 |year=2008|pages= 105\u2013113|doi= 10.1016/j.actamat.2007.09.002}}</ref> pore structures have been produced, through the use of non-aqueous and aqueous processing respectively. These materials exhibit anisotropic mechanical properties as a result of their anisotropic pore structures. Compressive strength for loads applied parallel to the wall direction of titanium foams are found to be, on average, 2.5 times greater than for those applied perpendicular to the wall direction.<ref name = \"r108\" />\n\n== Applications ==\n\nPotential structural applications for titanium foams include their general incorporation into light-weight structures and as components for mechanical energy absorption. The most important considerations for the use of titanium foams in structural applications includes their porosity, specific strength, ductility in compression and cost. Because of low manufacturing costs, most metal foams marketed for structural applications are of a close-celled aluminum variety.<ref name = \"r117\">{{cite journal|author=Y. Zhao, T. Fung, L. Zhang, F. Zhang|title= Lost carbonate sintering process for manufacturing metal foams|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=52|issue=4 |year=2005|pages= 295\u2013298|doi= 10.1016/j.scriptamat.2004.10.012}}</ref> In comparison, titanium foam manufacturing incurs a higher cost, but this cost is defensible in space applications where the material offers an otherwise incomparable reduction in overall weight. The lower thermal conductivity of titanium may also be appreciated in rocket construction.<ref name = \"r1\" /> The specific strength, overall energy absorbing capability and high melting point all reinforce titanium's superiority to aluminum in aerospace and military applications.<ref name = \"r3\" /> When used for aerospace applications, levels of porosity close to 90% are desired.<ref name = \"r80\">{{cite journal|author=O. Smorygo, A. Marukovich, V. Mikutski, A. Gokhale, G.J. Reddy, J.V. Kumar|title= High-porosity titanium foams by powder coated space holder compaction method|journal= Materials Letters |volume=83 |year=2012|pages= 17\u201319|doi= 10.1016/j.matlet.2012.05.082}}</ref> Titanium foams are capable of retaining their high tensile strength at temperatures up to 400&nbsp;\u00b0C; a limit imposed by the metal's low resistance to oxidation.<ref name = \"r44\" />\n\n=== Aerospace applications ===\nThe driving force for titanium foam's replacement of existing materials in the aerospace sector results from the following five factors:<ref name = \"r44\" />\n*Weight reduction: as a substitute for steels and nickel-based superalloys;\n*Application temperature: as a substitute for aluminum and nickel-based alloys and steels\n*Corrosion resistance: as a substitute for aluminum alloys and low-alloyed steels\n*Galvanic compatibility: with polymer matrix composites as substitutes for aluminum alloys\n*Space constraints: as substitutes for aluminum alloys and steels\n\nThe most urgent problem of engineering and its advanced branch of aerospace engineering is the efficient use of materials as well as increased service life.<ref name = \"r1\" />\n\n==== Sandwich panel cores ====\n[[File: Aluminium composite material.png|thumb|Model of a sandwich panel assembly]]\n\nSandwich panel cores are used throughout the aerospace industry; they are integrated within aircraft bodies, floors and internal panels. Sandwich constructions consist of two faces separated by a thick, light-weight core and are most commonly composed of balsa-wood, foamed polymers, glue-bonded aluminum or Nomex (paper) honeycombs. Typically, the cores are combined with reinforcing fibers to increase their shear modulus.<ref name = \"r118\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1155/2013/589216 |title=A Comparative Study of Ballistic Resistance of Sandwich Panels with Aluminum Foam and Auxetic Honeycomb Cores |journal=Advances in Mechanical Engineering |volume=5 |pages=589216 |year=2013 |last1=Yang |first1=Shu |last2=Qi |first2=Chang |last3=Wang |first3=Dong |last4=Gao |first4=Renjing |last5=Hu |first5=Haitao |last6=Shu |first6=Jian |doi-access=free }}</ref> Indeed, carbon fiber-reinforced polymers exhibit the highest specific stiffness and strength of these materials.<ref name = \"r119\">{{cite journal|author=K. Finnegan, G. Kooistra, H.N. Wadley, V. Deshpande|title= The compressive response of carbon fiber composite pyramidal truss sandwich cores|journal= International Journal of Materials Research |volume=98|issue=12 |year=2007|pages= 1264\u20131272|doi= 10.3139/146.101594|url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f4ff946af3ab18605ace98bd7336988dc8cfd0f6}}</ref><ref name = \"r120\">{{cite journal|author=S. Park, B. Russell, V. Deshpande, N. Fleck|title= Dynamic compressive response of composite square honeycombs|journal= Composites Part A: Applied Science and Manufacturing |volume=43|issue=3 |year=2012|pages= 527\u2013536|doi= 10.1016/j.compositesa.2011.11.022}}</ref> However, polymers decompose at low temperatures; thus employment of the aforementioned materials pose inherent challenges due to the limited range of temperature they may be utilized within as well as their moisture-dependent properties.<ref name = \"r13\" />\nThe largest and most inadequately predicted failure within the core results from strain localization. Strain localization refers to the development of bands exhibiting intensive straining as a result of the localization of deformations in the solid.<ref name = \"r121\">{{cite journal|author=F. Zok, H. Rathbun, M. He, E. Ferri, C. Mercer, R. McMeeking, A. Evans|title= Structural performance of metallic sandwich panels with square honeycomb cores|journal= Philosophical Magazine |volume= 85|issue=26\u201327 |year=2005|pages= 3207\u20133234|doi= 10.1080/14786430500073945|bibcode= 2005PMag...85.3207Z}}</ref>\n<ref name = \"r122\">{{cite journal|author=H. Rathbun, D. Radford, Z. Xue, M. He, J. Yang, V. Deshpande, N. Fleck, J. Hutchinson, F. Zok, A. Evans|title= Performance of metallic honeycomb-core sandwich beams under shock loading|journal= International Journal of Solids and Structures |volume=43|issue=6 |year=2006|pages= 1746\u20131763|doi= 10.1016/j.ijsolstr.2005.06.079}}</ref> For the best performance, the structure should exhibit low peak response force and high total energy absorption.<ref name = \"r18\"/> Titanium foams are lightweight, stiff, and possess the capability to resist blast. Furthermore, the use of titanium-based foams exhibiting homogenous porosity distribution would significantly decrease the risks associated with strain localization. The high strength-to-weight ratio of titanium foams offers an opportunity to provide increased bending and shearing stiffness as well as energy absorption capabilities during periods of bending.<ref name = \"r118\" /><ref name = \"r122\" /><ref name = \"r123\">{{cite journal|author=P. Moongkhamklang, D.M. Elzey, H.N. Wadley|title= Titanium matrix composite lattice structures|journal= Composites Part A: Applied Science and Manufacturing|volume= 39|issue=2 |year=2008|pages= 176\u2013187|doi= 10.1016/j.compositesa.2007.11.007}}</ref> Titanium foams may be utilized in environments with elevated temperatures (up to 400&nbsp;\u00b0C). Composite structures may also be produced; the incorporation of silicon carbide monofilaments into Ti-6-Al-4V foams was shown to exhibit an elastic modulus of 195 GPa and tensile strength of 800 MPa.<ref name = \"r124\">{{cite journal|author=P. Moongkhamklang, V. Deshpande, H. Wadley|title= The compressive and shear response of titanium matrix composite lattice structures|journal= Acta Materialia |volume=58|issue=8 |year=2010|pages= 2822\u20132835|doi= 10.1016/j.actamat.2010.01.004}}</ref>\n\n===== Auxetic structures =====\n[[File:Auxetic nonauxetic.png|thumb]]\nTitanium foams exhibiting auxetic pore structures are of interest for incorporation in sandwich panel cores due to their enhanced shear performance.<ref name = \"r126\">{{cite journal|author=A. Alderson, J. Rasburn, S. Ameer-Beg, P.G. Mullarkey, W. Perrie, K.E. Evans|title= An auxetic filter: a tuneable filter displaying enhanced size selectivity or defouling properties|journal= Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Research |volume=39|issue=3 |year=2000|pages= 654\u2013665|doi= 10.1021/ie990572w}}</ref>\n<ref name = \"r127\">{{cite journal|author=F. Scarpa, L. Ciffo, J. Yates|title= Dynamic properties of high structural integrity auxetic open cell foam|journal= Smart Materials and Structures|volume=13|issue=1 |year=2004|pages= 49\u201356|doi= 10.1088/0964-1726/13/1/006|bibcode= 2004SMaS...13...49S}}</ref> Foams with this pore structure exhibit negative Poisson's ratio in one or more dimensions.<ref name = \"r118\" /> Poisson's ratio is defined as the ratio of the lateral contractile strain to the longitudinal tensile strain for the foam undergoing uniaxial tension in the loading direction.<ref name = \"r128\">{{cite journal|author=A. Alderson|title= A triumph of lateral thought|journal= Chemistry & Industry|volume=10 |year=1999|pages= 384|pmid= 6038772}}</ref> Auxetic materials are typically able to resist indentations through their response to compression; upon compression, the auxetic material contracts.<ref name = \"r128\" /> In addition to indentation resistance, research has shown that auxetic foams offer better absorption of sound and vibration, enhanced shear resistance and facture toughness. These structures also exhibit synclastic bending, which results lends itself to integration within curved sandwich panels.\n\n=== Biomedical implants ===\n[[File:Tifemur.png|thumb|(a) Upper femur with simulated intramedullary rod insert fabricated from Ti-6Al-4V. (b) A through-section cutaway view illustrating inner, more porous foam core surrounded by more dense foam structure for stiffness compatibility.]]\n\n[[Titanium alloy]]s are the choice material for a diverse range of biomedical implants.<ref name = \"r129\">{{cite journal|author=C. Elias, J. Lima, R. Valiev, M. Meyers|title= Biomedical applications of titanium and its alloys|journal= JOM|volume= 60|issue=3 |year=2008|pages= 46\u201349|doi= 10.1007/s11837-008-0031-1|bibcode= 2008JOM....60c..46E}}</ref>\nCurrently employed titanium alloy implants include: hip joints,<ref name = \"r130\">{{cite journal|author=H. Agins, N. Alcock, M. Bansal, E. Salvati, P. Wilson, P. Pellicci, P. Bullough|title= Metallic wear in failed titanium-alloy total hip replacements|journal= J Bone Joint Surg |volume=70|issue=3 |year=1988|pages= 347\u2013356|doi= 10.2106/00004623-198870030-00005}}</ref>\nbone screws,<ref name = \"r9\" /><ref name = \"r131\">{{cite journal|author=D.N. Caborn, W.P. Urban, D.L. Johnson, J. Nyland, D. Pienkowski|title= Biomechanical comparison between BioScrew and titanium alloy interference screws for bone\u2014patellar tendon\u2014bone graft fixation in anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction|journal= Arthroscopy: The Journal of Arthroscopic & Related Surgery|volume=13|issue=2 |year=1997|pages= 229\u2013232|doi= 10.1016/S0749-8063(97)90159-6|pmid= 9127082}}</ref>\nknee joints,<ref name=\"r96\"/> spinal fusions,<ref name = \"r8\" /> shoulder joints,<ref name = \"r96\" /> and bone plates.<ref name = \"r129\" /><ref name = \"r133\">{{cite journal|author=M. Long, H. Rack|title= Titanium alloys in total joint replacement\u2014a materials science perspective|journal= Biomaterials|volume=19|issue=18 |year=1998|pages= 1621\u20131639|doi= 10.1016/S0142-9612(97)00146-4|pmid= 9839998}}</ref><ref name = \"r134\">{{cite journal|author=D.D. Deligianni, N. Katsala, S. Ladas, D. Sotiropoulou, J. Amedee, Y. Missirlis|title= Effect of surface roughness of the titanium alloy Ti\u20136Al\u20134V on human bone marrow cell response and on protein adsorption|journal= Biomaterials |volume=22|issue=11 |year=2001|pages= 1241\u20131251|doi= 10.1016/S0142-9612(00)00274-X|pmid= 11336296}}</ref> These alloys range from high ductility, commercially-pure titanium foams with high formability, to heat-treatable alloys with high strength. Titanium is well-suited for use in [[magnetic resonance imaging]] (MRI) and [[computed tomography]] (CT),<ref name = \"r138\">{{cite journal|author=A. Malik, O. Boyko, N. Aktar, W. Young|title= A comparative study of MR imaging profile of titanium pedicle screws|journal= Acta Radiologica|volume= 42|issue=3 |year=2001|pages= 291\u2013293|doi= 10.1080/028418501127346846}}</ref>\n<ref name = \"r139\">{{cite journal|author=O. Ortiz, T.G. Pait, P. McAllister, K. Sauter|title= Postoperative magnetic resonance imaging with titanium implants of the thoracic and lumbar spine|journal= Neurosurgery |volume=38|issue=4 |year=1996|pages= 741\u2013745|doi= 10.1227/00006123-199604000-00022}}</ref> which further enhances its applicability for biomedical implant applications.\n\n==== Bioimplants: microstructure ====\nBiomedical implants should have low density for patient comfort and high porosity and surface area to facilitate vascularization and the ingrowth of new bone.<ref name = \"r140\">{{cite journal|author=J. Jakubowicz, G. Adamek, M. Dewidar|title= Titanium foam made with saccharose as a space holder|journal= Journal of Porous Materials |volume=20|issue=5 |year=2013|pages= 1137\u20131141|doi= 10.1007/s10934-013-9696-0|doi-access=free}}</ref> Ideally, the implant will allow sufficiently easy fluid flow for cell nutrition and osteoblast multiplication as well as migration for cellular colonization of the implant to become uniform. The pores contained within the foam's cellular matrix mimic the extracellular matrix of bone, allowing the body to fixate with the implant. The porosity of the implant also promotes apposition and facilitates vascularization\u2212as cells are able to attach, reproduce and form basic functions.<ref name = \"r86\" /> It has been shown that a macropore size of 200\u2013500&nbsp;\u00b5m is preferred for ingrowths of new bone tissues and transportation of body fluids. The lower bound is controlled by the size of cells (~20&nbsp;\u00b5m), and the upper bound is related to the specific surface area through the availability of binding sites.<ref name = \"r86\">{{cite journal|author=C. Wen, M. Mabuchi, Y. Yamada, K. Shimojima, Y. Chino, T. Asahina|title= Processing of biocompatible porous Ti and Mg|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=45|issue=10 |year=2001|pages= 1147\u20131153|doi= 10.1016/S1359-6462(01)01132-0}}</ref> Finer pores further help in tissue growth and biofluid movement.<ref name = \"r141\">{{cite journal|author=K. Abshagen, I. Schrodi, T. Gerber, B. Vollmar|title= In vivo analysis of biocompatibility and vascularization of the synthetic bone grafting substitute NanoBone\u00ae|journal= Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part A |volume=91|issue=2 |year=2009|pages= 557\u2013566|doi= 10.1002/jbm.a.32237|pmid= 18985779}}</ref> Anisotropic, elongated pores (such as those attainable via the freeze-casting technique) may be beneficial in bone implants in that they can further mimic the structure of bone.\n\nThe porous surface geometry of the foam promotes bone in-growth, provides anchorage for fixation, and ensures stresses are transferred from the implant to the bone.<ref name = \"r37\">{{cite journal|author=I.-H. Oh, N. Nomura, N. Masahashi, S. Hanada|title= Mechanical properties of porous titanium compacts prepared by powder sintering|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=49|issue=12 |year=2003|pages= 1197\u20131202|doi= 10.1016/j.scriptamat.2003.08.018}}</ref> Surface roughness in the pore can enhance bone in-growth, and coarser cell size facilitates faster tissue growth.<ref name = \"r88\" />\nTo optimize the implant's functionality and ability to successfully fuse with bone, it may be necessary to manipulate the material's manufacturing methods in order to modify the foam's pore structure. Changes in pore structure can directly influence implant strength as well as other key properties.\n\n==== Bioimplants: mechanical properties ====\n\nHuman cancellous bone possesses a stiffness ranging from 12 to 23 GPa;<ref name = \"r142\">{{cite journal|author=C. Greiner, S.M. Oppenheimer, D.C. Dunand|title= High strength, low stiffness, porous NiTi with superelastic properties|journal= Acta Biomaterialia|volume=1|issue=6 |year=2005|pages= 705\u2013716|doi= 10.1016/j.actbio.2005.07.005|pmid= 16701851}}</ref> careful control and modification of manufacturing parameters to achieve similar strengths is imperative for practicality of integration.<ref name = \"r143\">{{cite journal|author=M.S. Aly|title= Effect of pore size on the tensile behavior of open-cell Ti foams: Experimental results|journal= Materials Letters |volume=64|issue=8 |year=2010|pages= 935\u2013937|doi= 10.1016/j.matlet.2010.01.064}}</ref> Correctly predicting the Young's modulus for foams is imperative for actual biomedical integration; a mismatch of Young's moduli between the implant and the bone can result in stress-shielding effects from a disproportional handling of stress.<ref name = \"r144\">{{cite journal|author=L.E. Murr, S.M. Gaytan, E. Martinez, F. Medina, R.B. Wicker|title= Next generation orthopaedic implants by additive manufacturing using electron beam melting|journal= International Journal of Biomaterials |volume= 2012|pages= 1\u201314|year=2012|doi= 10.1155/2012/245727|pmid= 22956957|pmc= 3432366}}</ref> The implant which typically exhibits a higher Young's modulus than the bone will absorb most of the load. As a result of this imbalance, the starting bone density will be reduced, there will be tissue death and, eventually, implant failure.<ref name = \"r145\">{{cite journal|author=H. Li, S.M. Oppenheimer, S.I. Stupp, D.C. Dunand, L.C. Brinson|title= Effects of pore morphology and bone ingrowth on mechanical properties of microporous titanium as an orthopaedic implant material|journal= Materials Transactions |volume=45|issue=4 |year=2004|pages= 1124\u20131131|doi= 10.2320/matertrans.45.1124|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nNatural bone exhibits the ability to adjust local fiber away from the low-stress regions toward high stress regions through the distribution of porosity, thus maximizing overall comfort.<ref name = \"r146\">{{cite journal|author=Y. Conde, A. Pollien, A. Mortensen|title= Functional grading of metal foam cores for yield-limited lightweight sandwich beams|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=54|issue=4 |year=2006|pages= 539\u2013543|doi= 10.1016/j.scriptamat.2005.10.050|url= http://infoscience.epfl.ch/record/90711}}</ref> Using finite element analysis, researchers examined the effect of filling pores with bone on mechanical properties.<ref name = \"r145\" /> They concluded that bone ingrowth significantly improved the mechanical properties, evidenced by decreased localized plasticity and stress concentrations. In effect, the titanium foam in the study allowed the bone to exhibit its natural ability to adjust local fiber away from the low-stress regions toward high stress regions.\n\nExperiments demonstrated that random combinations of pore size and shape result in lower Young's moduli. Theoretical models for the quantification of Young's moduli do not account for random pore size and shape distribution, so experimental measurements must be conducted in the presence of heterogeneous pore size and distribution. This is a limitation of the micro-mechanical models discussed above.\n\n==== Osseointegration ====\nCurrently utilized implants take a great deal of time to integrate with the body after the initial surgical procedure occurs. True adhesion between the implant and the bone has been difficult to achieve and, unfortunately, success rates of implant fixation are low due to the implant's failure to achieve long-term osseointegration into the bone.<ref name = \"r95\" /><ref name = \"r96\" /><ref name = \"r147\">{{cite journal|author=H.-W. Kim, Y.-H. Koh, L.-H. Li, S. Lee, H.-E. Kim|title= Hydroxyapatite coating on titanium substrate with titania buffer layer processed by sol\u2013gel method|journal= Biomaterials |volume=25|issue=13 |year=2004|pages= 2533\u20132538|doi= 10.1016/j.biomaterials.2003.09.041}}</ref> With an increasing number of individuals requiring orthopedic implants,<ref name = \"r11\" /> the development of materials with structural and biological potential to improve osseointegration is crucial. Utilization of titanium-based foams present one way to potentially improve the bioactivity <ref name = \"r6\" /><ref name = \"r149\">{{cite journal|author=V.D. Rani, K. Manzoor, D. Menon, N. Selvamurugan, S.V. Nair|title= The design of novel nanostructures on titanium by solution chemistry for an improved osteoblast response|journal= Nanotechnology |volume=20|issue=19 |year=2009|pages= 195101|doi= 10.1088/0957-4484/20/19/195101|pmid= 19420629|bibcode= 2009Nanot..20s5101D}}</ref><ref name = \"r150\">{{cite journal|author=B.K. Nayak, M.C. Gupta|title= Self-organized micro/nano structures in metal surfaces by ultrafast laser irradiation|journal= Optics and Lasers in Engineering |volume=48|issue=10 |year=2010|pages= 940\u2013949|doi= 10.1016/j.optlaseng.2010.04.010|bibcode= 2010OptLE..48..940N}}</ref><ref name = \"r151\">{{cite journal|author=R. Karpagavalli, A. Zhou, P. Chellamuthu, K. Nguyen|title= Corrosion behavior and biocompatibility of nanostructured TiO<sub>2</sub> film on Ti6Al4V|journal= Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part A |volume=83|issue=4 |year=2007|pages= 1087\u20131095|doi= 10.1002/jbm.a.31447|pmid= 17584904}}</ref> and reduce stress-shielding effects of currently employed bioimplant materials.\n\nThe problem of osseointegration is best understood by examining the process of natural bone growth. In the body, bone and tissues experience self-regeneration, and structural modifications occur normally in response to environmental stimuli.<ref name = \"r152\">{{cite journal|author=D.W. Hutmacher|title= Scaffolds in tissue engineering bone and cartilage|journal= Biomaterials |volume=21|issue=24 |year=2000|pages= 2529\u20132543|doi= 10.1016/S0142-9612(00)00121-6}}</ref> Successful osseointegration occurs in three main stages that follow a natural biologically determined procedure: 1) incorporation of the implant into the bone's formation, 2) adaption of the new bone mass to carry weight and 3) remodeling of the new bone structure. The first stage in this process is the most crucial for overall success;<ref name = \"r153\" /> the implant and the bone must form a rapid connection, and this bond must be strong and enduring. Owing to its porous structure, a titanium metal foam implant may be able to achieve close fixation with the bone and will decrease patient recovery time considerably. Essentially, the foam becomes an extracellular matrix in the body as tissue is integrated into it.<ref name = \"r86\" /> Today, the implants most commonly used for bone replacement lack the ability to promote these characteristics, which are found in natural bone and, as a result, the implants have limited lifetimes.<ref name = \"r86\" /> This phenomenon of osseointegration works similarly to direct fracture healing. However, instead of a bone fragment-end reconnecting to bone, the fragment-end connects to an implant surface.<ref name = \"r153\">{{cite journal|author=S.N. Khan, M. Ramachandran, S.S. Kumar, V. Krishnan, R. Sundaram|title= Osseointegration and more\u2013A review of literature|journal= Indian Journal of Dentistry |volume=3|issue=2 |year=2012|pages= 72\u201376|doi= 10.1016/j.ijd.2012.03.012}}</ref> In a study on fibroblastic interactions with high-porosity [[Titanium alloy|Ti6Al4V]] alloy, the metal foam was supportive of cell attachment and proliferation, migration through the porous network, and proved capable of sustaining a large cell population.<ref name = \"r7\" />\n\n==== Increasing bioactivity via coatings ====\nTitanium's propensity to form an oxide layer on its surface prevents corrosion of surfaces that are in contact with human tissues because the surface oxides minimize diffusion of metal ions from the bulk material to the surface.<ref name = \"r144\" /> When titanium gains a coating to make it more bioactive, it can turn the already biocompatible titanium surface into an interface able to enhance osteoblast adhesion and able to promote osseointegration.<ref name = \"r145\" /> Today, research is heavily focused on improving the success rate of integration and uses an understanding of the natural process of bone growth and repair to create coatings that will enhance the surface finish and surface properties of the implant. These adjustments allow the artificial structure to mimic biological materials and to gain acceptance into the body with fewer negative side effects.<ref name = \"r155\">{{cite journal|author=M. Lutolf, J. Hubbell|title= Synthetic biomaterials as instructive extracellular microenvironments for morphogenesis in tissue engineering|journal= Nature Biotechnology |volume=23|issue=1 |year=2005|pages= 47\u201355|doi= 10.1038/nbt1055|pmid= 15637621}}</ref><ref name = \"r156\">{{cite journal|author=Z. Tang, N.A. Kotov, S. Magonov, B. Ozturk|title= Nanostructured artificial nacre|journal= Nature Materials |volume=2|issue=6 |year=2003|pages= 413\u20138|doi= 10.1038/nmat906|pmid= 12764359|bibcode= 2003NatMa...2..413T}}</ref>\nA 3-year clinical and radiographic study found implants in humans coated by nanocrystalline [[hydroxylapatite]] (HA) to support osseointegration. The nanocrystalline HA was developed with a large rough surface of interconnecting pores between 10 and 20&nbsp;nm of the silica matrix gel, resulting in a porous bone structure. Mean rates of marginal bone loss were insignificant and the periotest values were indicative of a solid osseointegration.<ref name = \"r157\">{{cite journal|author=F. Heinemann, T. Mundt, R. Biffar, T. Gedrange, W. Goetz|title= A 3-year clinical and radiographic study of implants placed simultaneously with maxillary sinus floor augmentations using a new nanocrystalline hydroxyapatite|journal= Journal of Physiology and Pharmacology |volume=60 |year=2009|pages= 91\u201397|pmid=20400800}}</ref>\nIn effect, the pores are structured in such a way that they are able hold onto the proteins on the biomaterial's surface. Ideally, this allows the body to engage in self-repair in that the synthetic HA is recognized as a like-nanomaterial in which live tissues may develop<ref name = \"r10\" />\n\nTitanium foams can be coated with HA through various methods including plasma spraying, sol-gel and electrophoretic deposition. It has been shown that HA-coated titanium exhibits increased interfacial strength in comparison to titanium foams without the coating. In an effort to enhance bone in-growth, Spoerke et al. developed a method for growing organoapatites on titanium implants. Organoapatites may assist in-bone in-growth at the implant interface. The foams were manufactured using a modified HIP process, which exploits the allotropic nature of titanium to create higher porosity foams. Previous in vitro experimentation with the organoapatite-titanium foam held promising results including the possibility that ingrown tissue within these coated pores will improve the lifetime use of the foam through reduction of stress-shielding effects.<ref name = \"r50\" />\n\n==== Animal studies ====\nIn the lab, synthetic nanocrystalline bone grafting material in mice has shown in-growth of vascularized fibrous tissue which resulted in improved healing. Furthermore, new blood vessels were observed at day 5 after implantation, and the implant showed a high functional vessel density.<ref name = \"r141\" /> In a study examining the femoral epiphyses of rabbits in two to eight weeks of healing, bone-to-implant contact was compared to bone growth inside the chambers for four different implant surfaces. The researchers found that bone substitute materials may improve the bone apposition onto titanium.<ref name = \"r158\">{{cite journal|author=B.M. Willie, X. Yang, N.H. Kelly, J. Merkow, S. Gagne, R. Ware, T.M. Wright, M.P. Bostrom|title= Osseointegration into a novel titanium foam implant in the distal femur of a rabbit|journal= Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part B: Applied Biomaterials|volume= 92|issue=2 |year=2010|pages= 479\u2013488|pmc=2860654|pmid= 20024964|doi= 10.1002/jbm.b.31541}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Metal foam]]\n* [[Titanium]]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube| hdscnna5r1Q |title=Bone ingrowth in NRC Ti Foam}}\n* {{YouTube| 6No-EpeC20w |title=Experimental investigation of a titanium foam at low and high strain rates}}\n* {{YouTube| XDwyH3z_e2M |title=A Novel Titanium Foam for Orthopedic Load-Bearing}}\n* {{YouTube| _LV4VSeQ44M |title=New Age Titanium Foams for More Successful Dental Implants}}\n* {{YouTube| 1eIJGtBEYS4 |title=Metal Foam \u2013 Innovation Nation}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Titanium foam}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Foams]]\n[[Category:Metals]]\n", "text_old": "'''[[Titanium]] foams''' exhibit high specific strength, high energy absorption, excellent corrosion resistance and [[biocompatibility]]. These materials are ideally suited for applications within the [[aerospace]] industry.<ref name=\"r1\" >{{cite journal|author=A. Ermachenko, R.Y. Lutfullin, R. Mulyukov|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/287453168|title= Advanced technologies of processing titanium alloys and their applications in industry|journal= Rev. Adv. Mater. Sci|volume=29 |year=2011|pages= 68\u201382}}</ref><ref name=\"r2\">{{cite journal|author=K. Hurysz, J. Clark, A. Nagel, C. Hardwicke, K. Lee, J. Cochran, T. Sanders|doi=10.1557/PROC-521-191|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/231901144|title= Steel and titanium hollow sphere foams|journal= MRS Online Proceedings Library Archive |volume=521 |year=1998}}</ref><ref name=\"r3\">{{cite journal|author=A. Salimon, Y. Brechet, M. Ashby, A. Greer|title= Potential applications for steel and titanium metal foams|journal= Journal of Materials Science |volume= 40|issue=22 |year=2005|pages= 5793\u20135799|doi= 10.1007/s10853-005-4993-x|bibcode= 2005JMatS..40.5793S}}</ref> An inherent resistance to corrosion allows the foam to be a desirable candidate for various filtering applications.<ref name=\"r4\">{{cite journal|author=L. Gauckler, M. Waeber, C. Conti, M. Jacob-Duliere|title= Ceramic foam for molten metal filtration|journal= JOM Journal of the Minerals, Metals and Materials Society 37|volume= 37|issue=9 |year=1985|pages= 47\u201350|doi= 10.1007/BF03258640|bibcode= 1985JOM....37i..47G}}</ref><ref name=\"r5\">{{cite journal|author=L.P. Lefebvre, J. Banhart, D.C. Dunand|title= Porous Metals and Metallic Foams: Current Status and Recent Developments|journal= Advanced Engineering Materials|volume=10|issue=9 |year=2008|pages= 775\u2013787|doi= 10.1002/adem.200800241}}</ref> Further, titanium's physiological inertness makes its porous form a promising candidate for [[biomedical]] implantation devices.<ref name=\"r6\">{{cite journal|author=J.R. Bush, B.K. Nayak, L.S. Nair, M.C. Gupta, C.T. Laurencin|title= Improved bio\u2010implant using ultrafast laser induced self\u2010assembled nanotexture in titanium|journal= Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part B: Applied Biomaterials |volume= 97|issue=2 |year=2011|pages= 299\u2013305|doi= 10.1002/jbm.b.31815|pmid= 21394901}}</ref><ref name=\"r7\">{{cite journal|author=N. Cheung, I. Ferreira, M. Pariona, J. Quaresma, A. Garcia|title= Melt characteristics and solidification growth direction with respect to gravity affecting the interfacial heat transfer coefficient of chill castings|journal= Materials & Design |volume=30|issue=9 |year=2009|pages= 3592\u20133601|doi= 10.1016/j.matdes.2009.02.025}}</ref><ref name=\"r8\">{{cite journal|author=F.B. Christensen|title= Lumbar spinal fusion. Outcome in relation to surgical methods, choice of implant and postoperative rehabilitation|journal= Acta Orthopaedica Scandinavica|volume=75|issue=313 |year=2004|pages= 2\u201343|doi= 10.1080/03008820410002057}}</ref><ref name=\"r9\">{{cite journal|author=F.B. Christensen, M. Dalstra, F. Sejling, S. Overgaard, C. B\u00fcnger|title= Titanium-alloy enhances bone-pedicle screw fixation: mechanical and histomorphometrical results of titanium-alloy versus stainless steel|journal= European Spine Journal |volume= 9|issue=2 |year=2000|pages= 97\u2013103|doi= 10.1007/s005860050218|pmid= 10823424|pmc= 3611362}}</ref><ref name=\"r10\">{{cite journal|author=R. Kanaparthy, A. Kanaparthy|title= The changing face of dentistry: nanotechnology|journal= International Journal of Nanomedicine  |volume= 6|year=2011|pages= 2799\u2013804|doi= 10.2147/IJN.S24353|pmid= 22131826|pmc= 3224707}}</ref><ref name=\"r11\">{{cite journal|author=E.K. Simpson, R.A. James, D.A. Eitzen, R.W. Byard|title= Role of orthopedic implants and bone morphology in the identification of human remains|journal= Journal of Forensic Sciences |volume=52|issue=2 |year=2007|pages= 442\u2013448|doi= 10.1111/j.1556-4029.2006.00370.x|pmid= 17316248}}</ref> The largest advantage in fabricating titanium foams is that the mechanical and functional properties can be adjusted through manufacturing manipulations that vary [[porosity]] and cell morphology. The high appeal of titanium foams is directly correlated to a multi-industry demand for advancement in this technology.\n\n== Characterization ==\n\nBanhart<ref name=\"r12\">{{cite journal|author=J. Banhart|title= Manufacture, characterization and application of cellular metals and metal foams|journal= Progress in Materials Science|volume= 46|issue=6 |year=2001|pages= 559\u2013632|doi= 10.1016/S0079-6425(00)00002-5}}</ref> describes two dominating perspectives in which cellular metals are characterized, referring to them as atomistic and macroscopic. The atomistic (or molecular) perspective holds that a cellular material is a construction of struts, membranes, and other elements which possess mechanical properties of their bulk metal counterpart. Indeed, the physical, mechanical, and thermal properties of titanium foams are commonly measured using the same methods as that of their solid counterparts. However, special precautions must be taken due to the cellular structure of metal foams.<ref name=\"r13\">{{cite book|author=M.F. Ashby|title= Metal foams: a design guide|publisher= Butterworth-Heinemann|year=2000}}</ref> From a macroscopic perspective, the cellular structure is perceived as a homogenous structure and characterized by considering the effective (or averaged) material parameters.<ref name = \"r12\" />\n\n== Microstructure ==\n\nTitanium foams are characterized structurally by their pore topology (relative percentage of open vs. closed pores), [[porosity]] (the multiplicative inverse of relative density), pore size and shape, and anisotropy.<ref name = \"r13\" /> Microstructures are most often examined by [[optical microscopy]],<ref name=\"r14\">{{cite journal|author=J.C. Li, D.C. Dunand|title= Mechanical properties of directionally freeze-cast titanium foams|journal= Acta Materialia |volume=59|issue=1 |year=2011|pages= 146\u2013158|doi= 10.1016/j.actamat.2010.09.019}}</ref> [[scanning electron microscopy]] <ref name=\"r15\">{{cite journal|author=B. Ye, D.C. Dunand|title= Titanium foams produced by solid-state replication of NaCl powders|journal= Materials Science and Engineering A|volume=528|issue=2 |year=2010|pages= 691\u2013697|doi= 10.1016/j.msea.2010.09.054}}</ref> and [[X-ray tomography]].<ref name=\"r16\">{{cite journal|author=J.L. Fife, J.C. Li, D.C. Dunand, P.W. Voorhees|title= Morphological analysis of pores in directionally freeze-cast titanium foams|journal= J. Mater. Res.|volume=24|issue=1 |year=2009|pages= 117\u2013124|doi= 10.1557/JMR.2009.0023|bibcode= 2009JMatR..24..117F|url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/43a0585841f5705f8160bf6f6e81d25465a6139c}}</ref>\n\nCategorizing titanium foams in terms of pore structure (as either open- or close-celled) is the most basic form of differentiation. In close-celled foams, pores are composed of bubbles entrapped in the metallic solid. These foams consist of a continuous network of sealed pores wherein interconnections between the pores are virtually non-existent. Alternatively, in open-celled foams, the pores are interconnected and solid struts allow fluid to pass through.<ref name = \"r17\">{{cite journal|author=L.J. Gibson|title= Cellular solids|journal= MRS Bulletin|volume=28|issue=4 |year=2003|pages= 270\u2013271|doi= 10.1557/mrs2003.79|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nMost manufactured foams contain both types of pores, although in many cases the subtype is minimal.<ref name = \"r18\">{{cite journal|author=J. Luyten, S. Mullens, I. Thijs|title= Designing with pores-synthesis and applications|journal= KONA Powder and Particle Journal|volume=28 |year=2010|pages= 131\u2013142|doi= 10.14356/kona.2010012|doi-access= free}}</ref>\nAccording to the [[IUPAC]], pore sizes are classified into three categories: micro (less than 2&nbsp;nm), meso (between 2 and 50&nbsp;nm) and macro (larger than 50&nbsp;nm) pores.<ref name = \"r18\" />\n\n== Mechanical properties ==\n\nAs with other metal foams, the properties of titanium foams depend mostly on the properties of the starting material and the relative density of the resultant foam. Thermal properties in foams \u2013 such as melting point, specific heat and expansion coefficient \u2013 remain constant for both the foams and the metals from which they are composed. However, the mechanical properties of foams are greatly influenced by [[microstructure]], which include the aforementioned properties as well as anisotropy and defects within the foam's structure.<ref name = \"r21\">{{cite journal|author=P. Kelly, D. Nowell|title= Three-dimensional cracks with Dugdale-type plastic zones|journal= International Journal of Fracture|volume=106|issue=4 |year=2000|pages= 291\u2013309|doi= 10.1023/A:1026557509000}}</ref>\n\n=== Sensitivity to impurities ===\nThe [[mechanical properties]] of titanium foams are sensitive to the presence of interstitial solutes, which present limitations to processing routes and utilization. Titanium has a high affinity for [[atmospheric gases]]. In foams, this is evidenced by the metal's tendency to trap oxides within cell edges.<ref name = \"r22\">{{cite journal|author=M. Barrab\u00e9s, A. Michiardi, C. Aparicio, P. Sevilla, J.A. Planell, F.J. Gil|title= Oxidized nickel\u2013titanium foams for bone reconstructions: chemical and mechanical characterization|journal= Journal of Materials Science: Materials in Medicine|volume=18|issue=11 |year=2007|pages= 2123\u20132129|doi= 10.1007/s10856-007-3012-y|pmid= 17619983}}</ref><ref name = \"r23\">{{cite journal|author=D.C. Dunand|title= Processing of titanium foams|journal= Advanced Engineering Materials |volume= 6|issue= 6|year=2004|pages= 369\u2013376|doi= 10.1002/adem.200405576}}</ref><ref name = \"r24\">{{cite journal|author=L.-P. Lefebvre, E. Baril|title= Effect of oxygen concentration and distribution on the compression properties on titanium foams|journal= Advanced Engineering Materials|volume=10|issue=9 |year=2008|pages= 868\u2013876|doi= 10.1002/adem.200800122|url=https://nrc-publications.canada.ca/eng/view/fulltext/?id=bbf9fdc9-0320-4a33-bda4-624e9ee59772}}</ref>\nMicro-hardness of cell walls, [[elastic modulus]], and [[yield strength]] increase as a result of interstitial solutes; [[ductility]], which is a function of the quantity of interstitial impurities, is consequently reduced.<ref name = \"r25\">{{cite journal|author=N. Jha, D. Mondal, J. Dutta Majumdar, A. Badkul, A. Jha, A. Khare|title= Highly porous open cell Ti-foam using NaCl as temporary space holder through powder metallurgy route|journal= Materials & Design |volume=47 |year=2013|pages= 810\u2013819|doi= 10.1016/j.matdes.2013.01.005}}</ref> Of the atmospheric gases, nitrogen has the most significant impact, followed by oxygen and carbon.<ref name = \"r27\">{{cite journal|author=J. Luyten, S. Mullens, I. Thijs|title= Designing with pores\u2014synthesis and applications|journal= KONA Powder Part J|volume=28 |year=2010|pages= 131\u2013142|doi= 10.14356/kona.2010012|doi-access= free}}</ref>\nThese impurities are often present in the precursor mixture and also introduced during processing.\n\n=== Theoretical models for predicting mechanical properties ===\n==== Gibson & Ashby models ====\n\nGibson & Ashby<ref name = \"r17\"/> micromechanical models for [[porous materials]] provide mathematical equations for the prediction of mechanical parameters based on experimentally determined geometric constants. The constants of proportionality are determined by fitting experimental data to various mathematical models for structures consisting of cubes and solid struts and are dependent upon cell geometry. A limitation of the Gibson & Ashby <ref name=\"r17\" /> model is that it is most accurate for foams exhibiting porosities higher than 70%, although experimental comparisons for lower porosity foams have shown agreement with this model. Ye & Dunand found reasonable agreement to the Gibson & Ashby model for titanium foams exhibiting 42% porosity. Ultrasonic measurements provided an average [[Young's modulus]] value of 39 GPa, which is in relatively good agreement with the Gibson & Ashby prediction of 35 GPa.<ref name=\"r15\"/>\n\nThe Gibson & Ashby<ref name=\"r17\" /> models assume ideal structures; microstructural irregularities (e.g. inhomogeneous pore distribution; defects) are not considered. Additionally, experimental results from which the predetermined proportionality constants were based on experimental values that were obtained from simple compression tests. Consequently, they may not be applicable for multiaxial loads.<ref name = \"r28\">{{cite journal|author=S. Maiti, L. Gibson, M. Ashby|title= Deformation and energy absorption diagrams for cellular solids|journal= Acta Metallurgica|volume= 32|issue=11 |year=1984|pages= 1963\u20131975|doi= 10.1016/0001-6160(84)90177-9}}</ref>\n\n==== Minimum solid area (MSA) models ====\n\nMinimum solid area models assume that the load bearing area (cross-sectional area normal to the stress) is the logical basis for modeling mechanical behavior. MSA models assume pore interaction results in reduction of stress. Therefore, the minimum solid areas are the carriers of stress. As a result, predicted mechanical properties fluctuate based on the quantification of the solid area of the foam. For titanium foams consisting of partially sintered powders, the minimum solid area consists of the neck area between powders through the cross-section of cell walls between macropores.<ref name = \"r31\">{{cite journal|author=Z. Esen, \u015e. Bor|title= Processing of titanium foams using magnesium spacer particles|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=56|issue=5 |year=2007|pages= 341\u2013344|doi= 10.1016/j.scriptamat.2006.11.010}}</ref>\nThe mathematical relationships in MSA models<ref name = \"r32\">{{cite journal|author=R. Rice|title= Evaluation and extension of physical property-porosity models based on minimum solid area|journal= Journal of Materials Science |volume=31|issue=1 |year=1996|pages= 102\u2013118|doi= 10.1007/BF00355133|bibcode= 1996JMatS..31..102R}}</ref>\nare relatively consistent with the Gibson & Ashby model.<ref name = \"r17\" /><ref name = \"r33\">{{cite journal|author=R. Rice|title= Comparison of stress concentration versus minimum solid area based mechanical property-porosity relations|journal= Journal of Materials Science |volume= 28|issue=8 |year=1993|pages= 2187\u20132190|doi= 10.1007/BF00367582|bibcode= 1993JMatS..28.2187R}}</ref>\nHowever, the MSA models are designed to predict mechanical property parameters over a broader range of porosity levels. Like the Gibson & Ashby models, MSA models were derived assuming idealized (defect-free) structures containing uniform pore shapes, size and distribution.\n\n=== Compressive properties ===\n\nThe most frequently reported mechanical property of titanium foams is compressive strength.<ref name = \"r34\" /> It was generally accepted that the compressive properties of metal foams depended on the properties of the cell wall rather than on pore size. However, more recent research has indicated that smaller pore sizes equate to higher compressive strength. As pore sizes reach nano-dimensions, the relationship is even more clear due to changes in deformation mechanism.<ref name = \"r35\">{{cite journal|author=X. Wang, X. Wei, C. Wen, F. Han|title= Fabrication and characterisation of microporous titanium|journal= Powder Metallurgy |volume=54|issue=1 |year=2011|pages= 56\u201358|doi= 10.1179/174329009X409660}}</ref>\n\nTuncer & Arslan fabricated titanium foams via the space-holder method using various shaped space-holders to elucidate the effect of cell morphology on mechanical properties. They found that foams created with needle-like urea space-holders exhibited a decrease in elastic modulus and yield strength when compared to spherical pores.<ref name = \"r36\">{{cite journal|author=N. Tuncer and G. Arslan|title= Designing compressive properties of titanium foams|journal= Journal of Materials Science |volume=44|issue=6 |year=2009|pages= 1477\u20131484|doi= 10.1007/s10853-008-3167-z|bibcode= 2009JMatS..44.1477T}}</ref>\n\n== Processing methods ==\n\nMany metal foam manufacturing techniques are accomplished by the introduction of a gaseous phase into a precursor matrix, which can occur in either molten metal or a powdered metal form. Due to titanium's high melting point (1670&nbsp;\u00b0C) and high chemical affinity with oxygen, nitrogen, carbon and hydrogen (which dissolve rapidly either in liquid or solid titanium at a temperature above 400&nbsp;\u00b0C<ref name = \"r23\" />), solid-state processes based on powder densification are the preferred method of fabrication.<ref name = \"r15\" /><ref name = \"r23\" /><ref name = \"r31\" /><ref name = \"r34\">{{cite journal|author=M.M. Shbeh, R. Goodall|title= Open Celled Porous Titanium|journal= Advanced Engineering Materials|volume=19|issue=11 |pages= 1600664|year=2017|doi= 10.1002/adem.201600664|url= http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/116328/3/Open%20Celled%20Porous%20Ti%20Review.pdf}}</ref><ref name = \"r40\">{{cite journal|author=N. Davis, J. Teisen, C. Schuh, D. Dunand|title= Solid-state foaming of titanium by superplastic expansion of argon-filled pores|journal= Journal of Materials Research|volume=16|issue=5 |year=2001|pages= 1508\u20131519|doi= 10.1557/JMR.2001.0210|bibcode= 2001JMatR..16.1508D|url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/2bda2e4ec9f05d05d4943280f18a218a1e0c1539}}</ref><ref name = \"r41\">{{cite journal|author=D. Elzey, H. Wadley|title= The limits of solid state foaming|journal= Acta Materialia |volume=49|issue=5 |year=2001|pages= 849\u2013859|doi= 10.1016/S1359-6454(00)00395-5}}</ref>\nProcessing methods must also be designed to avoid exposure to air or moisture; vacuum or inert gas sintering processes are usually sufficient for preventing contamination.<ref name = \"r23\" /><ref name = \"r42\">{{cite journal|author=L.P. Lefebvre, E. Baril|title= Effect of oxygen concentration and distribution on the compression properties on titanium foams|journal= Advanced Engineering Materials|volume=10|issue=9 |year=2008|pages= 868\u2013876|doi= 10.1002/adem.200800122}}</ref>\n\n=== Loose-powder (gravity) sintering ===\n[[File: TitaniumUSGOV.jpg |thumb|Titanium powder]]\n[[File:Tisponge.png|thumb|Titanium sponge cylinder produced via powder metallurgy, 120 grams, 3\u00d74 cm.]]\n\nUtilizing [[powder metallurgy]] routes<ref name = \"r43\">{{cite book|author=W.D. Callister, D.G. Rethwisch|title= Materials science and engineering: an introduction|publisher= Wiley New York|year=2007}}</ref> for titanium foam fabrication allows for production at lower temperatures than those required through a melt process and reduces overall risks for contamination. In loose-powder sintering (also known as gravity sintering), pores are created through diffusion bonding arising from the voids existing between packed powder particles. Axial compaction followed by sintering follows the same procedure as above, but pressures is applied for compaction of the precursor material.<ref name = \"r44\">{{cite book|author=C. Leyens, M. Peters|title= Titanium and titanium alloys|publisher= Wiley |year=2003}}</ref> For both compaction methods, the resulting pore morphology is dependent upon the morphology of the metallic powder, making it difficult to control the size, shape, and distribution of the pores.<ref name = \"r43\" /> Another disadvantage includes the relatively high probability of pore collapse and limited achievable porosity levels.<ref name = \"r46\">{{cite journal|author=L. Zhang, Y. Zhao|title= Fabrication of high melting-point porous metals by lost carbonate sintering process via decomposition route|journal= Proceedings of the Institution of Mechanical Engineers, Part B: Journal of Engineering Manufacture |volume=222|issue=2 |year=2008|pages= 267\u2013271|doi= 10.1243/09544054JEM832|url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/78115c7fd8112c6a9f48eb8111476d8e30135e5e}}</ref>\n\n=== Expansion of pressurized bubbles ===\n[[File:Tiargon.png|thumb|Titanium foamed with argon]]\nTo produce titanium foams via expansion of pressurized gas, the titanium precursor mixture is placed within a gas-tight metal can, which is evacuated after filling. The metal can is pressurized with inert gas\u2014most commonly argon \u2013 and is pressed isostatically. The gas-filled pores are contained within the compacted matrix, and upon exposure to elevated temperatures, these bubbles expand through creep of the surrounding metal matrix.<ref name = \"r47\">{{cite journal|author=A. Kennedy, S. Asavavisitchai|title= Effects of TiB<sub>2</sub> particle addition on the expansion, structure and mechanical properties of PM Al foams|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=50|issue=1 |year=2004|pages= 115\u2013119|doi= 10.1016/j.scriptamat.2003.09.026}}</ref> Since processing titanium foams using [[hot isostatic pressing]] (HIP) eliminates the need for separate compaction and sintering processes, a wider variety of custom shapes and sizes are possible than via loose powder sintering techniques.<ref name = \"r48\">{{cite journal|author=M. Sharma, G. Gupta, O. Modi, B. Prasad|title= PM processed titanium foam: influence of morphology and content of space holder on microstructure and mechanical properties|journal= Powder Metallurgy|volume= 56|issue=1 |year=2013|pages= 55\u201360|doi= 10.1179/1743290112Y.0000000036}}</ref> Disadvantages of this process include reduced pore connectivity, limited achievable porosity, and a complicated experimental set-up.<ref name = \"r48\" /> However, a unique aspect of the HIP process with respect to titanium (and other polymorphic materials) is that transformation superplasticity can be enhanced through the HIP process by way of thermal cycling, or by cycling around the alpha/beta allotropic temperature boundaries of the metal.<ref name = \"r40\" />\n\n=== Superplastic expansion ===\nTitanium undergoes allotropic transformation from its \u03b1-phase (hexagonal close-packed (hcp) structure at temperatures less than 882.5&nbsp;\u00b0C) to its \u03b2-phase (body centered cubic, bcc) structure at temperatures above 882.3&nbsp;\u00b0C). Alpha-phase titanium products typically exhibit medium to high strength with excellent creep strength, whereas beta-phase titanium products typically exhibit very high strength and low ductility.<ref name = \"r40\" /><ref name = \"r44\" /> Foams created under thermal cycling conditions have been shown to exhibit increased porosity due to the density difference between allotropic phases. Davis et al. produced titanium foams with 41% porosity (as compared to 27% porosity through the normal HIP creep mechanism).<ref name = \"r40\" /> Increases in overall ductility were also observed in foams created through thermal cycling. In a similar experiment, porosity of 44% was achieved and determined as the maximum achievable porosity under thermal cycling conditions.<ref name = \"r49\">{{cite journal|author=N. Murray, D. Dunand|title= Microstructure evolution during solid-state foaming of titanium|journal= Composites Science and Technology |volume=63|issue=16 |year=2003|pages= 2311\u20132316|doi= 10.1016/S0266-3538(03)00264-1}}</ref> A later study also utilized exploitation of transformation superplasticity conditions through HIP, but in this case, the titanium powder in the precursor matrix was replaced with titanium wires to create anisotropic pores. The resulting anisotropic pores showed closer correlation with natural bone in that the foams exhibited higher elastic moduli, yield strength and deformation when subjected to longitudinally loaded forces than when loads were applied transversely.<ref name = \"r50\">{{cite journal|author=E.D. Spoerke, N.G. Murray, H. Li, L.C. Brinson, D.C. Dunand, S.I. Stupp|title= A bioactive titanium foam scaffold for bone repair|journal= Acta Biomaterialia|volume=1|issue=5 |year=2005|pages= 523\u2013533|doi= 10.1016/j.actbio.2005.04.005|pmid= 16701832}}</ref>\n\n=== Space-holder technique ===\nThe space-holder technique is the most commonly employed method for producing titanium foams. The space-holder technique allows for the fabrication of higher porosity foams (35\u201380% <ref name = \"r90\">{{cite journal|author=N. Murray, C. Schuh, D. Dunand|title= Solid-state foaming of titanium by hydrogen-induced internal-stress superplasticity|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=49|issue=9 |year=2003|pages= 879\u2013883|doi= 10.1016/S1359-6462(03)00438-X}}</ref>) than other techniques, while also giving the engineer more control over pore fraction, shape and connectivity.<ref name = \"r47\" /> Mechanical properties can be adjusted through the size, shape and quantity of space-holders employed. The space-holder technique was first demonstrated by Zhao and Sun<ref name = \"r91\">{{cite journal|author=Y. Zhao, D. Sun|title= A novel sintering-dissolution process for manufacturing Al foams|doi=10.1016/S1359-6462(00)00548-0|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=44|issue=1 |year=2001|pages= 105\u2013110}}</ref> for the fabrication of aluminum foams in a powder metallurgical method, which consisted of the incorporation of NaCl as a space-holder. The space-holder was mixed into the powder mixture and dissolved prior to sintering. The same method was used to create titanium foams for the first time when Wen et al. utilized ammonium hydrogen carbonate spacers.<ref name = \"r87\">{{cite journal|author=C. Wen, Y. Yamada, K. Shimojima, Y. Chino, H. Hosokawa, M. Mabuchi|title= Novel titanium foam for bone tissue engineering|journal= Journal of Materials Research|volume=17|issue=10 |year=2002|pages= 2633\u20132639|doi= 10.1557/JMR.2002.0382|bibcode= 2002JMatR..17.2633W}}</ref>\n\n==== Powder selection ====\nThe size and shape of the metal powder has a direct impact on the stability of the precursor as well as the resulting foam. For this purpose, powders that increase packing efficiency are most advantageous.<ref name = \"r36\" /> The use of spherical particles may result in less contact of particles which consequently leads to larger secondary pores and a higher probability of pore collapse prior to complete sintering.<ref name = \"r92\">{{cite journal|author=N. Jha, D. Mondal, J.D. Majumdar, A. Badkul, A. Jha, A. Khare|title= Highly porous open cell Ti-foam using NaCl as temporary space holder through powder metallurgy route|journal= Materials & Design |volume=47 |year=2013|pages= 810\u2013819|doi= 10.1016/j.matdes.2013.01.005}}</ref> This factor can be limited through different compaction techniques that decrease the degree of interstitial sites around the titanium particles. However, this method also has limitations; for example, the powders cannot be compacted to such a degree that would promote deformation of the spacer (unless anisotropic pore shape is desired).<ref name = \"r15\" /><ref name = \"r61\">{{cite journal|author=T. Imwinkelried|title= Mechanical properties of open\u2010pore titanium foam|journal= Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part A |volume=81|issue=4 |year=2007|pages= 964\u2013970|doi= 10.1002/jbm.a.31118|pmid= 17252551}}</ref>\n\n==== Space-holder selection ====\n[[File:Tisugar.png|thumb|Computer tomography (a) and electron micrograph (b) of the Ti foam made with saccharose as a space holder, showing two types of pores in titanium foam]]\nThe selection of the space-holder is one of the most crucial steps because it defines many of the properties of the resulting foam, including cell shape, cell size and macroporosity. The space-holder should be inert and represent the size and shape of the desired pores. The porosity may be adjusted anywhere between 50 and 85% without the filler material becoming a part of the resultant foam.<ref name = \"r10\" /> It is also important to select a spacer that has limited or no solubility in titanium, as this incorporation will affect the mechanical properties of the resulting foam.<ref name = \"r94\">{{cite journal|author=A. Mansourighasri, N. Muhamad, A.B. Sulong|title= Processing titanium foams using tapioca starch as a space holder|journal= Journal of Materials Processing Technology |volume=212|issue=1 |year=2012|pages= 83\u201389|doi= 10.1016/j.jmatprotec.2011.08.008}}</ref> \n\n==== Space-holder size and shape ====\nThe degree of homogeneity in pore distribution of the final product is primarily dependent on the adequacy of mixing of the precursor. The difference in particle size between the titanium powders and the spacers directly impacts the ability to adequately mix the preform. The greater the size difference, the more difficult it is to control this process.<ref name = \"r94\" /> Nonhomogeneous mixing resulting from the use of spacers considerably larger than the titanium particles employed and has shown adverse effects in the stability of the precursor after removal of spacer and in the distribution of porosity.<ref name = \"r36\" /><ref name = \"r95\">{{cite journal|author=G. Ryan, A. Pandit, D.P. Apatsidis|title= Fabrication methods of porous metals for use in orthopaedic applications|journal= Biomaterials |volume=27|issue=13 |year=2006|pages= 2651\u20132670|doi= 10.1016/j.biomaterials.2005.12.002|pmid= 16423390}}</ref>\nSpacer size has been investigated.<ref name = \"r36\" /><ref name = \"r48\" /><ref name = \"r85\" /> It was shown that the use of a coarse spacer results in thicker pore walls while the use of finer spacers results in enhanced compaction, leading to increased densification. Increased densification is evidenced by a monomodal pore distribution with the employment of fine spacers and a bimodal distribution using coarse spacers. Further, finer spacers result in a more homogenous pore distribution. Sharma et al.<ref name = \"r77\" /> utilized acicular spacers and achieved porosities up to 60% where pores were undistorted. In samples employing fine particles, porosities up to 70% were achievable before noting distortion in the pores.<ref name = \"r85\" /> However, the bimodal pore distribution observed in coarse-spacer samples showed to be beneficial in terms of mechanical properties in that higher compressive strengths were observed, beyond those that might exist due to the inverse relationship of porosity and compressive strength alone.<ref name = \"r85\">{{cite journal|author=N. Tuncer, G. Arslan, E. Maire, L. Salvo|title= Investigation of spacer size effect on architecture and mechanical properties of porous titanium|journal= Materials Science and Engineering: A|volume= 530 |year=2011|pages= 633\u2013642|doi= 10.1016/j.msea.2011.10.036}}</ref>\n\n==== Compaction ====\nThe precursor mixture of powders and space-holders are compacted into a mold under a specified pressure. This can be achieved through uniaxial or isostatic processes. The pores resulting from this method are open and interconnected via windows between neighboring pores with the size of the pores partially dependent upon the coordination number and contact area of the resulting compact. Compaction pressure must be high enough to ensure sufficient mechanical strength for retention of pore geometry specified by the space-holder, but not too high enough as to cause deformation of the space-holder.<ref name = \"r94\" />\n\n==== Sintering and space-holder removal ====\nWhen employing dissolvable spacers, it is possible to remove the spacer after sintering, which reduces the risk of pore collapse. \nIn most cases, foams created using space-holders contain bimodal pore distributions with macro-sized pores resulting from the space-holder particles and micro-sized pores located on the pore walls and resulting from incomplete sintering of the powder matrix. As a result, the macropores typically exhibit rough internal surfaces.<ref name = \"r96\">{{cite journal|author=A. Bansiddhi, T. Sargeant, S. Stupp, D. Dunand|title= Porous NiTi for bone implants: a review|journal= Acta Biomaterialia |volume=4|issue=4 |year=2008|pages= 773\u2013782|doi= 10.1016/j.actbio.2008.02.009|pmid= 18348912|pmc= 3068602}}</ref> In some applications, such as for the use of bio-medical implants, this is an advantageous property. Inner porosity (or micro-porosity) has been shown to reduce stiffness; thus, reduce the risk of stress-shielding effects, while also offering improved osseointegration.<ref name=\"r14\"/><ref name = \"r77\">{{cite journal|author=M. Sharma, G. Gupta, O. Modi, B. Prasad, A.K. Gupta|title= Titanium foam through powder metallurgy route using acicular urea particles as space holder|journal= Materials Letters |volume=65|issue=21 |year=2011|pages= 3199\u20133201|doi= 10.1016/j.matlet.2011.07.004}}</ref><ref name = \"r96\" />\n\n==== Space-holder materials ====\n\n===== Sodium chloride (NaCl) =====\nSodium chloride is the most commonly chosen space-holder for titanium foams because it is highly soluble in water and inert with respect to titanium. This inertness prevents contamination and degradation of the mechanical properties of the resulting foam. Moreover, NaCl is non-toxic; any residuals are bioinert.<ref name = \"r77\" /><ref name = \"r80\" />\n\nBansiddhi & Dunand pioneered the use of NaCl as a permanent space-holder for the fabrication of NiTi foams.<ref name = \"r102\">{{cite journal|author=A. Bansiddhi, D.C. Dunand|title= Shape-memory NiTi foams produced by replication of NaCl space-holders|journal= Acta Biomaterialia |volume= 4|issue=6 |year=2008|pages= 1996\u20132007|doi= 10.1016/j.actbio.2008.06.005|pmid= 18678532}}</ref> The resulting foams consisted of 32-36% porosity with more complete densification than they observed when producing NiTi foams using a sodium fluoride (NaF) space-holder.<ref name = \"r103\">{{cite journal|author=A. Bansiddhi, D.C. Dunand|title= Shape-memory NiTi foams produced by solid-state replication with NaF|journal= Intermetallics|volume=15|issue=12 |year=2007|pages= 1612\u20131622|doi= 10.1016/j.intermet.2007.06.013}}</ref> However, processing parameters resulted in molten NaCl and a metal/salt blend in the cavities of the foam. Certain risks are associated with using a molten space-holder including reaction with the metal, dissolving of the space-holder in the metal and prevention of densification through the creation of a thin layer of liquid between the metal and particles.<ref name = \"r96\" /> Near complete densification was achieved when NaCl was used as a permanent space-holder in pure titanium foam.<ref name = \"r15\" /> In this case, a temperature below the melting point of NaCl was used; titanium is less creep resistant than NiTi, which allows for densification at lower temperatures. The resulting foams achieved porosity of 50\u201367% with minimal observable microporosity. Anisotropic pore shape in some areas alluded to NaCl's deformation during HIP, which is desirable for some applications.<ref name = \"r88\">{{cite journal|author=B. Ye, D.C. Dunand|title= Titanium foams produced by solid-state replication of NaCl powders|journal= Materials Science and Engineering: A |volume=528|issue=2 |year=2010|pages= 691\u2013697|doi= 10.1016/j.msea.2010.09.054}}</ref> Additionally, an observed, rough inner surface of the pores holds advantages for biomedical implant applications. \nJha et al.<ref name = \"r92\" /> achieved 65-80% porosity through the use of NaCl as a space-holder and a cold compaction process at various pressures with two-stage sintering. In this case, NaCl was removed through dissolution after the second stage of sintering. Resulting Young's moduli (8\u201315 GPa) were considerably lower than the Young's modulus of 29 GPa achieved for 50% porosity foams.<ref name = \"r25\" /><ref name = \"r88\" /> This illustrates the known relationship between porosity and Young's modulus wherein Young's modulus decreases linearly with increasing porosity. Achievable porosity through the space-holder method is directly related to the type and amount of space-holder utilized (up to a threshold maximum achievable porosity level).\n\n===== Magnesium =====\n\nMagnesium can be removed either thermally or by reactive measures through the dissolution in acid.<ref name = \"r31\" /><ref name = \"r104\">{{cite journal|author=T. Aydo\u011fmu\u015f, \u015e. Bor|title= Processing of porous TiNi alloys using magnesium as space holder|journal= Journal of Alloys and Compounds |volume=478|issue=1 |year=2009|pages= 705\u2013710|doi= 10.1016/j.jallcom.2008.11.141}}</ref>\n<ref name = \"r105\">{{cite journal|author=S.W. Kim, H.-D. Jung, M.-H. Kang, H.-E. Kim, Y.-H. Koh, Y. Estrin|title= Fabrication of porous titanium scaffold with controlled porous structure and net-shape using magnesium as spacer|journal= Materials Science and Engineering: C |volume=33|issue=5 |year=2013|pages= 2808\u20132815|doi= 10.1016/j.msec.2013.03.011|pmid= 23623100}}</ref> Esen & Bor <ref name = \"r31\" /> found a critical content of magnesium as a space holder to be 55-60%, above which compacts shrink excessively during sintering. Foams ranging in porosity from 45 to 70% with a bimodal pore distribution and compressive strength of 15 MPa (for 70% porosity) were demonstrated. Kim et al. fabricated foams with anisotropic pores through the intentional deformation of Mg particles during compaction in an effort to enhance mechanical properties. A final porosity of 70% equated to a yield strength of 38 MPa for normal orientation of pores and 59 MPa when pores were aligned with the direction of compression.<ref name = \"r105\" />\n\n===== Urea =====\n\nAnother commonly employed space-holder for titanium foams is [[urea]], which yilded porosities from 20 to 75%.<ref name = \"r36\" /><ref name = \"r77\" /><ref name = \"r84\" /><ref name = \"r85\" /><ref name = \"r87\" /> Wen et al.<ref name = \"r87\" /> produced foams exhibiting a bimodal pore distribution with porosities ranging from 55 to 75%, Young's moduli between 3\u20136.4 GPa, and a plateau stress of 10\u201335 MPa. An inverse relationship between plateau stress and porosity was observed with increased porosity resulting in decreased plateau stress.<ref name = \"r87\" /> Tuncer et al. utilized urea in combination with irregularly shaped titanium powders in an effort to increase green strength through increased packing efficiency (of particles). This also eliminated the need for the incorporation of a binder.<ref name = \"r84\">{{cite journal|author=N. Tuncer, G. Arslan, E. Maire, L. Salvo|title= Influence of cell aspect ratio on architecture and compressive strength of titanium foams|journal= Materials Science and Engineering: A |volume=528|issue=24 |year=2011|pages= 7368\u20137374|doi= 10.1016/j.msea.2011.06.028}}</ref>\n\n===== Tapioca starch =====\n[[Tapioca]] starch can be burnt off easily through the sintering process and is insoluble in titanium. Titanium foams consisting of a bimodal pore distribution (macropores ranging from 100 to 300 \u03bcm) and 64\u201379% porosity, exhibited yield strengths of 23\u201341 MPa and Young's moduli of 1.6\u20133.7 GPa.<ref name = \"r72\">{{cite journal|author=A. Mansourighasri, N. Muhamad, A. Sulong|title= Processing titanium foams using tapioca starch as a space holder|journal= Journal of Materials Processing Technology |volume=212|issue=1 |year=2012|pages= 83\u201389|doi= 10.1016/j.jmatprotec.2011.08.008}}</ref>\n\n===== Ammonium bicarbonate =====\nAlthough ammonium bicarbonate has been utilized in the manufacturing of titanium foams,<ref name = \"r87\" /> it is not an ideal spacer in that it has a low melting/dissociation point and some solubility in titanium. This results in considerable shrinkage which makes control of pore shape difficult. Furthermore, the decomposition releases environmentally harmful gases.<ref name = \"r51\">{{cite book|author=V. Amig\u00f3 Borr\u00e1s, L. Reig Cerd\u00e1, D.J. Busquets Mataix, J. Ortiz|title= Analysis of bending strength of porous titanium processed by space holder method |year=2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Freeze-casting ===\n[[File: Photos_LSM25_anim_small.gif|thumb|Freeze-casting solidification set-up.]]\n\n[[File:Tifreeze.png|thumb|Compressive strength of freeze-cast titanium materials created via freeze-casting.]]\n\n[[Freeze-casting]] is a directional solidification technique that is utilized to fabricate materials exhibiting anisotropic, elongated pore structures.<ref name = \"r108\">{{cite journal|author=K. Scotti, D. Dunand|title=Freeze casting \u2013 A review of processing, microstructure and properties via the open data repository, Freeze ''Casting''.net|journal=Progress in Materials Science|volume=94|pages=243\u2013305|doi=10.1016/j.pmatsci.2018.01.001|arxiv=1710.00037|year=2018}}</ref> Pore morphology is defined, in large part, by the morphology of the solidified fluid.\nTitanium foams exhibiting [[Dendrite (metal)|dendritic]]<ref name = \"r111\">{{cite journal|author=H. Jung, S. Yook, T. Jang, Y. Li, H. Kim, Y. Koh|title= Dynamic freeze casting for the production of porous titanium (Ti) scaffolds|journal= Mater. Sci. Eng. C|volume= 33|issue=1 |year=2013|pages= 59\u201363|doi= 10.1016/j.msec.2012.08.004|pmid= 25428042}}</ref><ref name = \"r113\">{{cite journal|author=S. Yook, H. Jung, C. Park, K. Shin, Y. Koh, Y. Estrin, H. Kim|title= Reverse freeze casting: A new method for fabricating highly porous titanium scaffolds, with aligned large pores|journal= Acta Biomater.|volume= 8|issue=6 |year=2012|pages= 2401\u20132410|doi= 10.1016/j.actbio.2012.03.020|pmid= 22421310}}</ref> and [[lamellar]]<ref name = \"r109\">{{cite journal|author=Y. Chino, D.C. Dunand|title= Directionally freeze-cast titanium foam with aligned, elongated pores|journal= Acta Mater. |volume=56|issue=1 |year=2008|pages= 105\u2013113|doi= 10.1016/j.actamat.2007.09.002}}</ref> pore structures have been produced, through the use of non-aqueous and aqueous processing respectively. These materials exhibit anisotropic mechanical properties as a result of their anisotropic pore structures. Compressive strength for loads applied parallel to the wall direction of titanium foams are found to be, on average, 2.5 times greater than for those applied perpendicular to the wall direction.<ref name = \"r108\" />\n\n== Applications ==\n\nPotential structural applications for titanium foams include their general incorporation into light-weight structures and as components for mechanical energy absorption. The most important considerations for the use of titanium foams in structural applications includes their porosity, specific strength, ductility in compression and cost. Because of low manufacturing costs, most metal foams marketed for structural applications are of a close-celled aluminum variety.<ref name = \"r117\">{{cite journal|author=Y. Zhao, T. Fung, L. Zhang, F. Zhang|title= Lost carbonate sintering process for manufacturing metal foams|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=52|issue=4 |year=2005|pages= 295\u2013298|doi= 10.1016/j.scriptamat.2004.10.012}}</ref> In comparison, titanium foam manufacturing incurs a higher cost, but this cost is defensible in space applications where the material offers an otherwise incomparable reduction in overall weight. The lower thermal conductivity of titanium may also be appreciated in rocket construction.<ref name = \"r1\" /> The specific strength, overall energy absorbing capability and high melting point all reinforce titanium's superiority to aluminum in aerospace and military applications.<ref name = \"r3\" /> When used for aerospace applications, levels of porosity close to 90% are desired.<ref name = \"r80\">{{cite journal|author=O. Smorygo, A. Marukovich, V. Mikutski, A. Gokhale, G.J. Reddy, J.V. Kumar|title= High-porosity titanium foams by powder coated space holder compaction method|journal= Materials Letters |volume=83 |year=2012|pages= 17\u201319|doi= 10.1016/j.matlet.2012.05.082}}</ref> Titanium foams are capable of retaining their high tensile strength at temperatures up to 400&nbsp;\u00b0C; a limit imposed by the metal's low resistance to oxidation.<ref name = \"r44\" />\n\n=== Aerospace applications ===\nThe driving force for titanium foam's replacement of existing materials in the aerospace sector results from the following five factors:<ref name = \"r44\" />\n*Weight reduction: as a substitute for steels and nickel-based superalloys;\n*Application temperature: as a substitute for aluminum and nickel-based alloys and steels\n*Corrosion resistance: as a substitute for aluminum alloys and low-alloyed steels\n*Galvanic compatibility: with polymer matrix composites as substitutes for aluminum alloys\n*Space constraints: as substitutes for aluminum alloys and steels\n\nThe most urgent problem of engineering and its advanced branch of aerospace engineering is the efficient use of materials as well as increased service life.<ref name = \"r1\" />\n\n==== Sandwich panel cores ====\n[[File: Aluminium composite material.png|thumb|Model of a sandwich panel assembly]]\n\nSandwich panel cores are used throughout the aerospace industry; they are integrated within aircraft bodies, floors and internal panels. Sandwich constructions consist of two faces separated by a thick, light-weight core and are most commonly composed of balsa-wood, foamed polymers, glue-bonded aluminum or Nomex (paper) honeycombs. Typically, the cores are combined with reinforcing fibers to increase their shear modulus.<ref name = \"r118\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1155/2013/589216 |title=A Comparative Study of Ballistic Resistance of Sandwich Panels with Aluminum Foam and Auxetic Honeycomb Cores |journal=Advances in Mechanical Engineering |volume=5 |pages=589216 |year=2013 |last1=Yang |first1=Shu |last2=Qi |first2=Chang |last3=Wang |first3=Dong |last4=Gao |first4=Renjing |last5=Hu |first5=Haitao |last6=Shu |first6=Jian |doi-access=free }}</ref> Indeed, carbon fiber-reinforced polymers exhibit the highest specific stiffness and strength of these materials.<ref name = \"r119\">{{cite journal|author=K. Finnegan, G. Kooistra, H.N. Wadley, V. Deshpande|title= The compressive response of carbon fiber composite pyramidal truss sandwich cores|journal= International Journal of Materials Research |volume=98|issue=12 |year=2007|pages= 1264\u20131272|doi= 10.3139/146.101594|url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f4ff946af3ab18605ace98bd7336988dc8cfd0f6}}</ref><ref name = \"r120\">{{cite journal|author=S. Park, B. Russell, V. Deshpande, N. Fleck|title= Dynamic compressive response of composite square honeycombs|journal= Composites Part A: Applied Science and Manufacturing |volume=43|issue=3 |year=2012|pages= 527\u2013536|doi= 10.1016/j.compositesa.2011.11.022}}</ref> However, polymers decompose at low temperatures; thus employment of the aforementioned materials pose inherent challenges due to the limited range of temperature they may be utilized within as well as their moisture-dependent properties.<ref name = \"r13\" />\nThe largest and most inadequately predicted failure within the core results from strain localization. Strain localization refers to the development of bands exhibiting intensive straining as a result of the localization of deformations in the solid.<ref name = \"r121\">{{cite journal|author=F. Zok, H. Rathbun, M. He, E. Ferri, C. Mercer, R. McMeeking, A. Evans|title= Structural performance of metallic sandwich panels with square honeycomb cores|journal= Philosophical Magazine |volume= 85|issue=26\u201327 |year=2005|pages= 3207\u20133234|doi= 10.1080/14786430500073945|bibcode= 2005PMag...85.3207Z}}</ref>\n<ref name = \"r122\">{{cite journal|author=H. Rathbun, D. Radford, Z. Xue, M. He, J. Yang, V. Deshpande, N. Fleck, J. Hutchinson, F. Zok, A. Evans|title= Performance of metallic honeycomb-core sandwich beams under shock loading|journal= International Journal of Solids and Structures |volume=43|issue=6 |year=2006|pages= 1746\u20131763|doi= 10.1016/j.ijsolstr.2005.06.079}}</ref> For the best performance, the structure should exhibit low peak response force and high total energy absorption.<ref name = \"r18\"/> Titanium foams are lightweight, stiff, and possess the capability to resist blast. Furthermore, the use of titanium-based foams exhibiting homogenous porosity distribution would significantly decrease the risks associated with strain localization. The high strength-to-weight ratio of titanium foams offers an opportunity to provide increased bending and shearing stiffness as well as energy absorption capabilities during periods of bending.<ref name = \"r118\" /><ref name = \"r122\" /><ref name = \"r123\">{{cite journal|author=P. Moongkhamklang, D.M. Elzey, H.N. Wadley|title= Titanium matrix composite lattice structures|journal= Composites Part A: Applied Science and Manufacturing|volume= 39|issue=2 |year=2008|pages= 176\u2013187|doi= 10.1016/j.compositesa.2007.11.007}}</ref> Titanium foams may be utilized in environments with elevated temperatures (up to 400&nbsp;\u00b0C). Composite structures may also be produced; the incorporation of silicon carbide monofilaments into Ti-6-Al-4V foams was shown to exhibit an elastic modulus of 195 GPa and tensile strength of 800 MPa.<ref name = \"r124\">{{cite journal|author=P. Moongkhamklang, V. Deshpande, H. Wadley|title= The compressive and shear response of titanium matrix composite lattice structures|journal= Acta Materialia |volume=58|issue=8 |year=2010|pages= 2822\u20132835|doi= 10.1016/j.actamat.2010.01.004}}</ref>\n\n===== Auxetic structures =====\n[[File:Auxetic nonauxetic.png|thumb]]\nTitanium foams exhibiting auxetic pore structures are of interest for incorporation in sandwich panel cores due to their enhanced shear performance.<ref name = \"r126\">{{cite journal|author=A. Alderson, J. Rasburn, S. Ameer-Beg, P.G. Mullarkey, W. Perrie, K.E. Evans|title= An auxetic filter: a tuneable filter displaying enhanced size selectivity or defouling properties|journal= Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Research |volume=39|issue=3 |year=2000|pages= 654\u2013665|doi= 10.1021/ie990572w}}</ref>\n<ref name = \"r127\">{{cite journal|author=F. Scarpa, L. Ciffo, J. Yates|title= Dynamic properties of high structural integrity auxetic open cell foam|journal= Smart Materials and Structures|volume=13|issue=1 |year=2004|pages= 49\u201356|doi= 10.1088/0964-1726/13/1/006|bibcode= 2004SMaS...13...49S}}</ref> Foams with this pore structure exhibit negative Poisson's ratio in one or more dimensions.<ref name = \"r118\" /> Poisson's ratio is defined as the ratio of the lateral contractile strain to the longitudinal tensile strain for the foam undergoing uniaxial tension in the loading direction.<ref name = \"r128\">{{cite journal|author=A. Alderson|title= A triumph of lateral thought|journal= Chemistry & Industry|volume=10 |year=1999|pages= 384|pmid= 6038772}}</ref> Auxetic materials are typically able to resist indentations through their response to compression; upon compression, the auxetic material contracts.<ref name = \"r128\" /> In addition to indentation resistance, research has shown that auxetic foams offer better absorption of sound and vibration, enhanced shear resistance and facture toughness. These structures also exhibit synclastic bending, which results lends itself to integration within curved sandwich panels.\n\n=== Biomedical implants ===\n[[File:Tifemur.png|thumb|(a) Upper femur with simulated intramedullary rod insert fabricated from Ti-6Al-4V. (b) A through-section cutaway view illustrating inner, more porous foam core surrounded by more dense foam structure for stiffness compatibility.]]\n\n[[Titanium alloy]]s are the choice material for a diverse range of biomedical implants.<ref name = \"r129\">{{cite journal|author=C. Elias, J. Lima, R. Valiev, M. Meyers|title= Biomedical applications of titanium and its alloys|journal= JOM|volume= 60|issue=3 |year=2008|pages= 46\u201349|doi= 10.1007/s11837-008-0031-1|bibcode= 2008JOM....60c..46E}}</ref>\nCurrently employed titanium alloy implants include: hip joints,<ref name = \"r130\">{{cite journal|author=H. Agins, N. Alcock, M. Bansal, E. Salvati, P. Wilson, P. Pellicci, P. Bullough|title= Metallic wear in failed titanium-alloy total hip replacements|journal= J Bone Joint Surg |volume=70|issue=3 |year=1988|pages= 347\u2013356|doi= 10.2106/00004623-198870030-00005}}</ref>\nbone screws,<ref name = \"r9\" /><ref name = \"r131\">{{cite journal|author=D.N. Caborn, W.P. Urban, D.L. Johnson, J. Nyland, D. Pienkowski|title= Biomechanical comparison between BioScrew and titanium alloy interference screws for bone\u2014patellar tendon\u2014bone graft fixation in anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction|journal= Arthroscopy: The Journal of Arthroscopic & Related Surgery|volume=13|issue=2 |year=1997|pages= 229\u2013232|doi= 10.1016/S0749-8063(97)90159-6|pmid= 9127082}}</ref>\nknee joints,<ref name=\"r96\"/> spinal fusions,<ref name = \"r8\" /> shoulder joints,<ref name = \"r96\" /> and bone plates.<ref name = \"r129\" /><ref name = \"r133\">{{cite journal|author=M. Long, H. Rack|title= Titanium alloys in total joint replacement\u2014a materials science perspective|journal= Biomaterials|volume=19|issue=18 |year=1998|pages= 1621\u20131639|doi= 10.1016/S0142-9612(97)00146-4|pmid= 9839998}}</ref><ref name = \"r134\">{{cite journal|author=D.D. Deligianni, N. Katsala, S. Ladas, D. Sotiropoulou, J. Amedee, Y. Missirlis|title= Effect of surface roughness of the titanium alloy Ti\u20136Al\u20134V on human bone marrow cell response and on protein adsorption|journal= Biomaterials |volume=22|issue=11 |year=2001|pages= 1241\u20131251|doi= 10.1016/S0142-9612(00)00274-X|pmid= 11336296}}</ref> These alloys range from high ductility, commercially-pure titanium foams with high formability, to heat-treatable alloys with high strength. Titanium is well-suited for use in [[magnetic resonance imaging]] (MRI) and [[computed tomography]] (CT),<ref name = \"r138\">{{cite journal|author=A. Malik, O. Boyko, N. Aktar, W. Young|title= A comparative study of MR imaging profile of titanium pedicle screws|journal= Acta Radiologica|volume= 42|issue=3 |year=2001|pages= 291\u2013293|doi= 10.1080/028418501127346846}}</ref>\n<ref name = \"r139\">{{cite journal|author=O. Ortiz, T.G. Pait, P. McAllister, K. Sauter|title= Postoperative magnetic resonance imaging with titanium implants of the thoracic and lumbar spine|journal= Neurosurgery |volume=38|issue=4 |year=1996|pages= 741\u2013745|doi= 10.1227/00006123-199604000-00022}}</ref> which further enhances its applicability for biomedical implant applications.\n\n==== Bioimplants: microstructure ====\nBiomedical implants should have low density for patient comfort and high porosity and surface area to facilitate vascularization and the ingrowth of new bone.<ref name = \"r140\">{{cite journal|author=J. Jakubowicz, G. Adamek, M. Dewidar|title= Titanium foam made with saccharose as a space holder|journal= Journal of Porous Materials |volume=20|issue=5 |year=2013|pages= 1137\u20131141|doi= 10.1007/s10934-013-9696-0|doi-access=free}}</ref> Ideally, the implant will allow sufficiently easy fluid flow for cell nutrition and osteoblast multiplication as well as migration for cellular colonization of the implant to become uniform. The pores contained within the foam's cellular matrix mimic the extracellular matrix of bone, allowing the body to fixate with the implant. The porosity of the implant also promotes apposition and facilitates vascularization\u2212as cells are able to attach, reproduce and form basic functions.<ref name = \"r86\" /> It has been shown that a macropore size of 200\u2013500&nbsp;\u00b5m is preferred for ingrowths of new bone tissues and transportation of body fluids. The lower bound is controlled by the size of cells (~20&nbsp;\u00b5m), and the upper bound is related to the specific surface area through the availability of binding sites.<ref name = \"r86\">{{cite journal|author=C. Wen, M. Mabuchi, Y. Yamada, K. Shimojima, Y. Chino, T. Asahina|title= Processing of biocompatible porous Ti and Mg|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=45|issue=10 |year=2001|pages= 1147\u20131153|doi= 10.1016/S1359-6462(01)01132-0}}</ref> Finer pores further help in tissue growth and biofluid movement.<ref name = \"r141\">{{cite journal|author=K. Abshagen, I. Schrodi, T. Gerber, B. Vollmar|title= In vivo analysis of biocompatibility and vascularization of the synthetic bone grafting substitute NanoBone\u00ae|journal= Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part A |volume=91|issue=2 |year=2009|pages= 557\u2013566|doi= 10.1002/jbm.a.32237|pmid= 18985779}}</ref> Anisotropic, elongated pores (such as those attainable via the freeze-casting technique) may be beneficial in bone implants in that they can further mimic the structure of bone.\n\nThe porous surface geometry of the foam promotes bone in-growth, provides anchorage for fixation, and ensures stresses are transferred from the implant to the bone.<ref name = \"r37\">{{cite journal|author=I.-H. Oh, N. Nomura, N. Masahashi, S. Hanada|title= Mechanical properties of porous titanium compacts prepared by powder sintering|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=49|issue=12 |year=2003|pages= 1197\u20131202|doi= 10.1016/j.scriptamat.2003.08.018}}</ref> Surface roughness in the pore can enhance bone in-growth, and coarser cell size facilitates faster tissue growth.<ref name = \"r88\" />\nTo optimize the implant's functionality and ability to successfully fuse with bone, it may be necessary to manipulate the material's manufacturing methods in order to modify the foam's pore structure. Changes in pore structure can directly influence implant strength as well as other key properties.\n\n==== Bioimplants: mechanical properties ====\n\nHuman cancellous bone possesses a stiffness ranging from 12 to 23 GPa;<ref name = \"r142\">{{cite journal|author=C. Greiner, S.M. Oppenheimer, D.C. Dunand|title= High strength, low stiffness, porous NiTi with superelastic properties|journal= Acta Biomaterialia|volume=1|issue=6 |year=2005|pages= 705\u2013716|doi= 10.1016/j.actbio.2005.07.005|pmid= 16701851}}</ref> careful control and modification of manufacturing parameters to achieve similar strengths is imperative for practicality of integration.<ref name = \"r143\">{{cite journal|author=M.S. Aly|title= Effect of pore size on the tensile behavior of open-cell Ti foams: Experimental results|journal= Materials Letters |volume=64|issue=8 |year=2010|pages= 935\u2013937|doi= 10.1016/j.matlet.2010.01.064}}</ref> Correctly predicting the Young's modulus for foams is imperative for actual biomedical integration; a mismatch of Young's moduli between the implant and the bone can result in stress-shielding effects from a disproportional handling of stress.<ref name = \"r144\">{{cite journal|author=L.E. Murr, S.M. Gaytan, E. Martinez, F. Medina, R.B. Wicker|title= Next generation orthopaedic implants by additive manufacturing using electron beam melting|journal= International Journal of Biomaterials |volume= 2012|pages= 1\u201314|year=2012|doi= 10.1155/2012/245727|pmid= 22956957|pmc= 3432366}}</ref> The implant which typically exhibits a higher Young's modulus than the bone will absorb most of the load. As a result of this imbalance, the starting bone density will be reduced, there will be tissue death and, eventually, implant failure.<ref name = \"r145\">{{cite journal|author=H. Li, S.M. Oppenheimer, S.I. Stupp, D.C. Dunand, L.C. Brinson|title= Effects of pore morphology and bone ingrowth on mechanical properties of microporous titanium as an orthopaedic implant material|journal= Materials Transactions |volume=45|issue=4 |year=2004|pages= 1124\u20131131|doi= 10.2320/matertrans.45.1124|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nNatural bone exhibits the ability to adjust local fiber away from the low-stress regions toward high stress regions through the distribution of porosity, thus maximizing overall comfort.<ref name = \"r146\">{{cite journal|author=Y. Conde, A. Pollien, A. Mortensen|title= Functional grading of metal foam cores for yield-limited lightweight sandwich beams|journal= Scripta Materialia |volume=54|issue=4 |year=2006|pages= 539\u2013543|doi= 10.1016/j.scriptamat.2005.10.050|url= http://infoscience.epfl.ch/record/90711}}</ref> Using finite element analysis, researchers examined the effect of filling pores with bone on mechanical properties.<ref name = \"r145\" /> They concluded that bone ingrowth significantly improved the mechanical properties, evidenced by decreased localized plasticity and stress concentrations. In effect, the titanium foam in the study allowed the bone to exhibit its natural ability to adjust local fiber away from the low-stress regions toward high stress regions.\n\nExperiments demonstrated that random combinations of pore size and shape result in lower Young's moduli. Theoretical models for the quantification of Young's moduli do not account for random pore size and shape distribution, so experimental measurements must be conducted in the presence of heterogeneous pore size and distribution. This is a limitation of the micro-mechanical models discussed above.\n\n==== Osseointegration ====\nCurrently utilized implants take a great deal of time to integrate with the body after the initial surgical procedure occurs. True adhesion between the implant and the bone has been difficult to achieve and, unfortunately, success rates of implant fixation are low due to the implant's failure to achieve long-term osseointegration into the bone.<ref name = \"r95\" /><ref name = \"r96\" /><ref name = \"r147\">{{cite journal|author=H.-W. Kim, Y.-H. Koh, L.-H. Li, S. Lee, H.-E. Kim|title= Hydroxyapatite coating on titanium substrate with titania buffer layer processed by sol\u2013gel method|journal= Biomaterials |volume=25|issue=13 |year=2004|pages= 2533\u20132538|doi= 10.1016/j.biomaterials.2003.09.041}}</ref> With an increasing number of individuals requiring orthopedic implants,<ref name = \"r11\" /> the development of materials with structural and biological potential to improve osseointegration is crucial. Utilization of titanium-based foams present one way to potentially improve the bioactivity <ref name = \"r6\" /><ref name = \"r149\">{{cite journal|author=V.D. Rani, K. Manzoor, D. Menon, N. Selvamurugan, S.V. Nair|title= The design of novel nanostructures on titanium by solution chemistry for an improved osteoblast response|journal= Nanotechnology |volume=20|issue=19 |year=2009|pages= 195101|doi= 10.1088/0957-4484/20/19/195101|pmid= 19420629|bibcode= 2009Nanot..20s5101D}}</ref><ref name = \"r150\">{{cite journal|author=B.K. Nayak, M.C. Gupta|title= Self-organized micro/nano structures in metal surfaces by ultrafast laser irradiation|journal= Optics and Lasers in Engineering |volume=48|issue=10 |year=2010|pages= 940\u2013949|doi= 10.1016/j.optlaseng.2010.04.010|bibcode= 2010OptLE..48..940N}}</ref><ref name = \"r151\">{{cite journal|author=R. Karpagavalli, A. Zhou, P. Chellamuthu, K. Nguyen|title= Corrosion behavior and biocompatibility of nanostructured TiO<sub>2</sub> film on Ti6Al4V|journal= Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part A |volume=83|issue=4 |year=2007|pages= 1087\u20131095|doi= 10.1002/jbm.a.31447|pmid= 17584904}}</ref> and reduce stress-shielding effects of currently employed bioimplant materials.\n\nThe problem of osseointegration is best understood by examining the process of natural bone growth. In the body, bone and tissues experience self-regeneration, and structural modifications occur normally in response to environmental stimuli.<ref name = \"r152\">{{cite journal|author=D.W. Hutmacher|title= Scaffolds in tissue engineering bone and cartilage|journal= Biomaterials |volume=21|issue=24 |year=2000|pages= 2529\u20132543|doi= 10.1016/S0142-9612(00)00121-6}}</ref> Successful osseointegration occurs in three main stages that follow a natural biologically determined procedure: 1) incorporation of the implant into the bone's formation, 2) adaption of the new bone mass to carry weight and 3) remodeling of the new bone structure. The first stage in this process is the most crucial for overall success;<ref name = \"r153\" /> the implant and the bone must form a rapid connection, and this bond must be strong and enduring. Owing to its porous structure, a titanium metal foam implant may be able to achieve close fixation with the bone and will decrease patient recovery time considerably. Essentially, the foam becomes an extracellular matrix in the body as tissue is integrated into it.<ref name = \"r86\" /> Today, the implants most commonly used for bone replacement lack the ability to promote these characteristics, which are found in natural bone and, as a result, the implants have limited lifetimes.<ref name = \"r86\" /> This phenomenon of osseointegration works similarly to direct fracture healing. However, instead of a bone fragment-end reconnecting to bone, the fragment-end connects to an implant surface.<ref name = \"r153\">{{cite journal|author=S.N. Khan, M. Ramachandran, S.S. Kumar, V. Krishnan, R. Sundaram|title= Osseointegration and more\u2013A review of literature|journal= Indian Journal of Dentistry |volume=3|issue=2 |year=2012|pages= 72\u201376|doi= 10.1016/j.ijd.2012.03.012}}</ref> In a study on fibroblastic interactions with high-porosity [[Titanium alloy|Ti6Al4V]] alloy, the metal foam was supportive of cell attachment and proliferation, migration through the porous network, and proved capable of sustaining a large cell population.<ref name = \"r7\" />\n\n==== Increasing bioactivity via coatings ====\nTitanium's propensity to form an oxide layer on its surface prevents corrosion of surfaces that are in contact with human tissues because the surface oxides minimize diffusion of metal ions from the bulk material to the surface.<ref name = \"r144\" /> When titanium gains a coating to make it more bioactive, it can turn the already biocompatible titanium surface into an interface able to enhance osteoblast adhesion and able to promote osseointegration.<ref name = \"r145\" /> Today, research is heavily focused on improving the success rate of integration and uses an understanding of the natural process of bone growth and repair to create coatings that will enhance the surface finish and surface properties of the implant. These adjustments allow the artificial structure to mimic biological materials and to gain acceptance into the body with fewer negative side effects.<ref name = \"r155\">{{cite journal|author=M. Lutolf, J. Hubbell|title= Synthetic biomaterials as instructive extracellular microenvironments for morphogenesis in tissue engineering|journal= Nature Biotechnology |volume=23|issue=1 |year=2005|pages= 47\u201355|doi= 10.1038/nbt1055|pmid= 15637621}}</ref><ref name = \"r156\">{{cite journal|author=Z. Tang, N.A. Kotov, S. Magonov, B. Ozturk|title= Nanostructured artificial nacre|journal= Nature Materials |volume=2|issue=6 |year=2003|pages= 413\u20138|doi= 10.1038/nmat906|pmid= 12764359|bibcode= 2003NatMa...2..413T}}</ref>\nA 3-year clinical and radiographic study found implants in humans coated by nanocrystalline [[hydroxylapatite]] (HA) to support osseointegration. The nanocrystalline HA was developed with a large rough surface of interconnecting pores between 10 and 20&nbsp;nm of the silica matrix gel, resulting in a porous bone structure. Mean rates of marginal bone loss were insignificant and the periotest values were indicative of a solid osseointegration.<ref name = \"r157\">{{cite journal|author=F. Heinemann, T. Mundt, R. Biffar, T. Gedrange, W. Goetz|title= A 3-year clinical and radiographic study of implants placed simultaneously with maxillary sinus floor augmentations using a new nanocrystalline hydroxyapatite|journal= Journal of Physiology and Pharmacology |volume=60 |year=2009|pages= 91\u201397|pmid=20400800}}</ref>\nIn effect, the pores are structured in such a way that they are able hold onto the proteins on the biomaterial's surface. Ideally, this allows the body to engage in self-repair in that the synthetic HA is recognized as a like-nanomaterial in which live tissues may develop<ref name = \"r10\" />\n\nTitanium foams can be coated with HA through various methods including plasma spraying, sol-gel and electrophoretic deposition. It has been shown that HA-coated titanium exhibits increased interfacial strength in comparison to titanium foams without the coating. In an effort to enhance bone in-growth, Spoerke et al. developed a method for growing organoapatites on titanium implants. Organoapatites may assist in-bone in-growth at the implant interface. The foams were manufactured using a modified HIP process, which exploits the allotropic nature of titanium to create higher porosity foams. Previous in vitro experimentation with the organoapatite-titanium foam held promising results including the possibility that ingrown tissue within these coated pores will improve the lifetime use of the foam through reduction of stress-shielding effects.<ref name = \"r50\" />\n\n==== Animal studies ====\nIn the lab, synthetic nanocrystalline bone grafting material in mice has shown in-growth of vascularized fibrous tissue which resulted in improved healing. Furthermore, new blood vessels were observed at day 5 after implantation, and the implant showed a high functional vessel density.<ref name = \"r141\" /> In a study examining the femoral epiphyses of rabbits in two to eight weeks of healing, bone-to-implant contact was compared to bone growth inside the chambers for four different implant surfaces. The researchers found that bone substitute materials may improve the bone apposition onto titanium.<ref name = \"r158\">{{cite journal|author=B.M. Willie, X. Yang, N.H. Kelly, J. Merkow, S. Gagne, R. Ware, T.M. Wright, M.P. Bostrom|title= Osseointegration into a novel titanium foam implant in the distal femur of a rabbit|journal= Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part B: Applied Biomaterials|volume= 92|issue=2 |year=2010|pages= 479\u2013488|pmc=2860654|pmid= 20024964|doi= 10.1002/jbm.b.31541}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Metal foam]]\n* [[Titanium]]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube| hdscnna5r1Q |title=Bone ingrowth in NRC Ti Foam}}\n* {{YouTube| 6No-EpeC20w |title=Experimental investigation of a titanium foam at low and high strain rates}}\n* {{YouTube| XDwyH3z_e2M |title=A Novel Titanium Foam for Orthopedic Load-Bearing}}\n* {{YouTube| _LV4VSeQ44M |title=New Age Titanium Foams for More Successful Dental Implants}}\n* {{YouTube| 1eIJGtBEYS4 |title=Metal Foam \u2013 Innovation Nation}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Titanium foam}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Foams]]\n[[Category:Metals]]\n", "name_user": "207.98.193.40", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Titanium_foam"}
{"title_page": "El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish flamenco singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano\n| image                 =\n| caption            =\n| image_size            = <!-- Only for images smaller than 220 pixels -->\n| background          = \n| birth_name          = Enrique Castell\u00f3n Vargas\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1932|04|07|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Valencia]], Spain\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2020|04|22|1932|04|07|df=yes}}\n| origin              =\n| instrument          = voice\n| genre               = [[flamenco]]\n| occupation          = Musician, composer\n| years_active        = 1946-2000s\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     =\n| website             =\n}}\n'''Enrique Castell\u00f3n Vargas''' (7 April 1932 \u2013 22 April 2020), better known as '''El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano''' (\"The Gypsy Prince\") was a Spanish [[flamenco]] singer, actor and dancer.\n\n==Trajectory==\nAt the age of 14 he made his debut at the Teatro Calder\u00f3n in Madrid in the same show as [[Lola Flores]] and very soon after he performed his first show, \u201cPinceladas\u201d, becoming a great figure in Spanish song in the 1950s, despite the fact that his real passion was [[bullfighting]], but he did not have success in that field.<ref>[https://www.aplausos.es/noticia/53352/noticias/muere-el-principe-gitano-un-artista-que-sono-con-ser-torero.html Muere El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano, un artista que so\u00f1\u00f3 con ser torero] in Aplausos (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nHis most famous song is \"Ob\u00ed, ob\u00e1\". He also made a peculiar version of the [[Elvis Presley]] song \"[[In the Ghetto]]\".<ref>[https://www.eldiario.es/cultura/Enrique-Castellon-Vargas-Principe-Gitano_0_1019448822.html Muere con coronavirus el actor y cantante Enrique Castell\u00f3n Vargas, 'El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano'] in eldiario.es (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nHe died due to [[COVID-19]].<ref>[https://www.diarioinformacion.com/cultura/2020/04/22/fallece-88-anos-principe-gitano/2257979.html Fallece por coronavirus a los 88 a\u00f1os el 'Pr\u00edncipe gitano'] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Brindis al cielo]]'' (1954)\n*''[[Un heredero en apuros]]'' (1956)\n*''[[Veraneo en Espa\u00f1a]]'' (1956)\n*''[[El alma de la copla]]'' (1965)\n*''[[El milagro del cante]]'' (1967)\n*''[[Espa\u00f1olear]]'' (1969)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0889764}}\n* {{Discogs artist|El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Principe gitano}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish singers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish flamenco singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano\n| image                 =\n| caption            =\n| image_size            = <!-- Only for images smaller than 220 pixels -->\n| background          = \n| birth_name          = Enrique Castell\u00f3n Vargas\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1932|04|07|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Valencia]], Spain\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2020|04|22|1932|04|07|df=yes}}\n| origin              =\n| instrument          = voice\n| genre               = [[flamenco]]\n| occupation          = Musician, composer\n| years_active        = 1946-2000s\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     =\n| website             =\n}}\n'''Enrique Castell\u00f3n Vargas''' (7 April 1932 \u2013 22 April 2020), better known as '''El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano''' (\"The Gypsy Prince\") was a Spanish [[flamenco]] singer, actor and dancer.\n\n==Trajectory==\nAt the age of 14 he made his debut at the Teatro Calder\u00f3n in Madrid in the same show as [[Lola Flores]] and very soon after he performed his first show, \u201cPinceladas\u201d, becoming a great figure in Spanish song in the 1950s, despite the fact that his real passion was [[bullfighting]], but he did not have success in that field.<ref>[https://www.aplausos.es/noticia/53352/noticias/muere-el-principe-gitano-un-artista-que-sono-con-ser-torero.html Muere El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano, un artista que so\u00f1\u00f3 con ser torero] in Aplausos (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nHis most famous song is \"Ob\u00ed, ob\u00e1\". He also made a peculiar version of the [[Elvis Presley]] song \"[[In the Ghetto]]\".<ref>[https://www.eldiario.es/cultura/Enrique-Castellon-Vargas-Principe-Gitano_0_1019448822.html Muere con coronavirus el actor y cantante Enrique Castell\u00f3n Vargas, 'El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano'] in eldiario.es (in Spanish)</ref>\n\nHe died due to [[COVID-19]].<ref>[https://www.diarioinformacion.com/cultura/2020/04/22/fallece-88-anos-principe-gitano/2257979.html Fallece por coronavirus a los 88 a\u00f1os el 'Pr\u00edncipe gitano'] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Brindis al cielo]]'' (1954)\n*''[[Un heredero en apuros]]'' (1956)\n*''[[Veraneo en Espa\u00f1a]]'' (1956)\n*''[[El alma de la copla]]'' (1965)\n*''[[El milagro del cante]]'' (1967)\n*''[[Espa\u00f1olear]]'' (1969)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0889764}}\n* {{Discogs artist|El Pr\u00edncipe Gitano}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Principe gitano}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish musicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "ExRat", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_Pr%C3%ADncipe_Gitano"}
{"title_page": "Balconies of Cusco", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=June 2018}}\n[[File:Cuzco D\u00e9cembre 2007 - Balcons.jpg|thumb|Colonial balconies in Cusco]]\n[[File:Colonial balconies of Cusco Ephraim George Squier.jpg|thumb|Colonial balconies in the Plaza del Cabildo of Cusco in 1877 by [[Ephraim George Squier]].]]\nThe '''balconies of Cusco''' are colonial balconies found in much of the city of [[Cusco]], [[Cusco Region]], [[Peru]]. These balconies are most dated to colonial times<ref name=\"rpp.pe\">{{cite|url=http://rpp.pe/peru/actualidad/los-balcones-de-estilo-arabe-en-la-ciudad-del-cusco-noticia-513006|author=Adelayda Letona|work=RPP TV news|title=Los balcones de estilo \u00e1rabe en la ciudad del Cusco|date=August 17, 2012}}</ref> and some other to the early-Republican time.\n\nThese constructions are located in the corners of colonial and republican palaces and convents of old streets. They are of [[Mud\u00e9jar]] and [[Spanish Baroque architecture|Baroque]] styles.\n\nSome scientists say that these balconies have a type of discreet enclosure that kept women hidden from the sight of people in the exterior; in this way, these balconies or windows, served so that women could snoop without being seen from the street.<ref name=\"rpp.pe\"/>\n\nBalconies are a typical colonial Peruvian feature that can be seen in other colonial towns of Peru.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Balconies of Lima]]\n*[[Balcony]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Spanish Colonial architecture}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cusco]]\n[[Category:Colonial Peru]]\n[[Category:Spanish Colonial architecture in Peru]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=June 2018}}\n[[File:Cuzco D\u00e9cembre 2007 - Balcons.jpg|thumb|Colonial balconies in Cusco]]\n[[File:Colonial balconies of Cusco Ephraim George Squier.jpg|thumb|Colonial balconies in the Plaza del Cabildo of Cusco in 1877 by [[Ephraim George Squier]].]]\nThe '''balconies of Cusco''' are colonial balconies found in much of the city of [[Cusco]], [[Cusco Region]], [[Peru]]. These balconies are most dated to colonial times<ref name=\"rpp.pe\">{{cite|url=http://rpp.pe/peru/actualidad/los-balcones-de-estilo-arabe-en-la-ciudad-del-cusco-noticia-513006|author=Adelayda Letona|work=RPP TV news|title=Los balcones de estilo \u00e1rabe en la ciudad del Cusco|date=August 17, 2012}}</ref> and some other to the early-Republican time.\n\nThese constructions are located in the corners of colonial and republican palaces and convents of old streets. They are of [[Mud\u00e9jar]] and [[Spanish Baroque architecture|Baroque]] styles.\n\nSome scientists say that these balconies have a type of discreet enclosure that kept women hidden from the sight of people in the exterior; in this way, these balconies or windows, served so that women could snoop without being seen from the street.<ref name=\"rpp.pe\"/>\n\nBalconies are a typical colonial Peruvian feature that can be seen in other colonial towns of Peru.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Balconies of Lima]]\n*[[Balcony]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Spanish Colonial architecture}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cusco]]\n[[Category:Colonial Peru]]\n[[Category:Spanish Colonial architecture in Peru]]\n[[Category:Women's history]]\n", "name_user": "Antler century", "label": "safe", "comment": "deleted category of women's history, as this doesn't seem like a good fit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balconies_of_Cusco"}
{"title_page": "List of most-liked Instagram posts", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\nThis list contains the top 20 posts with the most [[Like button#Instagram|likes]] on the photo and video-sharing social networking service [[Instagram]]. The most-liked post on Instagram is a [[Instagram egg|photo of an egg]], which has been liked by over 54.3 million different accounts {{as of|2020|3|lc=on|df=}}.<ref name=\"Iasimone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8493277/egg-kylie-jenner-stormi-most-liked-instagram-photo-record|title=An Egg Dethrones Kylie Jenner & Travis Scott's Baby for Most Liked Instagram Photo Ever|first1=Ashley |last1=Tasimone|date=January 14, 2019|work=[[Billboard  (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 14, 2019}}</ref> The post is also the most-liked internet post of all time of any website.<ref name=\"Overall\">{{cite web|url=https://www.globalvillagespace.com/egg-becomes-most-liked-instagram-post/|title='Egg' becomes most-liked Instagram post|author=News Desk|date=May 13, 2019|website=Globalvillagespace.com|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=GWR>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/1/egg-photo-breaks-kylie-jenners-record-for-most-liked-image-on-instagram-554801|title=Egg photo breaks Kylie Jenner's record for most liked image on Instagram|first=Dan|last=Thorne|date=January 14, 2019|accessdate=January 15, 2019|work=[[Guinness World Records]]}}</ref> The like function has been removed in certain countries such as Canada and Australia in a trial to reduce the negative effects of \"competition\" on the platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mumbrella.com.au/instagram-removes-likes-for-australian-users-in-second-global-test-589324|title=Instagram removes likes for Australian users in second global test|last=Rigby|first=Brittney|date=2019-07-17|website=Mumbrella|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-19}}</ref>\n\n== Current record ==\n{{Main|Instagram egg}}\nOn January 4, 2019, the account @world_record_egg posted a photo of an egg with the specific purpose of surpassing the then most-liked Instagram post, a picture of [[Kylie Jenner]]'s daughter with 18.6 million likes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fox5sandiego.com/2019/01/11/an-egg-plans-to-dethrone-kylie-jenner-as-most-liked-instagram-photo/|title=An egg plans to dethrone Kylie Jenner as most liked Instagram post|first1=Malik |last1=Earnest|date=January 11, 2019|publisher=[[Fox 5 San Diego]]|accessdate=January 13, 2019}}</ref> The photo of the egg was originally taken by Serghei Platanov, who then posted it to [[Shutterstock]] on June 23, 2015, with the title \"eggs isolated on white background.\"<ref name=\"INSIDER\">{{cite web |last=Shamsian |first=Jacob |url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/world-record-egg-instagram-photographer-interview-meme-2019-1 |title=The guy who took a photo of an egg that broke Instagram's world record is shocked it became a meme: 'Egg is just an egg' |website=[[ThisIsInsider.com|Insider]] |date=January 16, 2018 |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2019, the egg post became the most-liked post on Instagram, to which the egg's account owner wrote \"This is madness. What a time to be alive.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/entertainment/2019/01/this-is-madness-picture-of-an-egg-beats-kylie-jenner-for-most-liked-instagram-post-ever.html|title='This is madness' - Picture of an egg beats Kylie Jenner for most liked Instagram post ever|author=Monika Barton|date=January 14, 2019|work=[[Newshub]]|accessdate=January 14, 2019}}</ref> In response to her record being surpassed, Jenner posted a video on Instagram of her cracking an egg open with the caption: \"Take that little egg.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/mbvd/egg-instagram-likes-beat-kylie-jenner|title=A Picture Of An Egg Beat Kylie Jenner For The Most Liked Instagram Of All Time|author=Michelle Broder Van Dyke|date=January 13, 2019|publisher=Buzzfeed News|accessdate=January 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=De|first=Elizabeth|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/instagram-account-egg-trying-break-kylie-jenner-most-liked-photo-record|title=This Instagram Account Is Trying to Break Kylie Jenner's Most-Liked Photo Record|date=January 13, 2019|accessdate=January 14, 2019|work=[[Teen Vogue]]}}</ref> The egg's original photographer was surprised by his photo's popularity, writing, \"Egg is just an egg.\"<ref name=\"INSIDER\"/>\n\nOn February 3, 2019, the creator of the @world_record_egg account was revealed to be Chris Godfrey, an advertising creative, and his friends CJ Brown and Alissa Khan-Whelan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/03/style/world-record-egg-instagram.html|title=Meet the Creator of the Egg That Broke Instagram|last=Bromwich|first=Jonah Engel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206103916/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/03/style/world-record-egg-instagram.html|archivedate=February 6, 2019|url-status=live|date=February 3, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=February 4, 2019|last2=Maheshwari|first2=Sapna|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Delahunty|first=Stephen|url=https://www.prweek.com/article/1672822/world-record-egg-team-launches-agency-backed-blurred-tin-man|title=World Record Egg team launches agency backed by Blurred and Tin Man|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 9, 2020|website=[[PRWeek]]}}</ref>\n\n==Top posts==\nThe following table lists the top 20 most-liked posts on Instagram.\n\nThree accounts have more than one of the most-liked posts in the top 20: [[Kylie Jenner]] has six, while [[Selena Gomez]] and [[Billie Eilish]] have two each.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Account name\n! Owner\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Post description\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Post\n! Likes<br/>(millions)\n! Date posted<br/>([[UTC]])\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n| @world_r